<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Russian Bank Hid Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Auditors have found that Russia's Central Bank  
kept its transactions with an offshore company off its accounting 
books and hid the profits it made on the nation's treasury-bill 
market, a newspaper reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The report comes just days after the International Monetary Fund  
approved a new, $4.5 billion loan program for Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	The news again raises questions of whether Russian finance  
officials have been straight with Western lenders, whether they are 
truly committed to reforming the battered economy and whether they 
have violated not only IMF guidelines, but also Russian law. 
</P>
<P>
	The auditors from PriceWaterhouseCoopers have been working on a  
contract for the IMF, which wanted to learn more about the Central 
Bank's relationship with the Financial Management Co., or FIMACO. 
</P>
<P>
	From 1993 through 1997, the bank secretly sent billions of  
dollars of its foreign reserves to the company, based in Britain's 
Channel Islands and is effectively under Central Bank control. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF had never been informed by Russian officials that they  
were moving funds, presumably including IMF money, out of the 
country. The bank's relationship with the offshore firm was 
publicly revealed earlier this year by Russia's embattled 
prosecutor-general, Yuri Skuratov. 
</P>
<P>
	Central Bank officials have repeatedly denied any wrongdoing.  
They said that the bank had channeled the money through FIMACO 
because it feared Russia could default on debts and international 
creditors would try to seize the nation's assets. 
</P>
<P>
	PriceWaterhouseCoopers found that the bank had kept double  
books, recording all its transactions with FIMACO outside the bank 
accounting registers, The Moscow Times reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Auditors also discovered that the bank had made profits by  
trading IMF loans and the nation's hard-currency reserves on the 
Russian short-term treasury bill market and neither recorded the 
profit nor shared it with the government, The Moscow Times said, 
citing the unpublished audit. 
</P>
<P>
	The Central Bank also lent $300 million of hard-currency  
reserves to commercial banks, the audit said, according to The 
Times. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
