<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 15:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jets Counting on QB Testaverde </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- Earlier this week, New York Jets  
quarterback Vinny Testaverde continuously stressed how excited he 
was about getting on the field for another season. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday morning, he showed how much.  
</P>
<P>
	After being swatted at by linebacker Olrick Johnson following a  
flea-flicker scramble, the Pro Bowler exchanged words with the 
rookie, flung the ball at him and then shoved the defender hard in 
the chest. 
</P>
<P>
	The team loved it.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's all right,'' coach Bill Parcells said later, smiling.  
</P>
<P>
	The Jets are counting on Testaverde's emotion again this season  
as they prepare for the defense of the franchise's first-ever AFC 
East championship. The veteran quarterback's remarkable resurgence 
last year, during which he went 12-1 as a regular-season starter, 
was the vital cog in a march to the conference title game against 
Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been thinking about it quite a lot,'' the 35-year-old  
quarterback said. ``I haven't had the greatest nights of sleep this 
past week. I'm ready to get this started. It's my 13th camp, and 
I'm a little surprised by just how ready and how hungry I am for 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	En route to his second Pro Bowl selection in the past three  
seasons, Testaverde posted one of the best statistical seasons in 
league history, throwing 29 touchdowns compared to only seven 
interceptions. In his inaugural campaign with the Jets after being 
waived by the Baltimore Ravens, the former University of Miami 
standout completed 259 of 421 passes for 3,256 yards and an 
AFC-best 101.6 passer rating. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Testaverde finds himself battling the doubts of some who  
recall his erratic, interception-riddled seasons with the woeful 
Tampa Bay Buccaneers from 1987-92. He also played for the Cleveland 
Browns from 1993-95 under current Jets assistant Bill Belichick. 
</P>
<P>
	``One or two games, maybe that's a fluke,'' Testaverde said.  
``To do it week in, week out, I don't think that's a fluke. That's 
hard work and dedication.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets agree. During the offseason, Testaverde signed a  
three-year, $19.5 million contract that includes options that may 
eventually pay him $27 million over seven seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he'll be better,'' receiver Wayne Chrebet said. ``What  
he did last year, he did in 12 games. Imagine what he can do in 16 
games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added wideout Keyshawn Johnson, ``What Vinny did last year is  
what high-level quarterbacks, guys like Steve Young and Mark 
Brunell, do every year. Vinny probably hasn't had the opportunity 
to do it. Now he has it, and I think he'll live up to the 
challenge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the first two days of the Jets' sweat-soaked training camp,  
Testaverde slipped easily into the leadership role. With former 
backup Glenn Foley, who begin last year as the starter, shipped off 
to Seattle, Testaverde is the clear No. 1 -- and needed little time 
to let Olrick Johnson know it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just a hot day,'' Testaverde said. ``I was frustrated  
because practice wasn't going so well. I lost my cool for a minute. 
Offensively, we didn't have our best day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, trying to break in among a talent-rich linebacking  
corps, got the message. 
</P>
<P>
	``Vinny came up to me later in the locker room and said, `Hold  
your head up,''' the rookie said. ``He said, `We're teammates. You 
protect me, too.' 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't want me touching Vinny,'' Johnson added. ``Vinny's  
a vital part of this team. It wasn't a hard hit, but I touched him. 
Vinny doesn't want his hands messed with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither do the Jets.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
