<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Arrested in Adoption Scam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A 21-year-old woman more than eight months  
pregnant was arrested and charged with fraud for allegedly 
promising her unborn child to seven would-be adoptive mothers for 
$16,000 each. 
</P>
<P>
	Kimberly Ussery, 21, pleaded innocent Friday and was held in  
lieu of $10,000 bail. Her three children were placed in the care of 
a friend. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was devastating. I can't think of a more personal  
affront,'' said Sylvia, one of the women Ussery allegedly told had 
been chosen to be the adoptive mother. She did not want her full 
name or her husband's name made public. 
</P>
<P>
	The 41-year-old woman from West Los Angeles resident and her  
husband signed papers for the child and paid Ussery and her 
boyfriend David Roth $1,250 a month for medical expenses and rent. 
</P>
<P>
	Sylvia became suspicious when Ussery wouldn't see a doctor. Her  
lawyer made some inquiries in the small circle of adoption 
attorneys and the scam was exposed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The saddest thing about it is it traffics in human emotions,''  
said Jane Gorman, an adoption lawyer in Orange County and San 
Francisco. ``Adoption for almost everybody is the end of the line 
of an almost desperate need to have a family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ussery allegedly also promised her baby to five other couples  
and a single mother, all of them who paid an estimated $16,000. 
</P>
<P>
	It had not been determined Saturday if the 21-year-old Roth, who  
was arrested earlier this week on an undisclosed parole violation, 
would face charges. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
