<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eagles, McNabb Agree to 7-Year Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- If Donovan McNabb's first week in the NFL is  
any indication, he's in for quite a ride. 
</P>
<P>
	McNabb and the Philadelphia Eagles agreed to a seven-year  
contract worth as much as $54 million with incentives Friday night, 
ending contentious negotiations that were marred by racial 
accusations by his agent. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement ended a tumultuous week that included missed  
practices, a damaging controversy and an ill-fated flight that 
forced the No. 2 draft pick to sit in a plane for three hours while 
waiting to fly to Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	No wonder McNabb's face bore an expression of relief,  
bewilderment and exasperation when he walked into Veterans Stadium 
-- his new home -- after midnight this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm excited that it's done,'' McNabb said. ``It's a dream come  
true to finally be a part of an organization which I've dreamed 
about playing in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Agent Fletcher Smith, whose comments about race playing a role  
stalled the negotiations, said the deal does not include voidable 
years like deals signed by top quarterbacks Tim Couch, Peyton 
Manning and Ryan Leaf. 
</P>
<P>
	It includes an $11.3 million signing bonus and incentive clauses  
that would trigger higher salaries in the final three years of the 
deal -- a similar structure to the one running back Ricky Williams 
got from New Orleans. 
</P>
<P>
	The bottom line: While McNabb's total package could be worth  
more than Couch's $48 million, seven-year deal, it guarantees 
nothing more than a minimum salary beyond the fourth year if McNabb 
doesn't play in the first three. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're happy with the deal,'' Smith said. ``It's an attractive  
package.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McNabb missed his fifth day of practice Friday and second day of  
full-squad workouts. The first-round draft choice is slated to back 
up starting quarterback Doug Pederson for the Eagles, who were 3-13 
last season. 
</P>
<P>
	McNabb was to report to training camp at Lehigh University this  
morning, but didn't know if he'd participate in workouts. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's something we'll talk about,'' McNabb said. ``I will be  
at practice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was a long, exhausting day for McNabb, who flew to Atlanta  
for a family reunion, only to learn that his contract was close to 
being finalized. His return flight was delayed three hours before 
it finally took off. 
</P>
<P>
	McNabb said he hoped his holdout would not tarnish his image.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think I just have to be me,'' he said. ``If I go in and  
perform the way coach Andy Reid and the rest of the staff want, I 
won't have to worry about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Reid stressed the importance of McNabb getting his  
contract resolved and reporting to camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every day, every practice, every rep he is missing, you can't  
get those back,'' Reid said. ``There's no price that you can put on 
those. Donovan needs to be here, and we want him here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiations ceased for two days this week after Smith's  
comments about race playing a role in the talks aired on a cable 
television show. Smith cited white quarterbacks who got voidable 
contracts and a black quarterback, Steve McNair, who didn't. 
</P>
<P>
	But the talks were salvaged when Smith, who is based in Chicago  
and has dealings with former NBA superstar Michael Jordan, flew to 
Philadelphia on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We felt it would be more constructive if we worked face to  
face, rather than on the phone where there can be distractions,'' 
Banner said. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Banner acknowledged that the controversy affected the  
negotiations, both sides said they thought it was over. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given that the statement came out of my mouth, I never really  
felt that race was an issue to begin with,'' Smith said. ``It 
didn't interfere with the discussions, especially over the past two 
days.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said the contract includes 8-10 incentives. If any  
incentive is reached in any of the first three seasons, the 
escalated salaries in the final three years kick in. He named three 
of the incentives: 1,601 passing yards, 30 touchdowns and a 100 
quarterback rating. 
</P>
<P>
	If the escalators kick in, Smith said McNabb's salary would be  
``about 5 percent more'' than Couch's in the final three seasons. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Bills    	
</P>
<P>
	Andre Reed, who threatened to retire if Buffalo didn't pay him  
more, is on his way to training camp with a possible agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed reportedly agreed to a one-year extension through the 2001  
season. General manager John Butler confirmed Reed would be in 
camp, but would not say if there is an agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed, the Bills' leading career receiver, plans to report  
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Packers    	
</P>
<P>
	Green Bay quarterback Brett Favre and wide receiver Antonio  
Freeman missed the first day of camp for veterans. 
</P>
<P>
	Favre is with his wife and newborn daughter, but was expected to  
join the team today. 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman, an unrestricted free agent before the Packers  
designated him their franchise player, is still working out terms 
of a new contract. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Patriots    	
</P>
<P>
	New England agreed to contracts with their remaining two draft  
picks, first-rounders Damien Woody and Andy Katzenmoyer. 
</P>
<P>
	Woody, taken with the 17th pick of the draft, agreed to a  
contract estimated at $1.25 million a year for five years with a 
$3.85 million signing bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	That left the Patriots under the salary cap by $835,000 a year,  
but there was no confirmation that Katzenmoyer, the Ohio State 
linebacker chosen with the 28th pick, received that as part of a 
four-year deal. 
</P>
<P>
                            *Buccaneers    	
</P>
<P>
	Tampa Bay's Chidi Ahanotu became one of the NFL's highest-paid  
defensive ends when he signed a six-year contract worth about $5 
million per season. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal included a signing bonus of more than $5 million.  
</P>
<P>
                             *Vikings    	
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota signed quarterback Daunte Culpepper, the team's  
first-round draft choice out of Central Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Culpepper, expected to back up Randall Cunningham, will join his  
new teammates at Vikings training camp in Mankato, Minn., next 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of his contract were not released, but WCCO-TV reported  
Culpepper signed a five-year contract worth about $2 million a year 
with a $5 million signing bonus. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Cowboys    	
</P>
<P>
	Dallas right guard Mike Kiselak, playing with the first team  
because of two other injuries, seriously damaged his left knee and 
defensive end Kavika Pittman broke several small bones in his right 
hand. 
</P>
<P>
	An MRI was inconclusive, and Kiselak is scheduled to undergo  
arthroscopic surgery Tuesday in Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	Pittman should be able to practice with a cast in 2-4 weeks.  
</P>
<P>
                             *Steelers    	
</P>
<P>
	Hours after offensive tackle Jamain Stephens couldn't complete a  
series of 40-yard runs on a 94-degree day, Pittsburgh cut the 1996 
first-round draft choice, who started 10 games at right tackle last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Steelers also got a jolt when Jerome Bettis, who has rushed  
for more than 1,000 yards in each of the last three seasons, 
reported to camp with an undisclosed left knee injury. He was 
injured 10 days ago while working with track coach Bob Kersee in 
St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Bettis is expected to be ready for the Sept. 12 opener against  
Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
                            *Cardinals    	
</P>
<P>
	Arizona cut tight end Chris Gedney, who underwent surgery to  
remove his colon July 4. 
</P>
<P>
	Gedney said he was shocked by the team's move because he was  
counting on the team's support as he underwent further surgery and 
mounted a comeback. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardinals general manager Bob Ferguson said Gedney, the leading  
pass catcher among Cardinals tight ends the last two seasons, was 
waived because he failed his physical. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Dolphins    	
</P>
<P>
	A contract stalemate kept Miami tackle Richmond Webb from  
reporting to training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Webb, a seven-time Pro Bowl selection, is unsigned and  
negotiating a long-term deal. He declined a one-year tender of 
$3.369 million when the Dolphins designated him their franchise 
player in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Webb, 32, has been a starting tackle since his rookie season in  
1990. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Seahawks    	
</P>
<P>
	The day after rookies and a few veterans showed up to camp, the  
remaining members of the Seattle Seahawks reported -- with the 
exception of wide receiver Joey Galloway and rookie defensive 
lineman Lamar King. 
</P>
<P>
	Galloway is seeking a sizable raise from the $1.6 million he is  
