<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 11:11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pan Am Games Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- It was no time to be sick.  
</P>
<P>
	Chris Humbert's ear was so infected when the Pan American Games  
water polo competition began, he missed the first two matches in 
the Olympic qualifying tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Tired, his head aching, his chest congested, his ear shut,  
Humbert and several ailing teammates set up a sick bay where they 
rested between matches. Their bodies were suffering, but their game 
didn't. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-7 Humbert scored five goals Friday night as the  
United States beat Cuba 11-7 to claim the gold medal and earn a 
trip to the Sydney Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I came to the pool and my temperature was 101,'' Humbert said.  
``This week hasn't been a lot of fun. We had to quarantine all the 
sick guys. We've come through some adversity, and this feels 
good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Humbert's offense was a big part of the Americans' commanding  
victory over a Cuban team they beat just 6-4 when their lanky 
two-meter man couldn't play early in the tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Also sparking the United States was the defense and  
length-of-the-pool passing of goalie Daniel Hackett. 
</P>
<P>
	Christopher Oeding and Humbert got behind the Cuban defense and  
took long passes from Hackett for easy scores within 40 seconds of 
one another to open the second period and make it 4-1. The United 
States led 6-2 at the half and 10-3 after three periods, using 
their superior swimming ability and strength. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think I could throw one any better than the one to  
Chris,'' Hackett said. ``You're always confident he will finish any 
shot. 
</P>
<P>
	``This game was just a test because half our guys have the flu,  
including Chris. He couldn't even practice all week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. women's basketball team looked like a group that hasn't  
spent much time together, which is precisely the case, but still 
won its opener. 
</P>
<P>
	Reserves Michelle Marciniak and Amy Herrig gave Team USA the  
spark it needed to get past Argentina 63-55. Marciniak got the 
Americans going with two length-of-the-court drives for baskets, 
and Herrig had 15 points and nine rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States isn't using a top team in the Pan Am Games,  
and the players didn't start practicing until July 17. The lack of 
time together was evident as coach Nell Fortner substituted 
constantly looking for the right combination. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can practice all you want, but the real experience comes  
from playing games with refs, scorekeepers, fans and everything 
else,'' Marciniak said. ``There's no substitute for that. We 
learned more tonight than from all the practices going against each 
other.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. men open tonight against Cuba.  
</P>
<P>
	U.S. pitcher Michele Smith almost duplicated teammate Danielle  
Henderson's perfect game in Thursday's softball opener. Smith was 
perfect through six innings before yielding a hit in a 5-0 victory 
over Netherlands Antilles. 
</P>
<P>
	Cubans dominated the final night of track and field by winning  
five of the 10 events, including a fourth straight Pan Ams gold by 
high jumper Javier Sotomayor. Sotomayor took only two jumps, 
clearing 7 feet, 2 1/2 inches and 7-6 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	Also winning for Cuba was Anier Garcia, who ran the 110-meter  
hurdles in 13.17 seconds to break one of the meet's oldest records, 
13.20 by Renaldo Nehemiah in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuba finished track and field with 11 gold medals. That was one  
more than the United States, which was shut out in the relays and 
failed to win a gold Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is tremendous,'' said Jose Salmeron, spokesman for the  
Cuban team. ``We did it with spectacular marks and in spite of not 
having as many key athletes as in the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans also suffered disappointments in field hockey and  
volleyball. 
</P>
<P>
	Any chances for the United States to qualify for the Olympics in  
men's field hockey ended with a 4-1 loss to Argentina. The men's 
volleyball team fell out of medal contention when it lost to 
Venezuela 25-21, 28-26, 25-22. 
</P>
<P>
	For the second time in the games, the U.S. women's volleyball  
team was swept by Cuba, but the Americans could still win the 
bronze. 
</P>
<P>
	Things went better for the United States in the ring on the  
opening night of boxing. Flyweight Jose Navarro of Los Angeles beat 
Carlos Valcarcel of Puerto Rico in the new format of four 
two-minute rounds. Welterweight LeChaunce Shepherd of Milwaukee, 
Wis., stopped Nicaragua's Isaac Caballero in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	Americans won the premier rowing event, the men's eight with  
cox. The U.S. team took control at 500 meters and won by nearly 
three seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Off the field, an official from the International Baseball  
Association told several reporters that two Cuban baseball players 
had defected. But Canadian immigration officials and sources close 
to the Cuban team said the official was wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the players mentioned by IBA delegate Enzo Gesu was  
pitcher Jose Ibar. But he was in the dugout today when Cuba 
advanced to the semifinals by beating the Dominican Republic 3-1. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
