<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heavyweight Contender Back to Jail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- A top heavyweight boxing contender accused of  
raping a woman in his hotel room had to be removed from a courtroom 
following an outburst. 
</P>
<P>
	Ike Ibeabuchi, 26, known as ``The President'' in the ring, was  
scheduled to be arraigned Friday but was removed from court after 
he became upset that the prosecution wanted bail set at $5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Ibeabuchi is to return to court for arraignment on Aug. 6. He  
will continue to be held without bail in the Clark County Detention 
Center pending the court appearance. 
</P>
<P>
	Ibeabuchi, undefeated at 20-0 with 15 knockouts and ranked No. 2  
by the IBF, is charged with sexual assault, attempted sexual 
assault, kidnapping and battery with intent to commit sexual 
assault. 
</P>
<P>
	All the charges stem from an incident at The Mirage on July 22  
when a 21-year-old entertainer told police she was raped by the 
boxer after being called to his suite. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 22:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BoSox Acquire Tigers' Florie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The Boston Red Sox acquired right-hander Bryce  
Florie from the Detroit Tigers on Saturday night for minor league 
left-hander Mike Maroth in the final deal before baseball's 
midnight trade deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	Florie, 29, was 2-1 with a 4.56 ERA for the Tigers in three  
starts and 24 relief appearances with a 4.62 ERA, striking out 40 
in 51 1-3 innings. He pitched two-thirds of an inning Saturday in 
Detroit's 7-6 loss at Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	Florie has a 17-19 career record with a 4.28 ERA, pitching for  
San Diego, Milwaukee and Detroit. He has 329 career strikeouts in 
405 2-3 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Maroth, 22, was Boston's third pick in the 1998 amateur draft.  
He is 10-6 in 18 starts and one relief appearance this season at 
Sarasota of the Class-A Florida State League, allowing 116 hits in 
104 1-3 innings. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 10:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pan Am Games Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- It was no time to be sick.  
</P>
<P>
	Chris Humbert's ear was so infected when the Pan American Games  
water polo competition began, he missed the first two matches in 
the Olympic qualifying tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Tired, his head aching, his chest congested, his ear shut,  
Humbert and several ailing teammates set up a sick bay where they 
rested between matches. Their bodies were suffering, but their game 
didn't. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-7 Humbert scored five goals Friday night as the  
United States beat Cuba 11-7 to claim the gold medal and earn a 
trip to the Sydney Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I came to the pool and my temperature was 101,'' Humbert said.  
``This week hasn't been a lot of fun. We had to quarantine all the 
sick guys. We've come through some adversity, and this feels 
good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Humbert's offense was a big part of the Americans' commanding  
victory over a Cuban team they beat just 6-4 when their lanky 
two-meter man couldn't play early in the tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Also sparking the United States was the defense and  
length-of-the-pool passing of goalie Daniel Hackett. 
</P>
<P>
	Christopher Oeding and Humbert got behind the Cuban defense and  
took long passes from Hackett for easy scores within 40 seconds of 
one another to open the second period and make it 4-1. The United 
States led 6-2 at the half and 10-3 after three periods, using 
their superior swimming ability and strength. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think I could throw one any better than the one to  
Chris,'' Hackett said. ``You're always confident he will finish any 
shot. 
</P>
<P>
	``This game was just a test because half our guys have the flu,  
including Chris. He couldn't even practice all week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. women's basketball team looked like a group that hasn't  
spent much time together, which is precisely the case, but still 
won its opener. 
</P>
<P>
	Reserves Michelle Marciniak and Amy Herrig gave Team USA the  
spark it needed to get past Argentina 63-55. Marciniak got the 
Americans going with two length-of-the-court drives for baskets, 
and Herrig had 15 points and nine rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States isn't using a top team in the Pan Am Games,  
and the players didn't start practicing until July 17. The lack of 
time together was evident as coach Nell Fortner substituted 
constantly looking for the right combination. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can practice all you want, but the real experience comes  
from playing games with refs, scorekeepers, fans and everything 
else,'' Marciniak said. ``There's no substitute for that. We 
learned more tonight than from all the practices going against each 
other.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. men open tonight against Cuba.  
</P>
<P>
	U.S. pitcher Michele Smith almost duplicated teammate Danielle  
Henderson's perfect game in Thursday's softball opener. Smith was 
perfect through six innings before yielding a hit in a 5-0 victory 
over Netherlands Antilles. 
</P>
<P>
	Cubans dominated the final night of track and field by winning  
five of the 10 events, including a fourth straight Pan Ams gold by 
high jumper Javier Sotomayor. Sotomayor took only two jumps, 
clearing 7 feet, 2 1/2 inches and 7-6 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	Also winning for Cuba was Anier Garcia, who ran the 110-meter  
hurdles in 13.17 seconds to break one of the meet's oldest records, 
13.20 by Renaldo Nehemiah in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuba finished track and field with 11 gold medals. That was one  
more than the United States, which was shut out in the relays and 
failed to win a gold Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is tremendous,'' said Jose Salmeron, spokesman for the  
Cuban team. ``We did it with spectacular marks and in spite of not 
having as many key athletes as in the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans also suffered disappointments in field hockey and  
volleyball. 
</P>
<P>
	Any chances for the United States to qualify for the Olympics in  
men's field hockey ended with a 4-1 loss to Argentina. The men's 
volleyball team fell out of medal contention when it lost to 
Venezuela 25-21, 28-26, 25-22. 
</P>
<P>
	For the second time in the games, the U.S. women's volleyball  
team was swept by Cuba, but the Americans could still win the 
bronze. 
</P>
<P>
	Things went better for the United States in the ring on the  
opening night of boxing. Flyweight Jose Navarro of Los Angeles beat 
Carlos Valcarcel of Puerto Rico in the new format of four 
two-minute rounds. Welterweight LeChaunce Shepherd of Milwaukee, 
Wis., stopped Nicaragua's Isaac Caballero in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	Americans won the premier rowing event, the men's eight with  
cox. The U.S. team took control at 500 meters and won by nearly 
three seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Off the field, an official from the International Baseball  
Association told several reporters that two Cuban baseball players 
had defected. But Canadian immigration officials and sources close 
to the Cuban team said the official was wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the players mentioned by IBA delegate Enzo Gesu was  
pitcher Jose Ibar. But he was in the dugout today when Cuba 
advanced to the semifinals by beating the Dominican Republic 3-1. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 11:50:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Soccer Gets Another Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- What the Women's World Cup started in  
the United States, those at the Pan American Games hope to push a 
little more down the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Less than three weeks after the second Women's Football  
Symposium in Los Angeles finished with a call for more women's 
age-limited tournaments -- and specifically a world championship -- 
five under-20 national teams have gathered in Winnipeg to compete 
for only the second confederation-sanctioned youth crown offered. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very positive to have this competition immediately after  
the World Cup,'' said Mexican coach Leonardo Cuellar, who also 
coached Mexico's women's team at USA '99 and brought five members 
of that squad to Winnipeg. ``The TV is here. This is being shown in 
Mexico. It is giving exposure to what needs to be done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the Pan Ams starting only 13 days after the Women's World  
Cup final, CONCACAF, which was given virtual control of the event, 
decided to make it an under-20 competition. 
</P>
<P>
	That limited the number of countries participating because most  
nations barely field a senior national team, let alone an underage 
side. 
</P>
<P>
	On top of that, the United States sent essentially its under-18  
team because of its commitment to the Nordic Cup, an annual 
invitational that for a little less than a decade has stood as a de 
facto youth championship. 
</P>
<P>
	That eight-team event is set for Iceland on Aug. 2-8.  
</P>
<P>
	``I hope it's obvious to the rest of the world that we're being  
very aggressive in an area of the game that needs promotion,'' 
CONCACAF deputy general secretary Ted Howard said. ``We also know 
we need to promote it in our member nations where it may not be the 
most accepted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only last week, CONCACAF joined Asia, Africa, Europe and South  
America in announcing that next year it will stage a continental 
championship for women. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Pan Ams is only the second non-exhibition title for  
girls, following in the path of last year's European under-18 
championship. 
</P>
<P>
	And it's clear those associated with the women's programs are  
thrilled. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is tremendous for our younger players,'' said Canada  
coach Neil Turnbull, who like Cuellar coached his country's senior 
team at the Women's World Cup. ``One thing we lack is World 
Cup-level experience. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I want to bring a new girl into the national team, her  
first cap might be against the United States -- the best team in the 
world. Her second might be against China. (The Pan Ams) is 
international soccer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Los Angeles two days before the World Cup final, Per Ravn  
Omdal of Norway, chairman of FIFA's Committee for Women's Football, 
said the creation of more women's championships, and specifically 
youth events, would spur confederations and national associations 
into creating and supporting women's teams. 
</P>
<P>
	But there is also the concern youth tournaments will widen the  
gap between the haves and have nots of women's soccer. The belief 
is that already developed powers will further improve, while others 
will become discouraged from getting pounded. 
</P>
<P>
	Clearly at the Pan Ams, the United States, Canada and Mexico are  
in one tier, with Costa Rica and Trinidad and Tobago in another. 
</P>
<P>
	In four games, the Americans and Canadians routed Costa Rica and  
Trinidad by a combined score of 25-2. The scores were similar to 
some seen during World Cup qualifying. 
</P>
<P>
	``The talent pool (at the youth level), despite gains, is not  
that big,'' 1999 Women's World Cup spokesman Aaron Heifetz said 
from his office in Los Angeles. ``It's much tougher for developing 
nations to put together teams.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But, even for those that get pummeled, some see positives.  
</P>
<P>
	``It all depends on what you do with it, how you view it,'' said  
U.S. coach Jay Hoffman, who also used to coach the U.S. men's 
under-20 team. ``It depends on what you do as a follow-up. If 
somebody just brought a team here, but doesn't do anything until a 
year from now ... 
</P>
<P>
	``If you bring a team in here, and next month you do a little  
more, and then a little more ... I assume all countries here are 
attempting to improve. If that's the case, it will only help sport, 
only help the confederation.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 18:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies, Mets Trade Four Players </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The Rockies and Mets swapped center fielders  
and left-handed relievers Saturday night, with Darryl Hamilton and 
Chuck McElroy going to New York and Colorado getting Brian McRae 
and Rigo Beltran. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rockies also got minor league outfielder Thomas Johnson in  
the deal, announced about 20 minutes before the Rockies played the 
Cardinals and about four hours ahead of the midnight EDT trading 
deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton, batting .303 with four homers and 24 RBIs, had been in  
the Rockies lineup and hitting second against the St. Louis 
Cardinals. He and McElroy, 3-1 with a 6.20 ERA, were called off the 
field during batting practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Both planned to join the Mets on Sunday in Chicago and were  
happy about landing with a contending team. Todd Helton was 
inserted in the No. 2 slot and played first base, and hit a two-run 
homer in the third. Jeff Barry played center field and batted 
sixth. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a little surprised, but a little relieved that it's  
over,'' Hamilton said. ``I gained about 25 games in a five-minute 
phone call. That makes it a little more interesting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McElroy, who has a 3.64 career ERA, also was looking forward to  
a fresh start. 
</P>
<P>
	``The adrenaline is going now,'' McElroy said. ``I didn't have  
the kind of year I wanted to here, so I'm looking forward to having 
some fun over there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McRae, 31, has been a disappointment with the Mets, batting .221  
with eight homers and 36 RBIs and stealing only two bases in eight 
attempts. He has been with the Mets about two years after coming 
from the Chicago Cubs on Aug. 8, 1997, in a deal that involved 
Lance Johnson and Mark Clark. 
</P>
<P>
	Beltran, 29, was optioned to Triple-A Norfolk July 25.  
</P>
<P>
	The deal apparently was attractive from a financial standpoint  
to the Rockies. Hamilton and McElroy are in the first year of 
three-year contracts, while McRae is in the final year of his 
contract and Beltran is not arbitration-eligible. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets figured Hamilton was a nice upgrade in center field.  
</P>
<P>
	``Darryl's hitting over .300 right now and we think he's going  
to improve us offensively and defensively,'' general manager Steve 
Phillips said. ``Unfortunately, Brian couldn't get anything going 
this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McElroy waived a no-trade clause to New York.  
</P>
<P>
	``When this time comes and teams need left-handed pitchers, you  
expect something,'' McElroy said. ``I thought it was going to be 
Houston or the Yankees or maybe San Diego.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this season, McRae had questioned manager Bobby  
Valentine's lineups. Shortly thereafter, the Mets put McRae and 
Bobby Bonilla on irrevocable waivers, though no team claimed them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately, Brian couldn't get anything going this year,''  
Phillips said. 
</P>
<P>
	McRae left Wrigley Field shortly after a 17-10 loss to the Cubs  
and was unavailable for comment. He did not play in the game. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
