<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 16:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chargers Safety Perry Retires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- San Diego Chargers free safety Darren Perry  
retired Saturday, the day before the team flew to Australia for its 
exhibition opener. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Mike Riley said the seven-year veteran knocked on his door  
at 7:30 a.m. and told him he was retiring due to an ailment in his 
right shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was shocking to everybody,'' Riley said. ``He had had some  
problems with nerves in his shoulder, stingers, the last couple of 
years. They made him uncomfortable enough for him to say he can't 
play the game either the way he wants to, or we would want him to 
physically.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said general manager Bobby Beathard: ``I had no clue.''  
</P>
<P>
	Perry joined the Chargers as an unrestricted free agent from  
Pittsburgh, signing a $3.25 million, two-year contract 
</P>
<P>
	A starter since being taken by the Steelers in the eighth round  
of the 1992 draft, Perry started all 110 games he played in and had 
32 interceptions. He missed two starts last year, including the 
season finale with a neck injury. 
</P>
<P>
	The free safety job likely will revert to Michael Dumas, San  
Diego's starter for all of 1997 and the first three games of 1998 
before he suffered a knee injury in practice and underwent surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chargers leave Sunday for Sydney, where they'll play the  
Denver Broncos next Saturday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
