<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Red Bow Tie Wins in Breeder's Crown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Red Bow Tie won his second straight  
Breeders Crown Open Pace on Saturday, edging Color Me Best by a 
neck and becoming the richest gelding in harness racing history. 
</P>
<P>
	Red Bow Tie's stirring victory in the $380,000 race came after  
beating back a neck-and-neck challenge from Color Me Best coming 
down the stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	The 5-year old son of Raging Glory, trained by Marty Gelrod and  
driven by Luc Ouelette, took the lead before the half post and, 
despite constant pressure from Color Me Best, refused to be denied. 
He covered the mile in 1:50 and earned $180,000, increasing his 
career earnings to $2,096,163. Red Bow Tie who was sent off at 2-1 
odds and paid $4.80. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, lightly raced Super Grit came roaring down the  
stretch to edge Fern by 2 1/2 lengths in the $580,000 Breeders Crown 
Trot in a career-best 1:53 1-5. 
</P>
<P>
	Super Grit, trained by Carl Conte Jr. and driven by Ron Pierce,  
was making just his fourth and fifth starts of the season and 
notched his second win by coming off the pace to pass the tiring 
Fern down the stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	Fern, who had won the Breeders Crown elimination three races  
earlier, was unable to hold off Super Grit in the final strides 
after beating back an earlier challenge from Mister Goal. 
</P>
<P>
	Super Grit, who has been raced little in the past year due to  
soundness problems, finished third in the elimination but had 
plenty left for his stretch drive in the final. The $290,000 
winner's purse more than doubled his winnings for the past two 
years and increased the 6-year old son of Supergill's career 
earnings to $973,768. 
</P>
<P>
	In the $282,500 Breeders Crown Open Pace for Mares, 50-1 long  
shot Shore By Five won with a stunning stretch drive that allowed 
her to overtake 6-5 favorite Sanabelle Island and hold off 
fast-closing Extreme Velocity to win by a nose in 1:50 4-5. 
</P>
<P>
	Shore By Five, fourth at the top of the stretch, put on a  
surprising burst of speed to pass tiring Sanabelle Island, who led 
most of the race. The Canadian-based mare had to hold off a late 
challenge from Extreme Velocity to win by a nose. Shore by Five's 
payoff of $108.20 was the third-largest in Breders Crown history. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm as shocked and surprised as anyone,'' Shore By Five's  
trainer, Bob McIntosh, said. ``I considered her a long shot who 
could maybe finish fourth or fifth. We were just hoping to get back 
our entry fee. But Daniel (Dube) gave her a great drive, the big 
fractions worked in her favor and she showed a lot of character 
down the stretch.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
