<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vikings Use Loss To Motivate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANKATO, Minn. (AP) -- When the Minnesota Vikings convene Sunday  
for training camp, last season's loss to Atlanta in the NFC 
championship game will serve as motivation for some players. 
</P>
<P>
	The Falcons' 30-27 overtime victory on Jan. 17 prevented the  
Vikings from going to the Super Bowl for the first time since 1977. 
The Vikings open the regular season on Sept. 12 against the Falcons 
in the Georgia Dome -- the site of this season's Super Bowl on Jan. 
30. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll use it,'' defensive tackle John Randle said. ``If  
anything, it's going to teach us about what it takes. Because this 
team had some young guys who really weren't sure what it was all 
about to get to the championship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For others, last year's loss has already been forgotten.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think our team won't use the Atlanta game at all,'' coach  
Dennis Green said. ``I think our team will forget about last year 
and move forward to this year. The bottom line is you're not owed 
anything. We're not motivated by a loss. We're motivated by what's 
ahead of us, not what's behind us. We don't have to worry about 
last year. That's not going to help us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vikings defensive line coach Andre Patterson said the team seems  
focused on this season, not the disappointing end to last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're a bunch of hungry guys,'' Patterson said. ``They don't  
seem like a group that has the hurt and pain still lingering from 
that Atlanta game. I don't think there's any pity or feeling sorry 
for themselves. They have a lot of pride in what they did 
accomplish. Now it's time for us to work hard again and try to take 
it to that next level.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
