<HEADLINE> First Lady: Husband Has 'Weakness' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, answering  
questions about her husband's affair with former White House intern 
Monica Lewinsky and the scandal that followed, said his actions 
were ``a sin of weakness, not a sin of malice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton defended President Clinton as ``a very, very good  
man'' but said, ``Yes, he has weaknesses, yes he needs to be more 
responsible, more disciplined,'' she told ``Talk'' magazine, 
according to a news release from the magazine Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine, edited by former New Yorker editor Tina Brown,  
debuts on newstands Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Questioned about the president's infidelity, Mrs. Clinton said,  
``I thought this was resolved ten years ago. ... I thought he had 
conquered it,'' according to a magazine press release. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton also said her husband was scarred by abuse as a  
small child, but the press release did not provide details. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton also talked about her moves toward a run for a U.S.  
Senate seat in New York. ``Now for the first time I am making my 
own decisions. I can feel the difference. It is a great relief.'' 
  	   	
</P>
