<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Beats US Women in Basketball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Emerging from the dressing room after  
a drubbing by Cuba, the first thing Nell Fortner did was apologize. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sorry you had to sit through that,'' the U.S. women's  
basketball coach said while still managing a smile. ``I'm sorry I 
had to sit through it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cuba handed the United States its worst loss ever in women's  
basketball at the Pan American Games, rolling past Fortner's team 
95-64 Saturday night. It also was the most points ever allowed by a 
U.S. women's team in Pan Ams play. 
</P>
<P>
	``I definitely wouldn't call that our A game,'' U.S. forward  
Lynn Pride said. ``Cuba is very good and very athletic. They 
brought their A game and we didn't respond.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United States and Cuba met in men's basketball later  
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cuban women overwhelmed the United States with their  
quickness, slashing drives to the basket and trapping zone defense. 
They jumped to a 14-3 lead in the first five minutes and the 
Americans never recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuba, which lost to Brazil in the first round, led 54-27 at  
halftime and easily topped the previous worst defeat of a U.S. team 
in Pan Ams play, 60-42 by Brazil in 1967. The most points the 
United States surrendered previously came in a 107-92 victory over 
Brazil in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I was more disappointed after our win last night than  
I am tonight,'' said Fortner, whose team opened with a sluggish 
63-55 victory over Argentina. ``I thought we were totally 
overmatched tonight. We played hard, but we couldn't get our shots 
to fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had some good looks early, but couldn't nail them. If we  
could have nailed some of them, it would have helped our confidence 
tremendously.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United States shot 27 percent in the first half (9-for-33)  
and 35 percent for the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuba, which has nine members of its 1996 Olympic team,  
constantly drove past the bewildered Americans for easy baskets and 
shot 61 percent. Of the Cubans' 32 baskets, 19 were layups or 
putbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were good, but we know we're a lot better defensive team  
than that,'' Pride said. ``We had a lot of breakdowns. We usually 
rely on our help, but it wasn't there tonight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pride, who'll be a senior at Kansas, led the Americans with 15  
points. Michelle Marciniak scored 12 and Itoro Umoh 10. Licet 
Castillo led Cuba with 17 points. She did not play in the second 
half. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
