<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schroeder Defends Austerity Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Determined to move his Social Democratic party to  
the political center, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder pledged in an 
interview released Saturday to stick to his austerity plans and 
announced measures aimed at bringing leftist critics in line. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with Der Spiegel newsmagazine, Schroeder cited  
polls showing public support for his 9-month-old government's 
efforts to balance the budget, yet ``uncertainty'' over whether he 
will be able to get the necessary cuts through parliament in the 
fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Schroeder accused old guard leftists of encouraging those doubts  
and hurting the government with constant carping over his plans to 
trim the welfare state and reduce business taxes, which he insists 
will encourage economic growth and help reduce the country's 10 
percent unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
	Union leaders and other leftists charge the austerity budget  
puts too much of the burden on the working-class and doesn't demand 
enough from industry and the rich. 
</P>
<P>
	But Schroeder said a balanced budget can be reached ``without  
economizing so much that the social welfare state breaks down. 
</P>
<P>
	``None of us want that, and none of us will do that,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Schroeder also said he planned to appoint a reformist ally,  
Transport Minister Franz Muentefering, to the task of lining up the 
party behind the government's course. 
</P>
<P>
	Schroeder took over as party chairman after Oskar Lafontaine,  
the left-wing's standard-bearer, quit in March, reportedly 
frustrated with Schroeder's more market-friendly approach. 
</P>
<P>
	The two have not talked since then, and Schroeder warned his  
former colleague, who is writing a book, not to ``throw stones at 
those doing the hard work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Muentefering, who ran last year's federal election campaign for  
the Social Democrats, is considered to have the backing as well of 
young party reformists, who recently accused party leaders of 
spending too much time on ``ideological navel-gazing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an open letter, the 13 Social Democratic lawmakers called on  
their party to back pragmatic reforms, such as flexible labor 
markets and clamps on state spending, laid out recently by 
Schroeder and British Prime Minister Tony Blair in a joint 
manifesto for modernizing the left. 
</P>
<P>
	But parliamentary president Wolfgang Thierse, one of the Social  
Democrats attacked in the letter, called on Schroeder not to stifle 
debate over the party's future. 
</P>
<P>
	``Criticism in a democracy is not insolent behavior,'' Focus  
newsmagazine quoted him as saying. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
