<HEADLINE> Ten Die in Michigan Plane Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COTTRELLVILLE TOWNSHIP, Mich. (AP) -- A plane carrying passengers  
on a weekend skydiving trip crashed early today, killing 10 people, 
state police said. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane, which took off from Marine City Airport, broke into  
several pieces after it crashed just prior to 9 a.m., officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	State police Trooper Raymond Volosky confirmed the crash later  
and said 10 were dead, but he would not confirm the total number of 
passengers aboard. A St. Clair County sheriff's dispatcher said 
early today that 10 people were aboard the craft. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials released no other details immediately.  
</P>
<P>
	Robert Franz, who lives nearby, said he heard the plane taking  
off -- and then he heard the engine go dead. A second or two later, 
he said, he heard a loud crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Franz says he grabbed his video camera and headed to the scene,  
about a half-mile away. He said the plane had crashed in an open 
field, and had broken into two sections. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials from the Federal Aviation Administration and the  
National Transportation Safety Board were en route to the scene. 
</P>
<P>
	Cottrellville Township is located about 40 miles north of  
Detroit. 
  	   	
</P>
