<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Mulls Plan To Cut Welfare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Speaker Dennis Hastert says he's  
seriously considering a plan that would take back billions of 
dollars given to the states to run their welfare programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans are searching for money to pay for a variety of  
programs. Despite projections of large budget surpluses, Congress 
must live within tight spending limits established in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying to balance the budget,'' Hastert, R-Ill., told  
reporters Friday. Still, he admitted the dicey nature of taking 
back money already promised: ``We have a contract with the states, 
an agreement with the states.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, federal spending on welfare went up when more  
people signed up for welfare and dropped when welfare rolls fell. 
In 1996, Congress agreed to give states $16.5 billion each year no 
matter how many people are on welfare. States took the financial 
risk if caseloads went up and they needed extra money to write more 
benefit checks. 
</P>
<P>
	As it turns out, welfare rolls have dropped further and faster  
than anyone predicted, to a 30-year low. As a result, states have 
more money to spend per person than ever before, and they have $4.2 
billion left unspent in their federal accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	That money has proven tempting to congressional budget writers,  
who are also considering cuts to child support and Medicaid 
funding. State governors, never happy about cuts in federal money, 
are lobbying heavily against each of the potential cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Republicans argue the states have plenty of money plus  
significant new power to run welfare and other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had the best relationship with the nation's governors  
that (Congress) has ever had,'' said Rep. John Boehner, R-Ohio. 
States should realize, he suggested, they can't always get their 
way. ``There's got to be some balance in this relationship. It 
can't be all one way. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is one of the tough decisions we have to make,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Other GOP leaders have argued against taking back the money, an  
idea that periodically comes up. 
</P>
<P>
	``We made a deal,'' House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill  
Archer, R-Texas, wrote to Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, 
R-Miss., in the spring. ``As state legislatures confront the 
toughest challenges of welfare reform, Congress is proposing to 
pull the rug from under them.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 08:30:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Social Security Surplus Untouchable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Just about drowned out by the partisan warfare  
in Congress over the Republicans' tax-cutting drive is one of the 
most dramatic and beneficial budget achievements in years: a 
bipartisan truce over two-thirds of the federal surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's dominant battle is over how to use $1 trillion in  
projected surpluses over the next decade. Republicans favor tax 
cuts and President Clinton and Democrats prefer domestic spending. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a little-heralded development, an additional $1.9  
trillion in anticipated surpluses expected from Social Security has 
become politically untouchable for both sides. Each party has 
pledged to leave the money alone, and can grab for it only at risk 
of being accused by opponents of stealing Social Security money. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they've trapped themselves,'' said Robert Bixby,  
policy director of the Concord Coalition, a bipartisan group that 
advocates budget frugality. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, the politicians have already nibbled at the Social Security  
money, using it, for instance, to pay for the bombing campaign 
against Yugoslavia. Yes, they undoubtedly will do so again, 
probably this fall when a likely agreement between Clinton and 
Republicans will result in billions more for schools, agriculture, 
defense and other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	And yes, 10-year projections are always shaky and actual  
surpluses could end up being far smaller than anticipated. 
</P>
<P>
	But neither side's grand budget plans envision using that  
enormous $1.9 trillion Social Security kitty for tax cuts or 
spending, a new and major development. 
</P>
<P>
	That means most of the money is likely to go to reduce the  
national debt. Economists from Federal Reserve Chairman Alan 
Greenspan on down say that is the best thing to do with it because 
reducing the debt lowers interest rates and energizes the economy 
in the long run. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if lawmakers dissipate the entire $1 trillion surplus from  
non-Social Security programs, ``we'd have still paid down a 
substantial portion of the debt and achieved something that was 
unthinkable two years ago,'' said Robert Reischauer, senior fellow 
at the Brookings Institution. 
</P>
<P>
	Until recent months, neither party hesitated to use Social  
Security surpluses to pay for tax or spending initiatives. 
</P>
<P>
	But that all changed last year, when Clinton -- looking to  
prevent Republicans from using the surpluses for a tax cut -- 
thought up his ``save Social Security first'' mantra. It was 
shorthand for not using the Social Security surpluses for tax cuts 
or spending, and it proved to have such undeniable political appeal 
that Republicans embraced it. 
</P>
<P>
	Then this year, something else happened. The surging economy has  
poured so much revenue into the federal government that projected 
surpluses have sprouted on the non-Social Security side of the 
budget, something unseen for decades. 
</P>
<P>
	That made the virtuous-sounding pledge to leave Social Security  
money alone painless as well because it turned out there was still 
$1 trillion in projected surpluses to play with. 
</P>
<P>
	``This couldn't have happened without a very rapid and  
unexpected improvement in the budget outlook,'' Reischauer said. 
</P>
<P>
	First Republicans, then Democrats have tried scoring political  
points by trumpeting the need for a so-called lock box. That is 
legislation that would allegedly make it harder for lawmakers to 
use the Social Security surpluses for anything but shoring up the 
program or reducing the national debt. 
</P>
<P>
	But politicians always find a way around such devices, and  
nothing has been enacted yet anyway. Yet, the political will to 
avoid angering senior citizens by being seen as raiding Social 
Security may suffice. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every politician in America has heard from senior citizens  
saying, 'Why are you robbing my Social Security,''' said Richard 
May, a former GOP House budget aide who is now a consultant in 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest question is what politicians will do if a severe  
recession or some other unforeseen event erases the projected 
surpluses. Will they then propose using Social Security funds for 
higher spending or tax cuts? 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they're out on that sand bar now, and if the tide  
comes in they're stuck,'' said Bixby. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Alan Fram covers Congress and the budget for The  
Associated Press. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
