<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 12:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Supports Background Checks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House has boosted the chances that  
Congress will approve legislation requiring background checks on 
all firearms sales at gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Six weeks after rejecting tougher gun control restrictions  
supported by the Senate, the House approved, 305-84, a nonbinding 
measure Friday endorsing background checks. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote came after House leaders named their participants in  
negotiations with the Senate to resolve differences between House 
and Senate bills toughening penalties against teen-age offenders. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure asks negotiators to write a compromise juvenile  
justice bill that would require background checks for all firearms 
sales at gun shows. Under current law, background checks are 
required only on sales by licensed dealers. 
</P>
<P>
	The resolution also calls for including measures to prevent  
violence in schools and ensuring that the legislation does not 
weaken existing gun regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	Although House negotiators are not required to follow those  
instructions, Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., the House Judiciary 
Committee's top Democrat, said the vote was a repudiation of the 
National Rifle Association, which has lobbied against new gun 
control laws. 
</P>
<P>
	``With today's vote, more than 300 of my colleagues finally  
joined the majority of the Senate in showing the courage to take on 
the NRA and enact tough bans on criminal purchases at gun shows, 
the biggest single loophole in our nation's gun safety laws,'' 
Conyers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote was particularly important, he said, because it came a  
day after a mass shooting in Atlanta. Investigators say Mark O. 
Barton shot nine people to death at two brokerage firms on Thursday 
after killing his wife and two children earlier in the week. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats said the tragedy should put more pressure on  
Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	``If this leadership doesn't act and doesn't pass commonsense  
gun legislation, they are going to have to explain to the American 
public why the NRA has more influence over them than all the 
mothers and fathers and children of this country,'' Rep. Nita 
Lowey, D-N.Y., said. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said provisions in the  
House bill that would toughen penalties against teen-age criminals 
would help reduce school violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``This legislation will not solve every problem, but it will  
take steps to make our schools safer,'' he said in a statement. ``I 
hope our Democrat colleagues put the good of the country in front 
of partisanship as we proceed with this issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some Democrats said they were pleased to see action on  
legislation that could result in tighter restrictions on gun 
ownership, but they still accused Republicans of obstruction. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's move. We are tired of seeing delay. We are tired of  
seeing stonewalling,'' said Rep. Rosa DeLauro, D-Conn. ``We also 
realize and understand that they have dragged their feet on this, 
putting it off until the last week. I don't know what they're 
hoping for, because it's not going away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate bill, in addition to requiring background checks on  
all firearms buyers at gun shows, would require dealers to provide 
safety devices with all handguns, ban importation of certain 
high-capacity firearms clips and impose a lifetime prohibition of 
gun ownership by anyone convicted as a juvenile of a serious 
felony. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
