<DOCNO> APW19990731.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 13:44:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Cohen Offers U.S. Aid to Ukraine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARTENIT, Ukraine (AP) -- The United States and Ukraine agreed  
Saturday to extend for another six years a program helping the 
former Soviet republic dismantle its ballistic missiles and nuclear 
weapons infrastructure. 
</P>
<P>
	Visiting Defense Secretary William Cohen also promised aid to  
Ukraine to fund its peacekeeping contingent for Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen announced the extension of the Cooperative Threat  
Reduction Program, saying the decision testified to Ukraine's 
commitment to nuclear disarmament and the two countries' growing 
ties. 
</P>
<P>
	``We already have more than 100 separate programs and our  
relationship continues to expand,'' Cohen told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Ukraine inherited the world's third-largest nuclear arsenal with  
the 1991 collapse of the Soviet Union, but pledged to become 
nuclear-free. It surrendered all its nuclear warheads to Russia, 
and was left with 130 SS-19 missiles, 46 SS-24 missiles and more 
than 40 Tu-160s and Tu-95 MC strategic bombers. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States has contributed more than $500 million under  
the Cooperative Threat Reduction Program to help Ukraine dismantle 
the weapons. The program was initiated in 1991 to promote nuclear 
disarmament in the former Soviet Union. The Ukrainian part was 
slated to expire in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Ukraine has destroyed all of its SS-19 missiles and their launch  
silos, one SS-24 silo and one bomber under the program. 
</P>
<P>
	But observers say cash-poor Ukraine has been lagging in  
destroying the rest of its nuclear arsenal because of money 
problems, prompting the six-year extension. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen arrived on Ukraine's Black Sea peninsula of Crimea for a  
whirlwind visit Saturday. He traveled to Foros, a resort where 
President Leonid Kuchma was vacationing. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense secretary's convoy stopped to pay respects to a  
memorial to British soldiers killed in the Crimean War of the 
1850s. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Kuchma and parliament approved the deployment of up  
to 800 soldiers in Kosovo. Kuchma said at the time that NATO had 
agreed to finance the soldiers' transportation and housing costs 
while Ukraine would pay their salaries. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Cohen said: ``We intend to contribute to a  
peacekeeping effort on the part of Ukraine. We will seek 
contribution from other NATO countries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Presidential spokesman Oleksandr Martynenko quoted Cohen as  
saying that financial details would be worked out during an 
upcoming visit by the alliance's deputy commander of armed forces 
in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen's meeting with Kuchma also touched upon bilateral military  
cooperation, nonproliferation of weapons of mass destruction and 
military reform. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Ukrainian armed forces are undergoing a complicated  
process of reform and the assistance of the U.S. defense ministry 
is very important for us,'' Ukrainian news reports quoted Kuchma as 
saying. 
</P>
<P>
	In meetings with Kuchma, Kuzmuk and other officials, Cohen also  
promised further assistance to Ukraine in military training, in 
particular peacekeepers, Martynenko said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen also met with Ukrainian Defense Minister Oleksandr Kuzmuk  
during a separate meeting near Partenit, a village 60 miles from 
the port of Sevastopol. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen's visit to Ukraine was part of a tour that also included  
visits to Japan and South Korea. He left Saturday evening for the 
former Soviet republic of Georgia, the final leg of his trip. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen last visited Ukraine in July 1997.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 13:44:43 </DATE_TIME>
