<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Timeline in Tripp Wiretapping Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	1993  
</P>
<P>
	Nov. 21: Linda Tripp, then a White House aide, encounters a  
volunteer, Kathleen Willey, leaving the Oval Office. Mrs. Tripp 
later says Mrs. Willey's lipstick was smeared and her blouse 
untucked. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	1995  
</P>
<P>
	July: Monica Lewinsky goes to work as a White House intern,  
later becoming a paid staff member. 
</P>
<P>
	Nov. 15: Sexual relationship begins between Clinton and Ms.  
Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	1996  
</P>
<P>
	April 5: White House transfers Ms. Lewinsky to the Pentagon.  
</P>
<P>
	Fall: Ms. Lewinsky tells Mrs. Tripp, now a Pentagon staffer,  
about her relationship with Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	1997  
</P>
<P>
	May 24: Ms. Lewinsky's sexual relationship with Clinton ends.  
</P>
<P>
	Aug. 11: In a Newsweek magazine story, Mrs. Tripp says Mrs.  
Willey told her Clinton made a pass at her in 1993; Clinton lawyer 
Robert Bennett says Mrs. Tripp ``is not to be believed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sept. 18: Mrs. Tripp and New York literary agent Lucianne  
Goldberg discuss Mrs. Tripp's proposal to write a book about White 
House sex scandals. 
</P>
<P>
	Sept. 29: In a tape-recorded conversation, Ms. Goldberg tells  
Mrs. Tripp ``there's no problem'' with secretly taping telephone 
calls in Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	Oct. 3: Mrs. Tripp purchases a voice-activated phone recorder at  
a Radio Shack and begins taping her conversations with Ms. 
Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	Nov. 24: Mrs. Tripp learns from her attorney, Kirby Behre, that  
secretly taping in Maryland is illegal, according to testimony she 
later gave for Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's investigation. 
She tapes Ms. Lewinsky several more times, saying it is ``to 
protect myself.'' After secretly arranging to contact attorneys for 
Paula Jones, Mrs. Tripp is subpoenaed in Mrs. Jones' lawsuit 
against Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	1998  
</P>
<P>
	Jan. 12: Mrs. Tripp hands over tapes to Starr.  
</P>
<P>
	Jan. 13: FBI agents working for Starr wire Mrs. Tripp with a  
hidden microphone and record her meeting with Ms. Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	Jan. 16: FBI agents and Starr's deputies confront Ms. Lewinsky  
and seek her cooperation in exchange for immunity from prosecution. 
No deal is made. Starr gets permission from federal appeals court 
to widen Whitewater investigation to include Clinton's relationship 
with Ms. Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	Jan. 17: In a deposition for Mrs. Jones' case, Clinton denies  
having sex with Ms. Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	Jan. 21: Word of Clinton affair with Ms. Lewinsky appears in  
press for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	Jan. 23: Columbia (Md.) Democratic Club urges Howard County  
State's Attorney Marna McLendon to order a criminal investigation 
of Mrs. Tripp. 
</P>
<P>
	Jan. 26: McLendon says she won't pursue investigation of Mrs.  
Tripp. 
</P>
<P>
	Jan. 29: Forty-nine Democratic members of Maryland's House of  
Delegates sign a letter criticizing McLendon. 
</P>
<P>
	Feb. 11: McLendon says she will hand over the Tripp case to  
Stephen Montanarelli, an appointed state prosecutor. 
</P>
<P>
	Aug. 6: Howard County grand jury begins hearing evidence against  
Mrs. Tripp. 
</P>
<P>
	Aug. 17: Clinton testifies before federal grand jury, publicly  
acknowledges improper relationship. 
</P>
<P>
	Sept. 12: Starr report released.  
</P>
<P>
	Oct. 8: House votes to hold impeachment inquiry.  
</P>
<P>
	Nov. 12: Ms. Goldberg and son Jonah testify before Howard County  
grand jury. Ms. Goldberg says she urged Mrs. Tripp to start taping 
after doubts were cast about Mrs. Tripp's credibility. Ms. Goldberg 
gives prosecutors tapes of two conversations she had with Mrs. 
Tripp and two others containing conversations between Ms. Lewinsky 
and Mrs. Tripp. 
</P>
<P>
	Nov. 13: Clinton agrees to pay Paula Jones $850,000 to drop her  
sexual harassment lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Dec. 10: Mrs. Tripp's former attorney, James Moody, appears  
before the grand jury, but refuses to answer questions or hand over 
tapes. 
</P>
<P>
	Dec. 11-12: House Judiciary Committee approves impeachment  
articles accusing Clinton of perjury in his deposition in the Jones 
suit, perjury in his grand jury testimony and obstruction of 
justice. 
</P>
<P>
	Dec. 19: House impeaches Clinton.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	1999	   Jan. 7: Clinton's impeachment trial begins in Senate.  
</P>
<P>
	Feb. 12: Senate acquits Clinton.  
</P>
<P>
	June: A federal judge orders Starr to give Mrs. Tripp's tapes to  
Montanarelli. 
</P>
<P>
	June 18: Howard County grand jury hears evidence obtained by  
prosecutors from Ms. Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	July 30: Grand jury indicts Mrs. Tripp on two counts of  
violating Maryland wiretapping law. 
  	   	
</P>
