<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> S. Miss Baseball Star Has Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Southern Mississippi baseball player  
Michael Artman, who set a school record with 106 hits this past 
season, was diagnosed with testicular cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Artman, a first baseman and center fielder, was released from  
Baptist Medical Center in Jackson on Friday and will begin 
chemotherapy this week. 
</P>
<P>
	His doctor is optimistic about his treatment and playing future.  
</P>
<P>
	``He said there's a strong possibility Michael will be able to  
play ball this spring,'' said Dan Artman, Michael's father. 
``Michael is pretty strong. I haven't heard a negative thing from 
him. He's had a lot of people calling, a lot of coaches and 
players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Testicular cancer is treatable when detected in the early  
stages. 
</P>
<P>
	Bicyclist Lance Armstrong, the 1993 world road race champion,  
won Tour de France this month after learning in October 1996 that 
he had testicular cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Artman, who batted .408 and finished the season with a 20-game  
hitting streak, was diagnosed with cancer when he came home to 
Jackson on a break from playing summer baseball in Missouri. 
</P>
<P>
	The 21-year-old junior helped lead Southern Miss to a 40-23  
record and its first NCAA Tournament appearance since 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	He will sit out the fall semester at Southern Miss while  
undergoing chemotherapy, Dan Artman said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
