<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Seeks To Ban Punitive Damages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BAY CITY, Mich. (AP) -- A federal bankruptcy judge said Friday he  
will focus on whether Dow Corning Corp.'s corporate parents should 
remain immune to lawsuits as part of a $4.5 billion settlement over 
silicone breast implants. 
</P>
<P>
	Dow Corning is owned equally by Dow Chemical Corp. and Corning  
Corp. Judge Arthur Spector said the heart of the settlement is the 
question of immunity for the two. 
</P>
<P>
	``This plan is illegal, it's unconstitutional, it's unauthorized  
and it's in bad faith under the (bankruptcy) code,'' attorney 
Geoffrey White, an attorney for several Nevada women, said during 
the last day of a hearing into the settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	Spector also requested lawyers to submit more briefs on the  
question of punitive damages. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the debtor's product didn't cause these people's diseases  
... then they shouldn't have to pay anything,'' he said. ``If they 
did cause diseases or syndromes, then until they have no more money 
they should pay.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Midland-based company filed for bankruptcy in 1995 after  
thousands of women started suing, claiming breast implants of Dow 
Corning silicone caused a variety of diseases. 
</P>
<P>
	Spector didn't say when his ruling might come. If he doesn't  
confirm the plan, a new settlement would have to be drafted. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the proposed settlement, women who blame illnesses on  
implants could get $12,000 to $300,000 each. They could also 
receive up to $25,000 for ruptured or leaking implants, and up to 
$5,000 for implant removal. 
</P>
<P>
	It provides $3.2 billion to settle claims from women with  
implants and an additional $1.3 billion to settle other claims, 
including claims from creditors and health-care organizations. The 
company would set aside up to $400 million to cover any costs of 
defending lawsuits by women who reject the settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 113,000 women voted on the settlement terms earlier this  
year, and 94 percent approved. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
