<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Heat-Related Death Toll at 133  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Twenty-six more people have died from the heat in  
Chicago, pushing Illinois' heat-related death toll to 49 and the 
nation's casualties to 133, even as today brought cooler weather to 
parts of the country. An additional 20 deaths in Chicago may be 
heat-related and were under investigation, Mayor Richard Daley 
said, announcing the latest deaths from the heat wave that scorched 
much of the nation and produced New York City's hottest July on 
record. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Pushes for Patients' Rights  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Seeking to exploit Republican defections,  
President Clinton pressed GOP leaders today to allow a House vote 
on legislation guaranteeing protections for managed-care patients 
before lawmakers leave next weekend for the summer. Clinton noted 
that some GOP House members, led by lawmakers who are also medical 
doctors, have joined Democrats to urge support for a ``patients' 
bill of rights'' for Americans whose health care plans are through 
health maintenance organizations. 

</P>
<P>
	Skydiving Plane Crashes, 10 Die  
</P>
<P>
	COTTRELLVILLE TOWNSHIP, Mich. (AP) -- Authorities said a plane  
carrying nine members of a skydiving group that was holding its 
annual campout crashed shortly after takeoff today, killing all the 
passengers and the pilot. State Police Sgt. Craig Nyeholt said the 
plane, a twin-engine Beech King Air 200, came down at 8:20 a.m. in 
a grassy field near Marine City Airport, about 40 miles north of 
Detroit. The cause wasn't known. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Sets Deadline for Tax Cut Deal  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans are laboring under a tight  
self-imposed deadline to sculpt a $792 billion tax cut compromise 
that can clear the House and Senate by week's end and set the stage 
for a fall veto showdown with the White House. House Speaker Dennis 
Hastert, R-Ill., and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., 
gave fellow Republicans only until Tuesday to resolve differences 
between bills passed by the House and the Senate. 

</P>
<P>
	Blair Urges End to Kosovo Violence  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair  
visited Kosovo's capital today, urging ethnic Albanians to live in 
peace with rival Serbs. Despite the 35,000 NATO troops in Kosovo, 
violence has continued, mostly in revenge attacks by ethnic 
Albanians on Serbs for the killings, rapes and forced removals that 
prompted the NATO attacks. Blair told several hundred people 
gathered in the city center that NATO fought the war to bring peace 
and justice to Kosovo, not to allow the minority Serbs in the 
province to be oppressed. 

</P>
<P>
	Quayle Proposes 30 Percent Tax Cuts  
</P>
<P>
	WOODSVILLE, N.H. (AP) -- Former Vice President Dan Quayle  
proposed a 30 percent tax cut and flexible tax-free savings 
accounts today, saying dramatic tax reductions are needed to 
strengthen American families. ``The American family is overtaxed, 
and this rate reduction will enable parents to keep more of their 
paycheck, which just might be the difference that allows more time 
with the children, rather than more time working,'' he said at a 
reception in Orford. 

</P>
<P>
	Barton's Wife Had Safety Concerns  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Mass killer Mark O. Barton's first victim in a  
murderous rampage last week -- his wife, Leigh Ann -- had been 
worried for her safety but loved Barton's children and wanted to 
continue to be involved in their lives, her older sister Dana 
Reeves said today. Barton killed his 27-year-old wife, his two 
children from a previous marriage, and nine people in the offices 
of two brokerage firms Thursday before killing himself. 

</P>
<P>
	Spacecraft Hits Moon, No Dust Seen  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lunar Prospector's violent collision with the  
moon today left no visible cloud of dust, but researchers still 
hope to find traces of water in a vapor plume possibly created by 
the impact. At least 20 observatory telescopes focused on the 
moon's south pole as the spacecraft, in its final task for science, 
was sent toward a frozen crater and smashed itself around 5:52 a.m. 
EDT today. 

</P>
<P>
	20th Swiss Disaster Victim Found  
</P>
<P>
	INTERLAKEN, Switzerland (AP) -- Police said today the body of one  
of the last tourists missing in a Swiss Alps river flood was found, 
bringing the death count from the canyoning disaster to 20. 
Rescuers located the body late last night. The tragedy occurred 
when unexpected floods swept through the canyon and engulfed 
tourists and guides bodysurfing through Saxeten Brook. One person 
was still missing. 

</P>
<P>
	Davies Surges Ahead in du Maurier  
</P>
<P>
	PRIDDIS, Alberta (AP) -- Laura Davies made birdie from the bunker  
on the 18th hole to build a two-shot lead over Canadian Dawn 
Coe-Jones going into the final round of the the du Maurier Classic. 
``If I shoot the best round tomorrow, then obviously I win,'' said 
Davies, at 9-under 207 after three trips around Priddis Greens Golf 
and Country Club. Davies also won the du Maurier in 1996. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
