<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Promises Help for Veterans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANDERSON, S.C. (AP) -- GOP Sen. John McCain met with hundreds of  
veterans during his weekend campaign tour of South Carolina before 
he ran into one who shared a very special bond with the former 
Vietnam POW running for president. 
</P>
<P>
	James William ``Billy'' Bailey, a 56-year-old school  
administrator from Anderson, was in the same North Vietnamese 
prison camp at the same time as McCain and turned out Saturday to 
lend support. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a man of integrity and honesty. I think he's the best man  
qualified to run for president,'' Bailey said after greeting McCain 
outside the bus. 
</P>
<P>
	At stops along his route, McCain addressed small but  
enthusiastic crowds about how money has corrupted the political 
process in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	He told audiences usually jammed with veterans about how the  
federal government must provide veterans' health care benefits and 
pay enlisted men and women enough to keep them off food stamps. 
Then he answered as many questions as his schedule allowed. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain, R-Ariz., also criticized both Democrats and Republicans  
for their allegiance to special interests and big money. 
</P>
<P>
	``All these huge amounts of money make good people do bad  
things,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain's ``Straight Talk Express'' bus tour started Friday and  
was to last four days. It is McCain's ninth visit to South 
Carolina, which holds its primary Feb. 19. He is splitting his 
campaign time between New Hampshire and South Carolina, where he is 
the most active GOP candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	``South Carolina will be a pivotal state as it was in 1996,'' he  
told a television interviewer Saturday in Greenville. ``South 
Carolina is the gateway to the Republican nomination.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even though Texas Gov. George W. Bush holds a huge lead in the  
polls and fund raising, the atmosphere on the McCain campaign bus 
is loose and upbeat. The tone is set by the 62-year-old McCain, who 
keeps up a steady stream of one-liners. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked on the bus how his campaign is going, McCain quipped:  
``It's always darkest before it's totally black.'' He quickly added 
he is pleased with the progress his campaign has made, both in fund 
raising and key polls. A recent poll in New Hampshire showed him 
far behind Bush, but with numbers that had climbed from 3 percent 
to the low teens. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaign aides say he should have the money and campaign  
organization to compete with Bush effectively in New Hampshire and 
South Carolina, which both have limited media markets. Political 
analysts say Bush will have an advantage in organization and 
establishment support in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain's campaign has raised $8.1 million and has almost $5  
million in cash, aides say. He said he has not faced the financial 
drought other candidates face because Bush has raised almost $40 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain is not competing in the Aug. 14 Iowa straw poll, saying  
straw polls are a waste of resources. But his advisers say they 
will discuss in the fall what level of effort they will put into 
the Iowa caucus, the initial step in the GOP selection process. 
</P>
<P>
	The key for McCain, advisers say, is to be competitive in the  
New Hampshire primary and be positioned to derail Bush's 
front-running campaign in South Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Accompany McCain on the bus tour are his wife, Cindy, and U.S.  
Reps. Lindsey Graham and Mark Sanford of South Carolina. The tour 
features a mix of stops for broadcast interviews and small rallies 
populated largely by military veterans. South Carolina has one of 
the nation's highest concentrations of veterans -- more than 
400,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Graham said McCain is a good match with South Carolina voters.  
</P>
<P>
	``Once people look and listen, he will do well,'' Graham said.  
</P>
<P>
	McCain, who comes from a family with a rich military tradition,  
was a POW in the Vietnam War for more than five years. He hopes to 
build a base of veteran support in South Carolina and attract 
disaffected voters who like his message on government reform. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we need a genuine American hero right now,'' said  
Billy Hudgens, a Greenwood insurance agent who came to a McCain 
event. ``I believe he has inner strength. It's evident from his 
wartime experience. He's willing to stand up to people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCain was asked by reporters on the bus why he was putting so  
much effort into the South Carolina primary. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because of the greatness of its citizens,'' he said, then  
grinned as he added: ``And its position on the political 
calendar.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
