<DOCNO> APW19990731.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 06:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GOP Braces for Tax-Cut Battle  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House and Senate Republicans are moving  
quickly to join forces for the coming battle against the White 
House over the size and scope of the tax cut they hope to give the 
American people in the next decade. The Senate yesterday approved a 
$792 billion tax plan that mirrors an earlier House-passed bill in 
size but differs in the kinds of tax relief included. The vote was 
57-43, mostly along party lines. President Clinton has said 
repeatedly he will veto the GOP plans because they are three times 
what the economy can safely digest. 

</P>
<P>
	Blair Cheered During Kosovo Visit  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Ethnic Albanians lavished British  
Prime Minister Tony Blair with cheers, flowers and even a kiss or 
two today as he visited the Kosovo capital and urged its people to 
live together in peace. It was Blair's first visit to Kosovo since 
NATO's bombing campaign against Yugoslavia. He visited British 
troops for several hours last night after attending a summit on 
Balkan stability in Sarajevo, Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</P>
<P>
	Craft Crashes Moon in Water Search  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Lunar Prospector spacecraft was sent to a  
violent collision with the moon today. But powerful telescopes 
watching from the Earth failed to detect a dust cloud, a result 
that some called ``a bit of a disappointment.'' The lack of dust, 
however, does not mean that a search for evidence of water on the 
moon has failed, experts said. Telescopes, using ultraviolet 
filters, will continue to look for clues that water vapor was 
splashed into the lunar sky by the impact. 

</P>
<P>
	Atlanta Gunman Promised Revenge  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Mark O. Barton, the gunman who killed nine people  
at two brokerage firms Thursday, had lost roughly $105,000 in stock 
trading in less than two months, authorities said yesterday. He 
left a note vowing revenge on those who had ``greedily sought my 
destruction.'' Barton's wife, son and daughter were found 
bludgeoned to death in the family residence. Thirteen also were 
wounded in the office attacks, with five still in critical 
condition last night. Barton killed himself to avoid arrest. 

</P>
<P>
	Rescuers Find 20th Swiss Disaster Victim  
</P>
<P>
	INTERLAKEN, Switzerland (AP) -- Rescuers have recovered the body  
of one of the last people missing after a river accident this week 
in the Swiss Alps, police said today. The discovery brings to 20 
the number of people confirmed killed in the flash flood. The body 
was found last night in Lake Brienz, about 2 1/2 miles downstream from 
the scene of the accident, at a depth of more than 200 feet, Bern 
state police said. The people were swept away as they bodysurfed 
down the fast-running Saxeten Brook on Tuesday near this central 
Alpine resort. 

</P>
<P>
	Partners To Get Airline Benefits  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- United Airlines agreed to extend some  
benefits to domestic partners, just hours after an appeals court 
yesterday refused to grant the company an exemption to a city 
ordinance mandating the benefits. The law, which took effect June 
1, 1997, requires companies doing business with San Francisco to 
offer the same benefits to domestic partners as they do to married 
spouses. United said it will begin offering family benefits to 
non-married families nationwide next May. The company has 20,000 
employees in San Francisco. 

</P>
<P>
	McGwire Ties Sosa With 38th Homer  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Mark McGwire tied Sammy Sosa for the major  
league lead with 38 home runs and set a record for most homers in a 
five-year span when he hit one in the sixth inning of St. Louis' 
game against Colorado last night. McGwire hit a 1-0 pitch from 
Pedro Astacio into the right-field bullpen to lead off the sixth 
for his 11th homer in 15 games and cut the Rockies' lead over the 
Cardinals to 3-2. He has 257 homers the last five years, breaking 
the record he shared with Babe Ruth, who hit 256 from 1926-30. 

</P>
<P>
	Yankees Pummel Red Sox 13-3  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Chuck Knoblauch and Derek Jeter started the game  
with consecutive home runs and Hideki Irabu struck out 12 last 
night to lead the New York Yankees to a 13-3 victory over the 
Boston Red Sox. Knoblauch, who missed the previous two games after 
complaining of dizziness, was 5-for-6 with four RBIs. Jorge Posada 
had two doubles and a two-run homer. The back-to-back homers to 
lead off the game were the first for the Yankees since April 27, 
1955, when Hank Bauer and Andy Carey did it against the Chicago 
White Sox. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
