<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 13:39:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bipartisan Tax-Cut Effort Fizzles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Efforts to craft a $500 billion bipartisan tax  
cut fizzled unceremoniously in the Senate on Thursday as political 
lines hardened and President Clinton reinforced his threat to veto 
a larger Republican tax relief package. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe America wants to be governed from the center, and  
America needs to be governed from the center,'' Sen. Arlen Specter, 
R-Pa., said of the bipartisan proposal, which roughly split the 
difference between the GOP's $792 billion tax cut and a smaller 
$290 billion version advanced by Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sen. John Breaux, D-La., a leading architect of the  
proposal, conceded, ``Neither party at this time is supportive.'' 
After more than an hour of debate, Breaux withdrew the measure 
without so much as a vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The developments came as the Senate marched methodically toward  
approval of the GOP-crafted bill, with tax breaks for individuals, 
families, education, retirement accounts and numerous other 
provisions. A final vote was set for Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	House-Senate talks are expected to begin this weekend, and GOP  
leaders harbor hopes of passing the resulting compromise through 
both houses next week. That would enable Republicans to spend 
Congress' August break touting the virtue of their measure, and set 
the stage for a fall confrontation with the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Before boarding Air Force One for a flight to Europe, Clinton  
renewed his threat to veto the bill, saying it was too large and 
``risky'' for the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's wrong with the American people sharing the surplus?  
After all, it belongs to them,'' rebutted Sen. Frank Murkowski, 
R-Alaska. House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., who shepherded a 
companion bill to passage last week, added, ``I don't think it's 
risky to have faith in the American people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's threatened veto, coupled with the Senate's arcane  
rules, turned the lengthy debate on the Senate floor into political 
theater. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats, maneuvering for advantage, called for reducing the  
GOP tax measure to provide room for a new prescription drug benefit 
for Medicare recipients. But the vote came on a parliamentary 
motion rather than on any specific proposal to provide prescription 
drug benefits to the nation's elderly. And it gained the support of 
only 45 senators -- all but one of them Democrats -- far below the 60 
votes it needed. 
</P>
<P>
	``This debate is about priorities. New tax breaks are a priority  
for the Republicans,'' said Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass. 
``Prescription drugs for senior citizens are not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. William Roth, R-Del., countered that as chairman of the  
committee with jurisdiction over Medicare, the Senate Finance 
Committee, he intended to address ``this most important concern'' 
as soon as lawmakers return to Washington from their scheduled 
August break. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., sharply rebutted Democratic claims  
that the GOP tax bill wouldn't leave room for a new Medicare 
benefit. Instead, he sought to turn the political tables. 
</P>
<P>
	A veto by Clinton, he said, would wipe out provisions to make  
education more affordable and child care more accessible. ``Where 
does he get off running around the land saying he's for education 
and we're not?'' Domenici said. 
</P>
<P>
	Similarly, Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, and other Republicans  
sought to substitute an across-the-board tax cut similar to the 
House measure for a portion of the bill pending in the Senate. That 
proposal, too, was rejected on a parliamentary motion after 
politically tinged debate. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats argued the change would make the measure more  
favorable to the wealthy at the expense of lower-income Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	But Gramm said 50 percent of Americans pay only 4.3 percent of  
income taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't get a tax cut because they don't pay income  
taxes,'' he said. ``Tax cuts are for taxpayers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Each side also labored to show its backing for popular programs  
for the elderly. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans pushed a ``lockbox'' amendment that they said would  
set aside surpluses generated by payroll tax revenue for Social 
Security. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats countered with a similar proposal that would have  
offered protection to Medicare, as well as Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	Both approaches were rejected.  
</P>
<P>
	As written, the GOP proposal called for reducing the 15 percent  
income tax rate to 14 percent, effective in 2001. Beginning in 
2005, the new 14 percent tax rate would apply to some income that 
is now taxed at 28 percent. Together, those provisions account for 
nearly $300 billion of the $792 billion measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation also includes relief from the so-called marriage  
penalty that forces some couples to pay more in taxes than they 
would if they were single. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also contains several provisions to assist taxpayers  
with retirement accounts, to provide tax breaks for education and 
long-term health care, and to reduce estate taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, the doomed bipartisan proposal would have increased  
the standard deduction by $4,300 for joint tax filers, $2,150 for 
heads of households and $1,300 for single filers. Supporters said 
that change would have eliminated the marriage penalty for many 
taxpayers and simplified tax filing for millions of Americans. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
