<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 13:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Johnny Mitchell Quits Jets Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- Johnny Mitchell's comeback with the New  
York Jets lasted one day. 
</P>
<P>
	The team's first-round draft pick in 1992, who was out of  
football for the last two seasons, turned in his equipment shortly 
before Saturday morning's training camp session and left without 
speaking to anyone. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell, 28, was signed by the Jets in February after asking  
coach Bill Parcells for a chance to make the roster. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets planned to terminate the tight end's contract, believed  
to be a two-year, $1.2 million deal, later Saturday. Mitchell was 
not given a signing bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	``It didn't take long, did it?'' Parcells said. ``It's sad. One  
day -- you'd think you'd give it more than that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After signing with Miami as a free agent in 1996, Mitchell  
lasted 12 days with the Dolphins before walking out of camp. He 
spent five weeks on the Dallas Cowboys' roster later that season 
before dropping out of football for two years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told the rest of the team, 'Any more of you that are going  
to quit, do it now,' '' Parcells said of announcing Mitchell's 
departure to the team. ``I told them, 'Don't waste my time.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Later in the day, another player apparently took Parcells' words  
to heart. Veteran offensive lineman Erik Norgard, expected to back 
up Kevin Mawae at center, also left camp for undisclosed reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets said they would take no immediate action on Norgard,  
who signed a three-year, $2.4 million contract with the Jets last 
spring after playing his first nine seasons with the Oilers. 
</P>
<P>
	The team said that Norgard, 33, told Parcells that he no longer  
wished to play. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Mitchell nor Norgard was available for comment.  
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-3, 248-pound Mitchell, who emerged from the club's  
offseason workout program in terrific shape, apparently had grown 
upset over his struggles with the playbook. Teammates who played 
with the former Nebraska standout during his initial tour with the 
club from 1992-95 said Mitchell had grown reserved in recent weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was more quiet than usual,'' safety Victor Green said. ``He  
came out (Thursday) and I didn't hear him say anything. He didn't 
even talk. I guess he couldn't deal with it. I heard someone say 
that he said it was too much mentally. He was making too many 
mental errors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets had hoped that Mitchell would earn a spot as one of the  
team's F-backs, a hybrid fullback-tight end position that Parcells 
and offensive coordinator Charlie Weis are considering for this 
season. With Mitchell gone, second-year tight end Blake Spence, 
along with fullbacks Jerald Sowell and Richie Anderson, are 
considered the front-runners for the role. 
</P>
<P>
	There was also speculation that the Jets will re-sign running  
back Keith Byars, a leader in the team's march to the AFC title 
game last season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
