<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 08:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors Puzzled by Drug's Underuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	So maybe they really should put statin drugs in the water supply  
as some heart doctors only half-jokingly suggest. 
</P>
<P>
	The put-it-in-the-water quip inevitably surfaces, it seems,  
whenever heart specialists gather to talk pills. It echoes both 
their confidence in statins' power to lower cholesterol and their 
frustration that millions miss out. 
</P>
<P>
	Why is it, they wonder, that despite nonstop haranguing by the  
country's top heart gurus and saturation advertising by drug 
makers, these safe, lifesaving medicines are so underused? 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly everyone who studies cholesterol for a living seems to  
agree that statin drugs should be taken by many more people. 
Statins are one of the true medical breakthroughs of recent times. 
They spectacularly reduce cholesterol, and they do it far better 
than even the most draconian diet and exercise programs. A 60-point 
drop in cholesterol is nothing special on statins. 
</P>
<P>
	Their effects on health are equally impressive. Statins keep  
arteries from clogging up and may even reverse the process. People 
on statins lower their risk of heart attacks by about one-third. 
They need fewer angioplasty and bypass operations. And they live 
longer. 
</P>
<P>
	Furthermore, the drugs are easy to take, and side effects are  
rare. Clearly, this is medicine that works. Yet statins are not 
being pumped into the water supply, not even close. 
</P>
<P>
	About 8 million Americans now take them. But in the opinion of  
many of the country's heart disease elite, perhaps 20 million, even 
30 million, should be on statins. As a result, heart disease, the 
country's No. 1 killer, will take many more than it should. 
</P>
<P>
	Statin drugs ``have had the greatest impact of anything I've  
seen over the past three decades,'' says Dr. Antonio Gotto, a 
cardiologist and dean of the Cornell University medical school. 
``With wider application, they have the potential of making a 
tremendous dent in death and disability from coronary disease. 
We've only started to scratch the surface of that potential.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Why is that? Many say it boils down to the simplest of  
shortcomings: Doctors fail to offer statins to people who need 
them; people who need them fail to take them. 
</P>
<P>
	Behind the obvious is a complex web of problems and  
uncertainties, and experts say no single thread tells the whole 
story. For instance, at $100 a month, price alone keeps many off 
the drug, and that's just the start. Some doctors are too out of 
touch or overworked to write the prescriptions. Some patients are 
too pill-phobic to take them. And then there's the fact that the 
medical system often emphasizes treating disease rather than 
preventing it. 
</P>
<P>
	Five brands are available: Lipitor, Zocor, Pravachol, Lescol,  
Mevacor and Baycol. They are called statins because their generic 
names, such as lovastatin and atorvastatin, all end the same way. 
The first of these drugs came on the market a decade ago, but the 
evidence of their worth amassed slowly, much of it over the past 
five years. 
</P>
<P>
	The drugs differ in potency but basically work the same way. All  
inhibit a protein called 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coenzyme A 
reductase, which is necessary for the liver to make cholesterol. 
When statins first came into use, many doctors were leery they 
might cause liver damage. But over time this has proven to be 
highly unusual. 
</P>
<P>
	Only about 1 percent of statins users have possible liver  
abnormalities, as measured by a blood enzyme test given a few weeks 
after treatment starts. The problem is reversible if they quit the 
medicine or possibly switch brands. In one big study, abnormal 
liver enzymes turned out to be just as common among people on dummy 
pills as those taking statins. Whatever the connection, serious 
liver damage from statins has proven to be exceedingly rare. 
</P>
<P>
	As prescription drugs go, statins are unusually free of risks.  
``Ten milligrams of statins is probably as safe as two aspirins,'' 
says Dr. Richard Pasternak of Massachusetts General Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors also were dubious at first because they had no proof  
that lowering cholesterol with statins actually saves lives. But 
this, too, has changed with a series of landmark mega-studies. 
</P>
<P>
	The first was the Scandinavian Simvastatin Survival Study, which  
tested Zocor on people with both obvious heart disease and high 
cholesterol. Their risk of dying during five years on the medicine 
was about 30 percent lower than expected. Since cardiovascular 
disease kills nearly 1 million Americans annually, the implications 
-- both for preventing deaths and selling drugs -- were obvious. 
</P>
<P>
	To see who else might benefit, four other big studies have since  
looked at statins' effects on folks with healthier hearts and less 
ominous cholesterol levels. The results are remarkably consistent. 
On statins, the risk of dying, of having a heart attack or of 
needing a bypass or angioplasty are between 25 percent and 33 
percent lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Committees of medical experts sometimes meet to help front-line  
doctors make sense of new medical evidence like this. The last time 
this happened for statin drugs was in 1993, when the federal 
government's National Cholesterol Education Program drew up 
guidelines. 
</P>
<P>
	That was before the big studies came out, but even then the  
committee felt the evidence was clear that people with heart 
disease should get statins -- along with sensible diets -- if their 
cholesterol levels are modestly elevated. It set the cutoff for 
cholesterol levels higher for those with no signs of heart disease. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, the committee will meet again to update these  
recommendations, and it almost certainly will lower the threshold 
for statin use. Still, Dr. James Cleeman, the education program's 
head, estimates that under the 1993 standards, about 12 million or 
13 million Americans should be taking statins -- or 50 percent more 
than are now. 
</P>
<P>
	Some experts believe statins should be offered to at least twice  
as many people as the 1993 government standards suggest. At some 
elite medical centers, doctors ignore the guidelines and put 
virtually all heart attack victims on statins, no matter what their 
cholesterol levels. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're adopting the philosophy that your cholesterol is too  
high for you if you've had a cardiac event,'' says Dr. Shelley 
Shapiro of the University of Southern California. ``We're starting 
it right in the ICU. They go home with statins.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There is little question among the experts that statins should  
be front-line therapy for what they call secondary prevention -- 
keeping victims of heart attacks and angina pain from getting 
worse. 
</P>
<P>
	``The data in secondary prevention are overwhelming,'' says Dr.  
John A. Ambrose of Saint Vincents Hospital in New York City. ``You 
can't even get people to argue about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet doctors estimate that the drugs are prescribed by only 20  
percent of those diagnosed with cardiovascular disease. 
</P>
<P>
	There is some disagreement about what doctors call primary  
prevention -- giving statins to those who have no outward signs of 
heart trouble. But even here, evidence is building that outwardly 
healthy people with only mildly elevated cholesterol will live 
longer and better if they take statins. 
</P>
<P>
	The most persuasive evidence comes from Gotto's study of about  
6,000 middle-aged men and women. Their total cholesterol readings 
averaged around 220, somewhat higher than ideal but typical for 
American adults, while their HDL, the variety of cholesterol that 
protects against heart attacks, was considered to be a bit low. On 
statins, their risk of first-time heart attacks and serious chest 
pain fell by about one-third. 
</P>
<P>
	To some, these results mean that many more healthy Americans  
should be on statins, even if their cholesterol levels seem normal. 
Indeed, only 17 percent of the people in Gotto's study would be 
considered candidates for taking statins under the 1993 guidelines. 
</P>
<P>
	Those rules discourage statins for healthy people unless their  
levels of artery-clogging LDL cholesterol are at least 160. The 
biggest controversy among statins advocates is how low this number 
should fall. Some say 100 is a reasonable cutoff. Others push for 
even more aggressive cholesterol lowering. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you look at more primitive societies, it's not uncommon to  
see adult males with LDLs less than 80,'' says Dr. Steven Nissen of 
the Cleveland Clinic, a member of the lower-is-better camp. ``We 
have simply set the standard too high. We've got to get LDL down to 
60 to 80 and total cholesterol under 150. I think we'll find if we 
do that, we will literally stop this disease in its tracks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Statins studies are underway to see if Nissen is right. No  
matter what the results, however, some doctors are likely to balk 
at putting perfectly healthy people on cholesterol drugs for life. 
This is because most won't benefit in the short run. In Gotto's 
study, 55 people had to take statins for five years to prevent one 
heart attack or angina onset. 
</P>
<P>
	However, doctors have many less-thought-out reasons, too, for  
ignoring statins. One is that many primary care doctors simply do 
not know much about them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't care if statins have been out there for 10 years. Lots  
of specialties are not good at incorporating new ideas into 
practice, and generalists tend to be slower,'' says Dr. Theodore 
Ganiats of the University of California-San Diego, who represents 
primary care doctors on the National Cholesterol Education Program. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other reasons:  
</P>
<P>
	--Many doctors feel that in a 10-minute office visit, they can  
convince patients to make only one or two changes. If a potbellied 
50-year-old smoker has high blood pressure and borderline diabetes, 
cholesterol may not seem like the most important thing to talk 
about. 
</P>
<P>
	--Some doctors may not want the extra work involved in persuading  
patients to take statins, making sure they have follow-up liver 
tests, checking their cholesterol counts, scaling up the doses as 
necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	--''Physicians tend to be a real show-me group that changes  
slowly and gets on the bandwagon slowly,'' says Dr. Calvin 
Weisberger, a Kaiser Permanente cardiologist in Los Angeles. Many 
probably remain skeptical of the benefits of statins, no matter 
what they've heard. 
</P>
<P>
	--Statins typically cost between $70 and $100 a month. This is  
likely to seem especially steep, considering that the drugs 
typically don't make people feel better. But prices are likely to 
fall in the next two to three years as the drugs lose patent 
protection and cheaper generics appear. Drug companies might even 
ask approval to sell them without prescription. 
</P>
<P>
	--Some people shun statins because they ``overestimate how much  
personal control they have over their cholesterol,'' says Dr. Margo 
Denke of the University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center. Most 
cannot bring seriously high cholesterol down enough with diet 
alone. That approach typically can lower cholesterol by only about 
5 percent to 10 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Some patients are not told, or don't understand, that they have  
to use statins for the rest of their lives, not just until their 
cholesterol falls. 
</P>
<P>
	Medical shortcomings have a way of healing themselves over time,  
and underuse of statins is likely to do the same. Experts estimate 
that statin prescriptions rose by almost one-third last year. And 
some doctors say the aversion to prescribing statins and taking 
them appears to be easing. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Andrew Hauser of William Beaumont Hospital in Royal Oak,  
Mich. has little doubt what this will mean. ``The statins, more 
than any other drug in the last decade, offer the promise for 
patients at risk of coronary artery disease to live a full life 
free of angina, heart attacks and premature death,'' he says. ``I 
have no idea what the reluctance is, personally. The evidence is so 
overwhelming.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
