<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Noon EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Ten Die in Michigan Plane Crash  
</P>
<P>
	COTTRELLVILLE TOWNSHIP, Mich. (AP) -- A plane carrying passengers  
on a weekend skydiving trip crashed early today, killing all 10 
aboard, state police said. The plane, which took off from Marine 
City Airport, broke into several pieces after it crashed just prior 
to 9 a.m., officials said. Officials from the Federal Aviation 
Administration and the National Transportation Safety Board are en 
route to the scene. Cottrellville Township is located about 40 
miles north of Detroit. 

</P>
<P>
	Two Hong Kong Stores Pull Sect Books  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Two bookstores that are among Hong Kong's  
largest have stopped selling books on the Falun Gong meditation 
group, banned in mainland China, a sect spokesman said today. The 
spokesman, Kan Hung-cheung, told government-owned Radio Hong Kong 
that that he did not know why the books were not being sold at some 
stores. Officials at Hong Kong's Commercial Press and the Joint 
Publishing Co. were not available for comment today. The report 
could spark fears that China is pressuring the territory to 
restrict freedoms. 

</P>
<P>
	Blair Urges End to Kosovo Violence  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair  
made a triumphant visit to Kosovo's capital today, urging grateful 
ethnic Albanians who gave him flowers and kisses to live in peace 
with rival Serbs. It is Blair's first trip to Kosovo since the end 
of NATO's bombing campaign against Yugoslavia and the return of 
hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanian refugees driven off by 
Serb forces. Blair told several hundred people gathered in the city 
center that NATO fought the war to bring justice to Kosovo, not to 
allow the minority Serbs in the province to be oppressed. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Braces for Tax-Cut Battle  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans are laboring under a tight  
self-imposed deadline to sculpt a $792 billion tax cut compromise 
that can clear the House and Senate by week's end and set the stage 
for a fall veto showdown with the White House. House Speaker Dennis 
Hastert, R-Ill., and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., 
have given fellow Republicans until only Tuesday to resolve 
differences between bills passed by the House and Senate. The 
Senate yesterday approved a $792 billion tax plan 57-43, mostly 
along party lines. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Pushes for Patients' Rights  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton challenged Congress today to  
pass certain guaranteed rights for managed-care patients' before 
lawmakers break for summer vacation next weekend. Some Republicans, 
led by physicians serving in Congress, are joining Democrats in 
support of the ``patients' bill of rights'' concept and Clinton 
predicts a strong bill would pass if GOP leaders allow a vote. 
``Protecting patients' rights shouldn't be a political issue,'' 
Clinton said in his weekly radio address. ``This isn't a partisan 
issue anywhere else in America. It shouldn't be in Washington, 
D.C.'' Most Republicans say the sweeping Democratic plans are too 
expensive. 

</P>
<P>
	Heat Wave Linked to 94 Deaths  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Cool air from Canada is bringing relief from the  
heat to parts of the Midwest and forecasters say a cold front 
should cause temperatures to drop in Michigan, Iowa and Nebraska 
today. Storms last night have already cooled things off in 
Wisconsin and Minnesota. In Chicago, where the heat index neared 
120 yesterday, forecasters say relief is also expected. The current 
heat wave has been linked to at least 94 deaths across the country 
since July 19. 

</P>
<P>
	Craft Crashes Into Moon in Water Search  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Lunar Prospector spacecraft was sent to a  
violent collision with the moon today, but powerful telescopes 
watching from the Earth failed to detect a dust cloud. The lack of 
dust, however, does not mean that a search for evidence of water on 
the moon has failed, experts said. Telescopes, using ultraviolet 
filters, will continue to look for clues that water vapor was 
splashed into the lunar sky by the impact. 

</P>
<P>
	Hawks, Blazers Ready To Deal  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Atlanta Hawks will trade all-star guard Steve  
Smith and backup Ed Gray to the Portland Trail Blazers for guards 
Isaiah Rider and Jim Jackson, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution 
reported in today's editions. The deal is likely to be announced 
Monday as the NBA trading and free-agency period begins, the 
newspaper said. The earliest the trade can be announced is 
tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
