<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rep. George E. Brown Eulogized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rep. George E. Brown Jr. was remembered Friday  
as a warm congressman with twinkling eyes, a commitment to justice, 
a passion for scientific research and a disdain for opinion polls. 
</P>
<P>
	``George Brown was one of the greatest leaders to ever serve in  
the House of Representatives,'' Rep. Jerry Lewis, R-Calif., said 
during a memorial service at Statuary Hall in the Capitol. 
</P>
<P>
	``He belonged to the house of the people,'' Sen. Barbara Boxer,  
D-Calif., said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, a California Democrat and the oldest member of the House  
at 79, died July 15 after a lengthy hospital stay. His family said 
he had developed an infection following heart surgery three months 
earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	He represented California's 42nd District, which includes the  
city of San Bernardino and other towns east of Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown was first elected to the House in 1962, representing the  
29th District in Los Angeles County for eight years and making a 
name for himself as an opponent of the Vietnam War. 
</P>
<P>
	He was re-elected over and over even though he sometimes took  
politically unwise positions, fellow lawmakers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He did not read polls,'' said Rep. Sam Farr, D-Calif. ``Nobody  
ever cast more unsafe votes than George Brown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri remembered Brown as  
``the most successful politician that I ever met who was a 
nonpolitician.'' 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert presented Brown's widow with two  
flags that flew over the Capitol in Brown's honor on Wednesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
