<DOCNO> APW19990731.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 07:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Reopens for Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Penny Hardaway's career in Orlando could be entering its final  
moments. The same might be true of Vin Baker's stint in Seattle, 
although that's a lot less likely. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Smith is expecting the Atlanta Hawks to trade him to  
Portland, and the Boston Celtics have been doing their utmost to 
deal Ron Mercer. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, Detlef Schrempf has gotten mad at the SuperSonics,  
Charles Oakley has been hot and cold toward the Raptors, Shandon 
Anderson has flirted with leaving the Jazz, and Mitch Richmond is 
wondering whether he'll ever get his big payday. 
</P>
<P>
	Those players, along with dozens of others, will get their  
answers in the first few days of August as the NBA's one-month 
moratorium on trades and free-agent signings ends. 
</P>
<P>
	``This moratorium month has created a sense of a lack of  
urgency,'' Orlando Magic general manager John Gabriel said Friday, 
``because there has been time to talk about a variety of deals 
while at the same time negotiating contracts with the players you 
plan to have back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whether the Magic plan to have Hardaway back is one of the  
biggest questions to be answered in the coming days. Hardaway opted 
out of the final three years of his contract, becoming a free 
agent, and seems to have a better chance of joining the Lakers, 
Raptors, Trail Blazers or Suns than staying in Orlando. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're still listening and negotiating,'' Gabriel said.  
</P>
<P>
	Hardaway seems most eager to play in a warm-weather city, but  
Portland and Toronto should be able to make better offers than the 
Lakers and Suns. 
</P>
<P>
	The four-time All-Star is one of more than 140 free agents who  
have been allowed to negotiate with all 29 teams since July 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Other players are attracting widespread interest as well.  
</P>
<P>
	With everyone on the lookout for a young, capable big man,  
players such as Lorenzen Wright of the Clippers and Jermaine O'Neal 
of the Trail Blazers have been inundated with offers. 
</P>
<P>
	Trade talk has been rampant, too, with Atlanta, Portland, Boston  
and Dallas among the most active teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think a lot of these teams are making panic moves,  
overreacting to what happened in a 50-game season,'' Jason Kidd of 
Phoenix said. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, who played with Kidd earlier this month on the U.S.  
Olympic qualifying team in Puerto Rico, has said he expects to be 
dealt to Portland for Isaiah Rider and another player, perhaps Jim 
Jackson or Kelvin Cato. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker, who opted out of his contract and became a free agent,  
was leaning toward returning to Seattle -- but not without first 
considering whether he'd prefer to join the Celtics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I definitely want to go back to Seattle, but I have to  
consider where I want to be for the next seven years of my life,'' 
Baker said. ``That's going to be based on my family and what I 
think is important for them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, Boston is a place I'd love to play, simply because  
of where I'm from -- Hartford -- and where my family and friends are. 
But again, Seattle is the place I'm hopefully looking forward to 
going back to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reports surfaced late in the week that the Celtics and Mavericks  
were discussing a sign-and-trade deal that would send Mercer to 
Dallas for Samaki Walker and a future No. 1 pick. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston also was willing to listen to almost any offer for Kenny  
Anderson, while Golden State was willing to take back virtually 
nothing for Donyell Marshall. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sonics were scrambling to find a replacement for Schrempf,  
who was miffed that Seattle offered him a deal worth only $1.1 
million after he made $3.3 million last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Possible replacements for Schrempf include Rick Fox, Cedric  
Henderson and Cedric Ceballos. 
</P>
<P>
	Oakley, miffed that the Raptors haven't markedly improved their  
original offer of $12 million for three years, could be involved in 
a sign-and-trade deal for Hardaway. Reports in Toronto said the 
Raptors were considering offering Oakley and Tracy McGrady to 
Orlando for Hardaway. 
</P>
<P>
	Oakley also has been courted by the Lakers and Atlanta Hawks.  
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, the backup shooting guard for Utah behind Jeff  
Hornacek, is considering relocating to San Antonio if the Jazz 
don't offer him a deal starting at more than $3 million per year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs have suddenly found themselves with about $2.75  
million in salary cap room after the NBA granted their request for 
an injury exception to help them cope with the loss of Sean 
Elliott, who needs a kidney transplant. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Richmond, there is interest in Golden State, Sacramento  
and Seattle, although none of those teams can pay him nearly as 
much as his current team, the Wizards. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
