<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lions Enlist Sanders' Father Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Stunned by Barry Sanders' retirement, the Detroit  
Lions' vice chairman is planning strategy to get the running back 
to reconsider walking away from the game. 
</P>
<P>
	And to that end, William Clay Ford Jr. has enlisted some help --  
from Sanders' father, William Sanders. 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Sanders said late Friday he would encourage his son to  
meet with Ford, who hopes to talk Barry into returning to the game. 
He announced his retirement on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	But even to William Sanders, the prospect of a meeting remained  
cloudy Friday night, given that his son is touring Europe and 
hasn't talked to his father. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry Sanders, 31, shocked the football world Wednesday by  
announcing his retirement after 10 years, just 1,458 yards shy of 
breaking Walter Payton's NFL career rushing record of 16,726 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders said in a statement his ``desire to exit the game is  
greater than my desire to remain in it'' for what would be the 
third year of a six-year, $36 million contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Those stunned by Sanders' move included Ford, who called  
Sanders' father at his Wichita, Kan., home Wednesday morning and 
sought his help in arranging a meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told him I'd do everything I can,'' the elder Sanders said  
Friday night. ``The guy (Ford) really seemed like he was on the 
up-and-up, a man of his word. Just in talking to him, he seemed 
awfully impressive. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to try to change (Barry's) mind, but I will ask  
him to contact Mr. Ford. I think that's only fair.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lions spokesman Bill Keenist on Friday night acknowledged that  
Ford spoke with the elder Sanders the day Barry Sanders announced 
his retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	``But that's the extent of what I can tell you,'' Keenist said.  
``Bill suggested that if there was anything he could do, that he 
would be available, and Mr. Sanders acknowledged that, and that was 
the extent of the discussion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders' retirement is not final, at least not technically. The  
Lions have put him on the reserve-did not report list, which would 
allow him to rejoin the team this season. Sanders also has not 
filed retirement papers with the league office. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's still possible (Sanders could return), and that's the  
basis of placing Barry in the category that we did,'' Lions coach 
Bobby Ross said. ``We've got to proceed as though he's not going to 
be here, but I'd be very happy if he came back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked Wednesday at London's Gatwick Airport whether he might  
change his mind, Sanders said: ``I don't think that's going to 
happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But his father said he believes that as far as his arranging a  
meeting, ``the odds are in Mr. Ford's favor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of his son, the elder Sanders said: ``I think he'll listen to  
me. He has nothing to lose. 
</P>
<P>
	But he added, ``I have no way of reaching him. In fact, I don't  
think he wants to be reached. I think he wants to just do his own 
thing.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
