<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Redskins Owner Visits Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FROSTBURG, Md. (AP) -- On the hottest day the Washington Redskins  
have ever experienced in the Maryland mountains, it was easy to 
spot the team's new owners. They were the ones wearing long 
trousers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's exciting, it's fantastic,'' Daniel Snyder said on his  
first visit to training camp since buying the team for $800 
million. ``It sure is hot, though.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That was about the only definite public pronouncement Snyder  
made before he watched practice in stifling heat unusual for the 
area. Still, he never took off the burgundy and gold tie and he and 
his father, Gerald Snyder, and another partner, Fred Drasner, 
checked out their investment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anybody know a rain dance?'' asked trainer Bubba Tyer, worried  
about the effects of the heat on his players. 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder has been quick to make changes in the front office and is  
promising to be a hands-on owner. Hardly a day goes by that a 
report doesn't surface over some move he'd reportedly like to make 
-- everything from acquiring Barry Sanders, Jamal Anderson or Carl 
Pickens to changing the name of Jack Kent Cooke Stadium or moving 
camp from Frostburg to the Washington area. 
</P>
<P>
	But with notepads open and cameras switched on, Snyder  
maintained his growing reputation of publicly saying nothing. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing I can say is that we're looking to improve the  
Redskins,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	When practice ended, helicopters landed on the field to whisk  
the Snyders and Drasner away, another first at Redskins camp. 
Before he left, Snyder held a long talk with coach Norv Turner on 
the field and also spoke at length with his hand-picked director of 
player personnel, Vinny Cerrato. 
</P>
<P>
	``They haven't slept lately,'' Snyder said. ``They usually talk  
to me late at night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the players seemed excited to have the new big man  
around. 
</P>
<P>
	``If your boss comes into the office, I'm sure you'd shake it up  
a bit,'' long snapper Dan Turk said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
