<DOCNO> APW19990731.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 07:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Pushes for Patients' Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton challenged Congress today to  
debate and pass certain guaranteed rights for managed-care 
patients' before lawmakers break for summer vacation next weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Republicans, led by physicians serving in Congress, are  
joining Democrats in support of the ``patients' bill of rights'' 
concept. That has Clinton predicting a strong bill would pass if 
GOP leaders would allow a vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``Protecting patients' rights shouldn't be a political issue.  
After all, no one asks us what our party affiliation when we show 
up at the emergency room or the doctor's office,'' Clinton said in 
his weekly radio address. ``This isn't a partisan issue anywhere 
else in America. It shouldn't be in Washington, D.C.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate has passed a weaker bill than the Clinton  
administration and almost all Democrats on Capitol Hill are 
pushing. House GOP leaders had planned to put a similar bill on the 
floor this week, which they said was necessary to get it passed 
before their vacation, but Republican defections to the Democratic 
bill prevented action. 
</P>
<P>
	Most Republicans contend the sweeping Democratic plans would be  
too expensive. They want a limited bill that would give patients 
new rights of appeal but no right to sue a health management 
organization that denies care. That legislation also would give 
doctors some new power without removing an HMO's right to determine 
what care is medically necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	On his address, which the president taped in Europe for  
broadcast today, Clinton said he has made wider protections 
available to 85 million Americans who use federal plans such as 
those under Medicare, Medicaid and Veterans Affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Evidence shows putting in patients' rights raised the cost of  
these plans by only a dollar a month; so we know these rights are 
affordable, as well as crucial,'' the president said. ``Yet, until 
Congress acts, tens of millions of Americans in managed care are 
still waiting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a few House Republicans signal their willingness for a  
stronger bill, Clinton said, ``There is a bipartisan consensus 
emerging behind a bill that would give all Americans the health 
protections they need. This bill should be debated and voted on 
this coming week, before Congress adjourns for the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``If that happens, I believe the bill would pass and the  
American people would benefit.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
