<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 18:01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Women's Soccer Gets Another Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- What the Women's World Cup started in  
the United States, those at the Pan American Games hope to push a 
little more down the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Less than three weeks after the second Women's Football  
Symposium in Los Angeles finished with a call for more women's 
age-limited tournaments -- and specifically a world championship -- 
five under-20 national teams have gathered in Winnipeg to compete 
for only the second confederation-sanctioned youth crown offered. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very positive to have this competition immediately after  
the World Cup,'' said Mexican coach Leonardo Cuellar, who also 
coached Mexico's women's team at USA '99 and brought five members 
of that squad to Winnipeg. ``The TV is here. This is being shown in 
Mexico. It is giving exposure to what needs to be done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the Pan Ams starting only 13 days after the Women's World  
Cup final, CONCACAF, which was given virtual control of the event, 
decided to make it an under-20 competition. 
</P>
<P>
	That limited the number of countries participating because most  
nations barely field a senior national team, let alone an underage 
side. 
</P>
<P>
	On top of that, the United States sent essentially its under-18  
team because of its commitment to the Nordic Cup, an annual 
invitational that for a little less than a decade has stood as a de 
facto youth championship. 
</P>
<P>
	That eight-team event is set for Iceland on Aug. 2-8.  
</P>
<P>
	``I hope it's obvious to the rest of the world that we're being  
very aggressive in an area of the game that needs promotion,'' 
CONCACAF deputy general secretary Ted Howard said. ``We also know 
we need to promote it in our member nations where it may not be the 
most accepted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only last week, CONCACAF joined Asia, Africa, Europe and South  
America in announcing that next year it will stage a continental 
championship for women. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Pan Ams is only the second non-exhibition title for  
girls, following in the path of last year's European under-18 
championship. 
</P>
<P>
	And it's clear those associated with the women's programs are  
thrilled. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is tremendous for our younger players,'' said Canada  
coach Neil Turnbull, who like Cuellar coached his country's senior 
team at the Women's World Cup. ``One thing we lack is World 
Cup-level experience. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I want to bring a new girl into the national team, her  
first cap might be against the United States -- the best team in the 
world. Her second might be against China. (The Pan Ams) is 
international soccer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Los Angeles two days before the World Cup final, Per Ravn  
Omdal of Norway, chairman of FIFA's Committee for Women's Football, 
said the creation of more women's championships, and specifically 
youth events, would spur confederations and national associations 
into creating and supporting women's teams. 
</P>
<P>
	But there is also the concern youth tournaments will widen the  
gap between the haves and have nots of women's soccer. The belief 
is that already developed powers will further improve, while others 
will become discouraged from getting pounded. 
</P>
<P>
	Clearly at the Pan Ams, the United States, Canada and Mexico are  
in one tier, with Costa Rica and Trinidad and Tobago in another. 
</P>
<P>
	In four games, the Americans and Canadians routed Costa Rica and  
Trinidad by a combined score of 25-2. The scores were similar to 
some seen during World Cup qualifying. 
</P>
<P>
	``The talent pool (at the youth level), despite gains, is not  
that big,'' 1999 Women's World Cup spokesman Aaron Heifetz said 
from his office in Los Angeles. ``It's much tougher for developing 
nations to put together teams.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But, even for those that get pummeled, some see positives.  
</P>
<P>
	``It all depends on what you do with it, how you view it,'' said  
U.S. coach Jay Hoffman, who also used to coach the U.S. men's 
under-20 team. ``It depends on what you do as a follow-up. If 
somebody just brought a team here, but doesn't do anything until a 
year from now ... 
</P>
<P>
	``If you bring a team in here, and next month you do a little  
more, and then a little more ... I assume all countries here are 
attempting to improve. If that's the case, it will only help sport, 
only help the confederation.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0124 </DOCNO>
