<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religious Conservatives Back Forbes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Publisher Steve Forbes' effort to  
broaden his political base got a boost Saturday when a dozen 
conservative religious leaders signed a letter declaring him a 
leader of ``America's new conservative movement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He knows that the liberties we enjoy are rooted in faith,''  
said the letter, mailed to conservative activists around the state 
where precinct caucuses in February launch the presidential 
nominating season. 
</P>
<P>
	Dissemination of the letter follows a bizarre week in which the  
head of the Iowa section of the Christian Coalition of America 
charged that Forbes approached her temporary employment agency 
about hiring people to vote for him in Iowa's August straw poll. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes denied the charge by Bobbi Gobel, and she issued a  
statement backing away from the claim. The organization fired her 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The endorsement letter, which Forbes aides said was in the works  
months before the Gobel brouhaha, was signed by prominent ministers 
and activists who have played an important role among religious 
conservatives for years. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes' aides said the endorsement is aimed at demonstrating the  
candidate's inroads toward bridging a gap that dogged his last 
presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	When Forbes sought the GOP presidential nomination in 1996,  
social conservatives were deeply suspicious of his commitment to 
issues such as opposing abortion. After focusing almost exclusively 
on a flat income-tax system, he was forced from the race. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, Forbes has devoted heavy attention to conservative  
issues, promising, for example, that as president he would appoint 
only judges opposed to abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	In their endorsement letter, the religious leaders said Forbes  
is ``a leader of America's new conservative movement. He believes 
in freedom and he knows that the freedom we enjoy is a gift from 
God.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The letter was signed by pastors Greg Altizer, of Cedar Rapids;  
Jan Burns, of Farmington; Don Culp, of Keokuk; Michael Erpelding, 
of Fort Dodge; John Graham, of Belle Plaine; Robert Grossman, of 
Garner; Morris Hurd, of Kellogg; Laddie Oliver, of Keosauqua; and 
Brad Sherman, of Iowa City. 
</P>
<P>
	It also got the backing of Keith Fournier, former head of the  
Catholic Alliance. Also signing on were Steve Scheffler, former 
field director of the Iowa Christian Coalition, and prominent 
religious conservative leader Nancy Streck. 
</P>
<P>
	``As never before we need someone who is willing to lead a  
cultural renewal in America,'' the letter said. ``We need someone 
who is not afraid to speak out for the things he believes, a return 
to the time when life was more valuable than choice, when children 
could pray to God in school without fear of reprisal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The letter urges conservative activists to show up at the straw  
poll and vote for Forbes. ``The Forbes campaign will provide 
transportation, registration, food and entertainment,'' the letter 
notes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Gobel episode ended Friday with a terse statement from the  
Christian Coalition's national headquarters that Gobel ``has been 
dismissed.'' It said the state board was being reorganized. 
</P>
<P>
	The statement also said the Christian Coalition ``sincerely  
regrets any inappropriate and inaccurate public statements that 
have recently been made regarding presidential campaigns or 
candidates.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gobel long has been hostile toward Forbes, which caused some to  
suspect her motives. Adding to that, she told reporters she was 
upset that the large number of candidates courting conservatives 
divided their vote and weakened their influence. 
</P>
<P>
	About Forbes, she said when she made the straw poll allegations:  
``I don't buy the conversion.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
