<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                         *Amaryllis Fleming    	
</P>
<P>
	NETTLEBED, England (AP) -- Amaryllis Fleming, a celebrated  
cellist and one of the most colorful figures of the musical and 
social world of the 1960s, died Tuesday. She was 73. 
</P>
<P>
	Having begun playing cello at an early age, Ms. Fleming won a  
spot at the Royal College of Music in 1943. She established herself 
throughout the 1950s, eventually choosing to concentrate on chamber 
music. She later became a professor of cello at the Royal College 
of Music. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1970, she stood in for Bette Davis in a film called  
``Connecting Rooms,'' in which the Hollywood star played a cellist. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Dr. Edmund Klein    	
</P>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Dr. Edmund Klein, who pioneered the  
treatment of certain skin cancers with topical chemicals, died 
Saturday. He was 77. 
</P>
<P>
	Klein was among the first to recognize the need for nonsurgical  
therapies for superficial skin cancer like that arising from 
prolonged exposure to the sun. 
</P>
<P>
	He also advanced the use of immunotherapy, in which agents are  
applied to stimulate the immune system, enabling the body to fend 
off tumors. The method pointed the way toward the use of interferon 
and interleukins in cancer therapy today. 
</P>
<P>
	His work was honored with a Clinical Research Award from the  
Albert and Mary Lasker Foundation in 1972. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Simon Nkabinde    	
</P>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- Simon Nkabinde, a singer who  
became a legend in South Africa while popularizing Zulu music 
internationally, died Wednesday. He was 61. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallo Music Co. announced Nkabinde's death and said that he had  
been ill for some time with diabetes. 
</P>
<P>
	Nkabinde, better known as Mahlathini, was the gravel-voiced lead  
singer for his group, Mahlathini and the Mhaotella Queens. He had 
performed his music alongside such internationally known artists as 
Stevie Wonder and Sting. 
</P>
<P>
	Mahlathini and the Mahotella Queens produced hit after hit in  
the '60s and '70s and was often regarded as South Africa's first 
superband. The group disbanded in the late '70s but reformed to 
record the hit Yebo in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	He popularized Mbaqanga music, a fusion of dominant African  
rhythms, pop and jazz that started in the black township of Soweto 
outside Johannesburg. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Nilo A. Olin    	
</P>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) -- Nilo A. Olin, a former West Virginia  
sports cartoonist and photographer, died Thursday. He was 85. 
</P>
<P>
	After serving in World War II as an Army combat photographer,  
Olin joined The Charleston Gazette, where he became known for his 
caricatures of athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	In the early days of television, Olin became chief photographer  
at Charleston stations WKNA-TV and WCHS-TV. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1957, he moved to Washington as chief photographer for  
American Forest Products Industries and later as photo chief for 
the National Institute of Mental Health. 
</P>
<P>
	Olin is survived by his wife, Hazel, two children, one  
grandchild and a sister. 

</P>
<P>
                       *Anatoliy Solovianenko    	
</P>
<P>
	KIEV, Ukraine (AP) -- Anatoliy Solovianenko, one of Ukraine's  
best known opera singers and a former Metropolitan Opera soloist, 
died Thursday of an apparent heart attack. He was 66. 
</P>
<P>
	The tenor performed as a soloist for decades at the Kiev Opera  
and Ballet Theater in the Ukrainian capital and was a soloist at 
the Metropolitan Opera in New York in 1977-78. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, Solovianenko headed a charity foundation and  
performed in concerts. 
</P>
<P>
	He held a variety of Soviet titles and awards, including the  
prestigious Popular Artist of the USSR title and the Lenin Prize, 
as well as Ukraine's State Shevchenko Prize. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Stanley Suyat    	
</P>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- Stanley Suyat, a former state official who later  
joined the Clinton administration in Washington, died Sunday of 
cancer. He was 55. 
</P>
<P>
	Suyat served as state director of consumer protection from 1979  
to 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	He worked in Bill Clinton's 1993 presidential campaign in  
Nevada, and later became White House liaison and acting chief of 
staff with the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Suyat later became associate director for management of the  
Peace Corps for four years. He was director of civil rights for the 
U.S. Department of Energy at the time of his death. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
