<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Keeps Hospital Restraint Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A challenge by hospitals and mental health  
care providers to new proposed federal regulations on the use of 
restraints in hospitals was dismissed Friday by a federal judge. 
</P>
<P>
	The rules, which were announced in June by the Health Care  
Financing Administration, prohibit the use of restraints and 
seclusion as a means for coercion, discipline, convenience or 
retaliation. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Association of Psychiatric Health Systems and the  
American Hospital Association contested a provision requiring a 
physician or licensed practitioner to meet face-to-face with and 
evaluate the patient within one hour of being placed in seclusion 
or restraints. 
</P>
<P>
	The two groups sought a temporary injunction against enforcement  
of the provision, saying that it was a major change in practice and 
merited further discussion. They proposed a substitute that would 
have allowed the doctor to consult with the patient's nurse within 
an hour and determine whether to come in immediately or give orders 
over the phone and come in at a later point. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Court Gladys Kessler dismissed their motion  
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Covall, executive director of the National Association of  
Psychiatric Health Systems, said the group supports the overall 
regulations, but feared that provision would cause substanital 
hardship to physicians. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the groups will continue to work with the administration  
on the regulations, which are to go into effect in late August. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
