<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rather Would Be Happy Chasing Story </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Even though he's a multi-million dollar anchor  
man, Dan Rather likes to pound the pavement just like a 
rank-and-file journalist. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm chasing my dream of trying to be a great reporter,'' the  
CBS veteran told the Aug. 9 edition of People magazine. ``If I 
can't be the smartest or most affable person on television, I can 
be the hardest-working.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rather, 67, makes $6 million a year to anchor the network's  
evening news, and has no plans to retire, even after his contract 
expires in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like anchoring,'' he said, ``but if tomorrow someone said,  
'Dan, we'd like to have somebody else,' I'd say 'Fine. Make me the 
AP bureau chief in Alpine, Texas, and I'll be very happy.''' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
