<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Heat Wave Linked to 94 Deaths  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Cool air from Canada is bringing relief from the  
heat to parts of the Midwest and forecasters say a cold front 
should cause temperatures to drop in Michigan, Iowa and Nebraska 
today. Storms last night have already cooled things off in 
Wisconsin and Minnesota. In Chicago, where the heat index neared 
120 yesterday, forecasters say relief is expected tonight from a 
cool front moving into the region. The current heat wave has been 
linked to at least 94 deaths across the country since July 19. The 
Midwest has been hardest hit, with Missouri logging 29 heat-related 
deaths, Illinois 23 and 10 in Ohio. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Braces for Tax-Cut Battle  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House and Senate Republicans are moving  
quickly to join forces for the coming battle against the White 
House over the size and scope of the tax cut they hope to give the 
American people in the next decade. The Senate yesterday approved a 
$792 billion tax plan that mirrors an earlier House-passed bill in 
size but differs in the kinds of tax relief included. The vote was 
57-43, mostly along party lines. President Clinton has said 
repeatedly he will veto the GOP plans because they are three times 
what the economy can safely digest. 

</P>
<P>
	Six Die in Michigan Plane Crash  
</P>
<P>
	MARINE CITY, Mich. (AP) -- A plane carrying 10 people on a  
weekend skydiving trip crashed early today, killing at least six 
aboard, officials said. The conditions of the other four were not 
immediately known, said a dispatcher with the St. Clair County 
Sheriff's office. The plane went down prior to 9 a.m., the 
dispatcher said. Officials from the Federal Aviation Administration 
and the National Transportation Safety Board are en route to the 
scene of the accident. 

</P>
<P>
	Twenty Hurt in Car-Bus Collision  
</P>
<P>
	DOWNERS GROVE, Ill. (AP) -- Twenty factory workers were injured,  
some seriously, when a car driven by an alleged drunken driver 
slammed into the back of a bus that was carrying them to work, 
authorities said. Several passengers were ejected from the small 
bus about 10 p.m. last night after the collision caused it to hit a 
power pole on Interstate 355 and tip over, the police said. At 
least 18 people were hospitalized, including three who were in 
intensive care. The driver of the BMW that collided with the bus 
was also injured. She was charged with driving under the influence. 

</P>
<P>
	Blair Cheered During Kosovo Visit  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Ethnic Albanians lavished British  
Prime Minister Tony Blair with cheers, flowers and even a kiss or 
two today as he visited the Kosovo capital and urged its people to 
live together in peace. It was Blair's first visit to Kosovo since 
NATO's bombing campaign against Yugoslavia. He visited British 
troops for several hours last night after attending a summit on 
Balkan stability in Sarajevo, Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</P>
<P>
	Rescuers Find 20th Swiss Disaster Victim  
</P>
<P>
	INTERLAKEN, Switzerland (AP) -- Rescuers have recovered the body  
of one of the last people missing after a river accident this week 
in the Swiss Alps, police said today. The discovery brings to 20 
the number of people confirmed killed in the flash flood. The body 
was found last night in Lake Brienz, about 2 1/2 miles downstream from 
the scene of the accident, at a depth of more than 200 feet, Bern 
state police said. The people were swept away as they bodysurfed 
down the fast-running Saxeten Brook on Tuesday near this central 
Alpine resort. 

</P>
<P>
	Craft Crashes Moon in Water Search  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Lunar Prospector spacecraft was sent to a  
violent collision with the moon today. But powerful telescopes 
watching from the Earth failed to detect a dust cloud, a result 
that some called ``a bit of a disappointment.'' The lack of dust, 
however, does not mean that a search for evidence of water on the 
moon has failed, experts said. Telescopes, using ultraviolet 
filters, will continue to look for clues that water vapor was 
splashed into the lunar sky by the impact. 

</P>
<P>
	Hawks, Blazers Ready To Deal  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Atlanta Hawks will trade all-star guard Steve  
Smith and backup Ed Gray to the Portland Trail Blazers for guards 
Isaiah Rider and Jim Jackson, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution 
reported. The deal is likely to be announced Monday as the NBA 
trading and free-agency period begins, the newspaper said in 
today's editions. The earliest the trade can be announced is 
tomorrow. By trading Smith, 30, the Hawks would end a commitment of 
$36 million over the next four seasons to a player who missed 14 
games last season with bruised knees. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
