<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 17:33:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Braces for Battle on Tax Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House and Senate Republicans are moving  
quickly to join forces for the coming battle against the White 
House over the size and scope of the tax cut they hope to present 
to the American people in the next decade. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate on Friday approved a $792 billion tax plan that  
mirrors an earlier House-passed bill in size but differs in the 
kinds of tax relief included. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote was 57-43, mostly along party lines.  
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton has said repeatedly he would veto the GOP  
plans because they are three times what he thinks the economy can 
safely digest amid efforts to ensure the solvency of Social 
Security and Medicare and pay down the national debt. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Senate made the wrong choice for America's future,''  
Clinton said in a statement Friday. ``By pushing through a tax plan 
that is too big and too bloated, the majority party has pushed 
aside our vital national priorities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said congressional  
tax specialists would begin talks as early as today, and that a 
House-Senate conference could be held early next week to pave the 
way for final passage of a compromise plan at week's end. 
</P>
<P>
	There is some urgency because Congress recesses at the end of  
the week for its month-long summer vacation. But Lott indicated the 
final bill would not be sent to the president until Congress 
returns in September, avoiding a veto while lawmakers are away from 
Washington and giving them a chance to make their case to voters. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to make sure the American people understand what we  
have done,'' said Senate Budget Committee Chairman Pete Domenici, 
R-N.M. ``We'd like to get our message across.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lott began that message campaign today in the weekly Republican  
radio address. With the federal budget projected to show a $3.4 
trillion surplus in the next decade, he asked, ``shouldn't you be 
able to keep more of what you earn, for your household needs, or to 
save for your family's future?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It isn't selfish to want lower taxes. You know your family  
pays too much for government. I know it. And so does the president. 
But he wants that cash for spending here in Washington,'' Lott 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Clinton and most Democrats say that if Social Security  
revenues are put aside, the surplus amounts to about $1 trillion, 
and the GOP plans would put nearly all of that into tax cuts -- 
ignoring education, defense and other programs and doing little to 
fix Social Security and Medicare. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP course ``can best be characterized as one of both  
wishful thinking and fiscal disaster,'' said Senate Democratic 
leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota. 
</P>
<P>
	The main elements of the Senate plan include a reduction in the  
bottom 15 percent income tax bracket to 14 percent and expansion of 
the number of taxpayers eligible for that bracket. 
</P>
<P>
	It would increase the standard deduction for married couples in  
2001 and allow those couples to file returns as singles in a 
combined form starting in 2005. That would help to eliminate 
situations in which married people pay more than singles because 
their combined incomes forces them into a higher bracket. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate bill would raise the exemption for estate taxes from  
$1 million to $1.5 million in 2007 and raise annual contribution 
limits for individual retirement accounts from $2,000 to $5,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The big difference in the House bill is that it provides for an  
across-the-board 10 percent cut in tax rates. It also cuts the top 
capital gains tax rate for most investments held at least a year 
from 20 percent to 15 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott, who backed a failed attempt to include an across-the-board  
cut in the Senate bill, said he wasn't sure the House-Senate 
conference would move in that direction, but ``if it were that or 
anything else in this bill I'd take that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Four Democrats -- Robert Torricelli of New Jersey, Mary Landrieu  
and John Breaux of Louisiana and Bob Kerrey of Nebraska -- voted for 
the GOP plan, while Republicans Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania and 
George Voinovich of Ohio opposed it. 
</P>
<P>
	Torricelli, who earlier backed an unsuccessful attempt by  
Democratic and Republican moderates to push a $500 billion tax cut, 
said he thought that approach would eventually prevail. 
</P>
<P>
	``After the political script gets played out, the bipartisan  
plan will serve as a blueprint for an October solution that bridges 
the divergent positions on tax cuts,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
