<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 03:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sharp Still Rolling at Dover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DOVER, Del. (AP) -- Before he drove his first lap at Dover Downs  
International Speedway, John Hollansworth Jr. had his doubts. 
</P>
<P>
	As a law school graduate, he likes to weigh all evidence before  
accepting anything. So when confronted with testimony that nothing 
could be any tougher than Dover Downs, Hollansworth had trouble 
believing it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was reading the driver quotes on my laptop last night,  
especially Eddie Cheever about how physically demanding this track 
is and his comparison to Monte Carlo,'' Hollansworth said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Monte Carlo street course, where Cheever raced in Formula  
One, is reputed to be the most difficult driving test of any in the 
world. Cheever says Dover is equally demanding. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't believe him ... until I got out there,'' Hollansworth  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Once he did, Hollansworth learned the feeling of racing 180 mph  
into sharp, highly banked turns where gravity fights against 
centrifugal force. Then he drove in a fashion belying his rookie 
status in the Indy Racing League. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was our first time out here,'' he said after running the  
fifth-fastest lap Friday as practice began for Sunday's MBNA 
Mid-Atlantic 200. ``We have never tested.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Billy Boat also heard tales of racing on the concrete surface  
called White Lightning. Because he missed the race last year -- the 
first open-wheel event in Dover since 1969 -- with an injury, Boat 
also was unsure how difficult the track could be. 
</P>
<P>
	After practice, he wondered no longer.  
</P>
<P>
	``I can see why they call this place The Monster Mile,'' Boat  
said. ``I can see it's going to be hard on the drivers and 
equipment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Owner-driver Cheever knows that all too well. After the driver  
collected $1.4 million for winning the 1998 Indianapolis 500, the 
owner lost $800,000 when both Cheever and teammate Robby Unser 
wrecked at Dover. But the physical demands created by 24 degrees of 
banking in the turns and 9 degrees on the straightaways concern 
Cheever the most. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're never truly flat with your steering wheel, never on  
center,'' he said. ``It takes a lot of effort, and at the end of 
the day you're spent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because his fastest lap, posted at 182.066 mph, was second only  
to points leader Scott Goodyear, Cheever spent no time worrying 
about his Infiniti engine -- the only power plant of its kind in the 
IRL. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are definitely in better shape horsepower-wise now than we  
were at this time last year,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether that newfound power will be enough to outrun Goodyear is  
unknown. His Aurora engine took him around the track on his fastest 
lap in 19.476 seconds, at 182.315 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	``The track was very fast, and much better than it was last  
year,'' Goodyear said of the smoothed-out surface. ``We ran in some 
close contact, and the car seems OK.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That was somewhat of a relief to Goodyear, the only two-time  
winner on the circuit this year. He had to make a change early into 
the morning practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``The car we initially came here to run, unfortunately, I had  
problems with it,'' he said. ``It didn't feel right on the first 
two or three warmup laps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He pitted twice, making chassis adjustments both times to his  
Aurora-powered G Force. 
</P>
<P>
	``We looked for things and couldn't find them, so we had to put  
the backup car out, and only got about 10 minutes in the early 
session,'' he said. ``But things went well in the last session, and 
we're quite pleased.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Third-fastest was defending race champion Scott Sharp, a victory  
short of becoming the first IRL driver to win five times in his 
career. His Dallara-Aurora went 182.030. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Dismore, Sharp's Kelley Racing teammate, was fourth-fastest  
at 181.938, followed by the Dallara-Aurora of Hollansworth, who 
went 181.378. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
