<DOCNO> APW19990731.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 17:34:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Passes Tax Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans pushed their $792 billion tax cut  
through the Senate on Friday, courting a classic veto struggle this 
fall with President Clinton and Democrats who claim the measure 
shortchanges Medicare and other domestic programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote was 57-43 -- largely along party lines -- in favor of the  
GOP plan. The 10-year measure includes broad-based tax relief as 
well as provisions designed to address the so-called marriage 
penalty and make it easier to accumulate retirement savings and pay 
for education. 
</P>
<P>
	Passage was followed by the beginning of efforts at forging a  
quick House-Senate compromise. Congressional GOP leaders hope to 
speed the final measure through both houses next week, although it 
won't be sent to Clinton until after Labor Day. 
</P>
<P>
	That would leave time for the GOP rank and file to trumpet the  
benefits of tax cuts during Congress' long August break. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to cut taxes and the president wants to spend it,''  
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said of projected 
federal surpluses. ``That's what this fighting is all about. We are 
determined to give working Americans the tax relief they are 
entitled to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton wasted little time renewing his oft-stated veto threat.  
``The Republican tax cut is so large it would undo our fiscal 
discipline and imperil our prosperity,'' he said in a written 
statement. ``It would crowd out our commitments to pay down the 
debt, to save Social Security and to strengthen and modernize 
Medicare with a long overdue prescription drug benefit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate measure includes a reduction from 15 percent to 14  
percent in the lowest personal income tax bracket, effective in 
2001. Beginning in 2006, it would gradually shift some income 
currently taxed at 28 percent into that lower bracket. 
</P>
<P>
	It also includes provisions to reduce the marriage penalty, in  
part by slowly raising the standard deduction for married couples 
to double the amount allowed for individuals. Individuals currently 
may claim $4,300, and couples $7,200. 
</P>
<P>
	Moments before final passage, the measure was amended to let  
investors exclude from taxes the first $1,000 in long-term capital 
gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the bill, more students would be allowed to deduct the  
interest on their education loans; limits on deductible 
contributions to individual retirement accounts would rise 
gradually to $5,000, and there would be liberalized tax incentives 
for individual and corporate donors to charities. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also would create a new deduction for the cost of  
long-term care insurance, and raise the estate tax exemption -- 
already scheduled to increase to $1 million -- up to $1.5 million in 
2007. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout three days of debate on the Senate floor, Republicans  
said their budget would set aside the vast bulk of projected 
surpluses for Social Security. The tax cuts, they stressed, would 
consume less than 24 cents of each dollar of predicted surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	``It helps the family and it helps the country,'' said Sen.  
William V. Roth, R-Del., chairman of the Finance Committee and 
architect of the legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	But Democrats and the president contended the GOP bill would dip  
into Social Security surpluses beginning in 2005, and leave little 
or nothing for other domestic programs. They also said that by 
providing tax cuts based on economic forecasts that might not 
materialize, the Republicans were risking a return to the days of 
large federal deficits. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is another riverboat gamble with the American economy,''  
said Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., in an echo of the rhetoric used in 
the early 1980s when Republicans cut taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats countered with a smaller tax cut of $290 billion,  
which was rejected earlier in the week. Efforts to fashion a 
bipartisan compromise at $500 billion collapsed Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	A final compromise is still a possibility at year's end, but the  
immediate prospect is for a veto confrontation driven by competing 
readings of the electorate's wishes 15 months before the next 
elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans, who called their measure the Taxpayer Refund Act of  
1999, hope they can force Clinton to bend to their wishes on tax 
cuts, and say the president and other Democrats will pay a 
political price otherwise. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats, meanwhile, believe they can frame the debate as a  
choice between risky, overlarge tax cuts on one side, and the fate 
of Medicare and other politically popular programs on the other. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout the three days of floor debate, both sides sought to  
shore up potential weaknesses in their position. For their part, 
Republicans parried Democratic claims about Medicare by pledging to 
address the issue of prescription drugs this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats abandoned Clinton's initial approach of targeted tax  
relief in favor of broad-based tax cuts, although on a far smaller 
scale than the GOP wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	With an eye on the 2000 elections, when eight first-term  
Republican senators will seek new terms, Democrats forced a series 
of politically charged votes, including one on a proposal to reduce 
the tax cut to make room for prescription drug benefits for 
Medicare recipients. The amendment failed. 
</P>
<P>
	On final passage, the bill was supported by 52 Republicans, Sen.  
Bob Smith, I-N.H., and Democrats Mary Landrieu and John Breaux of 
Louisiana, Bob Kerrey of Nebraska and Robert Torricelli of New 
Jersey. In opposition, there were 43 Democrats and two Republicans, 
George Voinovich of Ohio and Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference, Lott and House Speaker Dennis Hastert,  
R-Ill., outlined an ambitious schedule that calls for a compromise 
by Tuesday, with final votes in the two chambers by the end of next 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	There are numerous differences between the bills. One is a  
House-passed provision that calls for a 10 percent across-the-board 
income tax cut rather than the reduced income tax bracket the 
Senate approved. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott told reporters ``there's a lot of support'' among Senate  
Republicans for an across-the-board cut, adding, ``That is the 
fairest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It will fall to Lott and Hastert to prod the chairmen of the  
tax-writing committees, Roth and Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, to 
avoid prolonged haggling that would slow the broader GOP political 
strategy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
