<HEADLINE> Galaxy 1, Fire 0 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Simon Elliott's goal just before halftime  
Saturday lifted the Los Angeles Galaxy to a 1-0 MLS victory over 
the Chicago Fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Elliott's 20-foot boot sailed over the head of Fire goaltender  
Zach Thornton and into the net with 3:24 left in the first half. 
Clint Mathias and Mauricio Cienfuegos assisted on the goal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fire had chances to tie the game in the second half but most  
of their shots missed by several yards. Los Angeles goaltender 
Kevin Hartman, who leads the league with seven shutouts this 
season, was forced to make a spectacular save on a shot from Josh 
Wolff in the 77th minute. 
</P>
<P>
	The Galaxy (12-8, 30 points) moved into second place ahead of  
Chicago (10-9, 28) in the Western Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the Galaxy's third game in seven days but it was the Fire  
who came out flat. They were outshot 8-3 in the first half. 
</P>
<P>
	Luckily for the players, temperatures cooled from a high of 102  
degrees on Friday to the relatively comfortable 80s Saturday in 
Soldier Field at the city's downtown lakefront. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fire entered the game 4-1 at home against Los Angeles.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
