<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crane Collapse Cause Disputed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Two companies involved in the construction of  
Miller Park have come to two different conclusions as to what 
caused the fatal crane collapse at the partially-built ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitsubishi Heavy Industries of America, which is building the  
stadium's retractable roof, is implicating the 567-foot crane. 
There seems to have been a critical failure as it lifted a 400-ton 
roof piece July 14, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Everything seems to point to structural failure, said Patrick  
Knight, Mitsubishi's attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	``In all honesty, I think weather is going to be shown to be a  
zero factor in this whole thing,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But crane owner and operator, Neil F. Lampson Inc., blames the  
lift that killed three ironworkers on high winds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really think that, quite frankly ... that it was an act of  
God that that wind came up and gusted the way it did,'' Lampson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Lampson also blamed the accident on inaccurate estimates of  
how far the gusts would cause the piece of roof being hauled by the 
crane to sway in the wind. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everybody involved with that lift underestimated the  
sail area on that load and how much effect those gusting winds were 
going to have on it,'' Lampson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nobody's fault. It was just underestimated, and nobody  
knows what the speed of the wind gusts were at the top of that 
building,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	There is no evidence that the crane malfunctioned, said Don  
Carlson, Lampson's attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	Both companies agree that even when the lift was underway, no  
one at the site spoke out against continuing in the face of high 
winds. 
</P>
<P>
	The local ironworkers union will wait until the Milwaukee County  
District Attorney's office determines the cause of the crash before 
coming out with its version of the fatal lift, said Brent Emons, 
business manager for Iron Workers Local 8. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, sorting out responsibility for the accident that  
killed three ironworkers is moving from the ballpark to law offices 
and courtrooms. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
