<HEADLINE> Martha Stewart Co. Files for IPO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- You can buy Martha Stewart books, magazines or  
home products. And soon, you'll be able to buy stock in her 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, the ubiquitous queen of better homemaking, cooking and  
gardening, is planning to raise some $100 million in an initial 
public offering of shares in her company, Martha Stewart Living 
Omnimedia Inc., according to documents filed Thursday with the 
Securities and Exchange Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart would retain control of the company, which had $180  
million in revenue and a net profit of $23.8 million in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's centerpiece business is the monthly magazine  
Martha Stewart Living, but its television merchandising and 
Internet businesses have experienced strong growth. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it may use $42 million of the proceeds to buy  
out the remaining 6.2 percent stake held by Time Warner, an initial 
backer of Stewart's magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the documents say a 5 percent stake in the company will be  
sold for $25 million to Kleiner, Perkins, Caufield and Buyers, a 
venture capital firm in San Francisco. The firm will also have the 
right to 15 percent of any publicly traded class of stock issued in 
an Internet business for an additional $21 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The company expects to be listed on the New York Stock Exchange.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
