<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 18:16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  $54 Million McNabb Misses Practice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) -- Donovan McNabb spent his first day as the  
highest-paid player in Philadelphia Eagles history in much the same 
fashion as the previous week or so. 
</P>
<P>
	No helmet. No pads. No football.  
</P>
<P>
	More waiting.  
</P>
<P>
	McNabb's seven-year, $54 million contract was so long and  
complicated that by the time the NFL let him sign it, it was too 
late to join his new team on the field. 
</P>
<P>
	McNabb finally put his signature on the 32-page contract  
Saturday afternoon, but not until his teammates had finished two 
grueling workouts in near 100-degree heat. 
</P>
<P>
	Just like the discordant boos he received on draft day and the  
controversial holdout that followed, it wasn't the kind of debut 
McNabb had envisioned. 
</P>
<P>
	``Donovan will perform so well that looking back on this moment  
today, in 100 degrees here, 15 years from now we can count the 
number of Super Bowls we've won together,'' Eagles owner Jeffrey 
Lurie said. ``Not the number of days held out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McNabb's journey from No. 2 draft pick to official pro football  
player has been a strange one, for sure, especially in the past 72 
hours. 
</P>
<P>
	After missing the first several days of workouts due to a  
contract squabble, McNabb then looked on helplessly as his agent 
lit a firecracker of controversy under the talks with an assertion 
that race was playing a role. 
</P>
<P>
	He sat in a plane at the Atlanta airport for three hours while  
trying to get to Philadelphia, then arrived at Veterans Stadium 
after midnight. McNabb and his teammates had every reason to 
believe he'd be doing what he does best -- throwing a football -- a 
few hours later at Lehigh University. 
</P>
<P>
	But McNabb was excused from the morning workout, staying at his  
Cherry Hill, N.J., home until mid-morning while several teammates 
were knocked out of practice with heat exhaustion. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, there was little time for McNabb to have a physical,  
and there were plenty of details to work out with the league. Joe 
Banner, the Eagles' executive vice president, said NFL lawyers 
required some language in the contract reworded. 
</P>
<P>
	``Donovan is not allowed to sign the contract until it's all OK,  
and he is not allowed to practice until he signs the contract,'' 
Banner said. 
</P>
<P>
	McNabb showed up for an afternoon news conference toting a  
playbook under his arm. He's going to need it. Starting quarterback 
Doug Pederson already knows coach Andy Reid's offense, and he's 
been practicing while McNabb has been sitting idle. 
</P>
<P>
	``The perception is that because he's the No. 1 pick and a high  
pick, his talent is going to allow him to walk in and play 
immediately,'' offensive coordinator Rod Dowhower said. ``Reality 
is, Doug knows this offense. Doug knows how to execute this 
offense. The rest of the offensive players need to catch up with 
Doug.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McNabb, seated next to Lurie, didn't blink when the owner called  
him ``a potential franchise quarterback.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Finally, it's over, and I can participate with the rest of the  
team,'' McNabb said. ``I don't put any pressure on myself that's 
not needed. Ever since I was a member of the Syracuse Orangemen, I 
had the label as being `The Man' as you may call it. That didn't 
bother me at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McNabb didn't seem concerned about the time he's missed, calling  
his first NFL training camp ``more of a touch-up, a deal that all 
quarterbacks need.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not what Dowhower or Reid would want to hear.  
</P>
<P>
	``The only way to learn is to do,'' Dowhower said. ``That goes  
for everybody. ... This is professional football. There's a certain 
reality to it. If you want to make a lot of money, you've got to be 
the starter, at some point. Sometimes, you walk into a lot of money 
and you're not the starter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New details emerged Saturday about McNabb's contract and how it  
compares with deals given to other top quarterbacks like Tim Couch, 
the No. 1 pick this year, and Peyton Manning and Ryan Leaf, the top 
two picks in last year's draft. 
</P>
<P>
	McNabb got an $11.3 million signing bonus, but the deal does not  
include the voidable years or buy-back clause for which Smith had 
pushed. That means McNabb cannot earn a second signing bonus, and 
it could hinder agent Leigh Steinberg's attempt to get that kind of 
deal for No. 3 pick Akili Smith of Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	A highly placed NFL source who has seen McNabb's contract said  
it could be worth $53.7 million if he achieves all the bonuses and 
so-called escalator clauses. 
</P>
<P>
	The source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said McNabb  
would earn significant bonus money if he's in the top eight in the 
league in any of 4-5 passing categories in any of the first four 
years. The bonuses are higher if he's in the top five, and even 
higher if he's in the top three in any category during any season. 
</P>
<P>
	Some bonus money also is tied to making the playoffs or Pro  
Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	Escalated salaries in years 5-7 of the contract would kick in if  
McNabb achieves certain passing statistics that are very attainable 
if he simply gets playing time. 
</P>
<P>
	The source, who is also familiar with the contracts signed by  
Couch, Manning and Leaf, said McNabb ranked behind Couch in total 
value and ahead of Manning and Leaf. 
</P>
<P>
	If he achieves all the incentives in his contract, Couch could  
earn as much as $59.4 million for seven years, the source said. 
Manning could make $48 million for six years and Leaf could get a 
little more than $31 million for five years by achieving all the 
incentives. 
  	   	
</P>
