<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies Sign Cuban Outfielder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Cuban outfielder Josue Perez, whose contract with  
Los Angeles was voided by the commissioner's office June 25, signed 
with the Philadelphia Phillies on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Perez agreed to a one-year, $850,000 contract that includes an  
invitation to the Phillies major-league camp next spring. 
</P>
<P>
	Perez and another Cuban, first baseman Juan Carlos Diaz, were  
declared free agents June 25 after the commissioner's office ruled 
the Dodgers violated rules barring scouting in Cuba and engineering 
defections. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a continuing effort to broaden our scouting, we felt it was  
important to get into the Cuban market,'' Phillies general manager 
Ed Wade said. ``This fits into that frame of thinking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perez, 21, was playing with Vero Beach in the Class A Florida  
State League when his contract with the Dodgers was voided. In 62 
games there, he hit .279 with two homers, 22 RBIs and 14 steals. 
</P>
<P>
	After signing with the Dodgers prior to the 1998 season, Perez  
played in the Dominican Summer League, where he hit .335 with eight 
doubles, seven triples, two homers, 17 RBIs and 24 steals in 167 
at-bats. 
</P>
<P>
	``Perez is a true center-fielder with excellent speed,'' said  
Mike Arbuckle, the Phillies scouting director. ``On offense, he's a 
switch-hitter that is good from both sides of the plate. We see him 
as a base stealer with a chance to make things happen.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
