<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 08:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Examples of Assigned Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	In the Watergate and Iran-Contra scandals, chief judges at the  
federal courthouse in Washington made special assignments of 
important cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge John Sirica, a Republican appointee of President  
Eisenhower, assigned himself two cases stemming from the Watergate 
break-in and the subsequent cover-up by President Nixon's top 
aides. The trials resulted in guilty verdicts for all but one 
defendant. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Iran-Contra affair, chief judge Aubrey Robinson assigned  
important cases to two of the most experienced judges at the 
courthouse, Gerhard Gesell and Harold Greene, appointees of earlier 
Democratic administrations. Oliver North was convicted of three 
felonies in the trial in Gesell's courtroom and President Reagan's 
national security adviser, John Poindexter, was convicted of five 
felonies in the trial that Greene presided over. Convictions in 
both cases were overturned on appeal. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 18:22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  20th Swiss Disaster Victim Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INTERLAKEN, Switzerland (AP) -- The body of one of the last  
tourists missing in a Swiss Alps river flood was found, bringing 
the death count from the canyoning disaster to 20, Bern state 
police said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rescuers using underwater cameras located the body late Friday  
night, 207 feet deep in Lake Brienz, a few miles downstream from 
the scene of the accident. 
</P>
<P>
	The tragedy occurred when unexpected floods swept through the  
canyon and engulfed tourists and guides bodysurfing feet-first 
through foaming waters of Saxeten Brook, near Interlaken Alpine 
resort. 
</P>
<P>
	One person was still missing. Police said they would suspend the  
search until Monday to give exhausted rescuers a chance to recover. 
The rescue effort would continue to concentrate on Lake Brienz. 
</P>
<P>
	The tourists were ``canyoning,'' a new extreme sport in which  
participants slide, jump or rappel down waterfalls and mountain 
streams into gorges without rafts. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said Friday they were investigating whether five  
guides on the expedition, hosted by Adventure World, were guilty of 
negligent homicide for not taking notice of a pending storm, which 
caused the floods. 
</P>
<P>
	Another three guides who went with the group of 45 vacationers  
were among those killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Police so far have released the names of nine victims. Relatives  
are still helping identify the badly battered bodies. 
</P>
<P>
	A memorial service is scheduled for Thursday in Interlaken.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0177 </DOCNO>
