<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 21:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reds Get Juan Guzman From Orioles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- This time, the Cincinnati Reds got a pitcher  
instead of trading one away. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds got starter Juan Guzman from the Baltimore Orioles for  
two minor league pitchers and cash late Saturday night, a sign of 
how far they've come. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past two years, the Reds made news by trading starter  
Dave Burba and closer Jeff Shaw for prospects. This time, the 
small-market surprise of the season showed it is serious about 
winning. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all knew we needed pitching and the people in this  
organization are dedicated to trying to win,'' general manager Jim 
Bowden said. ``No one thought a payroll in the $30 million range 
would have a winning record let alone be two games out of the 
playoffs (as a wild card) right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles got minor league pitchers B.J. Ryan and Jacobo  
Sequea and agreed to send the Reds an undisclosed amount of cash to 
pay part of Guzman's $5.25 million salary. 
</P>
<P>
	It marked the second year in a row that Guzman, 32, was traded  
on July 31. The Toronto Blue Jays sent him to the Orioles for 
pitcher Nerio Rodriguez and minor league outfielder Shannon Carter 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds have beaten the odds by staying in first or second  
place in the NL Central since June 16 despite a small payroll -- $33 
million on opening day. They were looking for another starter for 
their injury-thinned rotation, but weren't about to give up top 
prospects or add to their payroll substantially. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Orioles agreed to help pay Guzman's salary, the deal  
was done. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did not want to trade anyone on our 25-man roster. We  
didn't want to trade anyone from our bullpen,'' Bowden said. 
</P>
<P>
	Guzman will be a free agent after this season. He went 5-9 with  
a 4.18 ERA and one complete game in 21 starts for the Orioles. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds felt they had to upgrade their rotation, which has been  
their main weakness all season. The problem was that they didn't 
want to trade any of their top prospects or substantially add to 
their payroll. 
</P>
<P>
	Heading into their 11-1 loss to San Francisco on Saturday, Reds  
starters had pitched only 554 innings, tied with Minnesota for 
fewest in the major leagues. On average, a Reds starter lasts 5 1-3 
innings. 
</P>
<P>
	The bullpen has saved the club so far, turning in a 2.92 ERA  
that is the best in the majors. But it also has thrown 354 1-3 
innings, second-most in the majors. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we get our starter to go six or seven innings, we feel we  
have the best bullpen in the league and a chance to win every 
game,'' Bowden said. ``We're getting a starting pitcher who's given 
the Orioles six or seven innings nearly every time out, especially 
since the middle of June.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Guzman had a 3.16 ERA in June and a 3.62 ERA in July.  
</P>
<P>
	Ryan, a left-hander, was the Reds' 17th-round pick in last  
year's draft and made a remarkably quick rise through the farm 
system. Ryan, 23, made it to Double-A last season and represented 
the Reds in the All-Star Futures Game at Boston this July. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds called him up from Triple-A last Monday, giving him the  
quickest rise through Cincinnati's farm system since C.J. Nitkowski 
made his debut in 1995, one year after being drafted. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan made one appearance for the Reds, then was optioned to  
Triple-A on Friday to open a roster spot for Denny Neagle. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have (left-handers) Gabe White and Dennys Reyes in the  
bullpen, and you've got to give up something to get something,'' 
Bowden said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sequea, 17, was 4-6 with a 4.92 ERA in 16 starts for Class A  
Rockford. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
