<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Firm Won't Appeal Paula Jones Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Paula Jones' law firm won't seek more  
than the $79,999 it was awarded for fees incurred due to President 
Clinton's false testimony about his relationship with Monica 
Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision not to appeal by the Dallas-based firm of Rader,  
Campbell, Fisher &AMP; Pyke all but wraps up Mrs. Jones' dispute with 
Clinton, who has said he is willing to comply with the court order 
issued Thursday by U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright. 
</P>
<P>
	``We thought that more attorneys fees were caused by his lying,  
but Judge Wright didn't see it that way and so it's over,'' lawyer 
Wes Holmes said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The head of The Rutherford Institute, a Virginia-based  
conservative group that also worked for Mrs. Jones, said he likely 
would decide next week whether to appeal the institute's $9,485 
award, but would prefer to let the case end. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're weighing the money, the attorney time, the chance factor  
with the court and then probably as big of a factor: Do we want to 
be in this case for another year?'' said Rutherford President John 
W. Whitehead. 
</P>
<P>
	The law firm had sought $437,825 and The Rutherford Institute  
had sought $58,533. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's attorneys have said the president will not appeal the  
$90,686 payment he was ordered to compensate for legal costs 
related to what the judge called his ``false, misleading and 
evasive answers'' in his January 1998 deposition. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's denials of a sexual relationship with Ms. Lewinsky led  
to his impeachment by the House. The Senate acquitted him after a 
trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright dismissed Mrs. Jones' sexual harassment lawsuit April 1,  
1998, but Clinton agreed to an $850,000 settlement after Mrs. Jones 
appealed the dismissal. Clinton admitted no wrongdoing. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 02:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Glimpses of Shooting Victims' Lives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Charles Allen Tenenbaum discussed buying burial  
plots with his wife only last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think he had a premonition of anything,'' said Rabbi  
S. Robert Ichay. ``But he knew that life was not always the way we 
imagine it, or the way we would like it to be -- that things could 
happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Tenenbaum was the first of nine people who died in a  
shooting rampage to be buried. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 1,000 people attended Tenenbaum's funeral, hastily  
arranged in keeping with the Jewish law forbidding funerals on the 
Sabbath, which began at sunset. 
</P>
<P>
	The Great Savings Grocery, the family-owned grocery where  
Tenenbaum worked, was closed the day after he and eight others were 
fatally shot by Mark O. Barton. Like Barton, Tenenbaum, 48, was a 
day trader at one of the stock brokerages where the slaughter 
occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, a stream of mourners gathered at the store to pay  
respects. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody in the neighborhood liked him,'' said Thomas Glass,  
who recently retired after working as a butcher there for 33 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Ichay said Tenenbaum was planning his first pilgrimage to Israel  
next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the victims, like 36-year-old Texas native Kevin Dial,  
worked for the firms that Barton targeted. Others, like 52-year-old 
Dean Delawalla, were customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Police would not specify which victim was where or doing what,  
but friends and witnesses provided glimpses into their lives and 
last hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Dial, the son of former Pittsburgh Steelers and Dallas Cowboys  
wide receiver Buddy Dial, was office manager at Momentum 
Securities, where the shooting began. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kevin was the light of his life,'' said Tom Alexandar,  
attorney for Buddy Dial, who is recovering from a stroke. ``He was 
a very, very bright, wonderful young man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Blaier, an Allegiance Telecom sales manager who worked down  
the hall from Dial, called him ``probably one of the happiest guys 
I ever saw.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another victim, Edward Quinn, was a 58-year-old father of three  
and day trader. He was only a couple of years into his retirement 
after decades with United Parcel Service, where he last served as 
southeast regional director for security and loss prevention. 
Friends and neighbors said Quinn seemed to have three passions, 
beside his family: his lawn, flyfishing and golf. 
</P>
<P>
	``When he retired his plan was to begin traveling the world and  
playing at all the great old courses across the planet,'' said Ken 
Sternad, a UPS spokesman who had known Quinn for 10 years. ``That 
was his goal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just three weeks ago, Quinn traveled to St. Louis after the  
birth of his first grandson, Bryce. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was a tremendous family man,'' son Michael Quinn said  
through sobs. ``Would bend over backwards in any way, shape or form 
to help his family out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the victims had nothing to do with the stock market at  
all. 
</P>
<P>
	Vadewattee Muralidhara, 44, had just moved to Atlanta from tiny  
Swainsboro three months ago with her pediatrician husband. The 
soft-spoken homemaker and mother of two college-aged children was 
at the office building to take a computer course, said her friend 
Peggy Corbin. 
</P>
<P>
	``The one thing I would say is she was a very sweet-spirited  
person,'' Corbin said. ``Just very dedicated to her children. They 
were her life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Until a couple of months ago, victim Scott Webb, 30, lived with  
his father in Chesterfield, an upscale community in west St. Louis 
County, Mo. Neighbors said the two biked and jogged together. 
</P>
<P>
	Also killed were 42-year-old Russell Brown of Cumming, Ga.;  
Joseph J. Dessert, 60, Marietta, Ga.; and Jamshid Havash, 44, of 
Dunwoody, Ga. 
</P>
<P>
	Delawalla doted on his son, Faisal, 15, encouraging him to play  
hockey, soccer, tennis and football, said his brother, Fred 
Delawalla. 
</P>
<P>
	``You never think (something) like this could strike this close  
until it happens and ... all of a sudden the realities sort of come 
to the surface,'' he said. ``That you're living in a glass world 
here.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
