<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Cool Air, Rain Bring Relief from Heat  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Raging heat that has been blamed for 144 deaths  
across the nation is still a problem for much of the country, but 
slightly cooler weather is edging into the Midwest, bringing rain 
and storms to several states. Sporadic heavy rain and thunderstorms 
swept through parts of Iowa, Missouri, Michigan, Kansas and 
Indiana. In Chicago, however, 26 more people have died from the 
heat, pushing Illinois' heat-related death toll to 50. 

</P>
<P>
	Man Charged in Woodstock Sex Crime  
</P>
<P>
	ROME, N.Y. (AP) -- A 26-year-old man was arrested and charged  
with sex crimes for an alleged assault on a 15-year-old girl as 
fires raged in the final hours of Woodstock. Timothy A. Weeden, a 
state prison guard from Rome, was arrested early Monday soon after 
the alleged assault and was indicted Tuesday on charges of 
first-degree sodomy and sexual abuse, third-degree sodomy, and 
endangering the welfare of a child. 

</P>
<P>
	1,010 Gypsies Seek Refuge in Italy  
</P>
<P>
	BARI, Italy (AP) -- More than 1,000 illegal immigrants traveling  
in an old tugboat landed in southern Italy today under Italian 
military escort, the biggest single arrival in a weeks-long influx 
of Gypsies from Yugoslavia. Authorities said 489 of the 1,010 
aboard were children. The would-be refugees burst into applause 
when they docked at the southern port of Bari. Thousands of Gypsies 
have landed illegally in Italy since the war in Kosovo ended, with 
many saying they were fleeing revenge attacks by ethnic Albanians 
in the Serbian province. 

</P>
<P>
	Serbian Church Damaged in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A NATO spokesman said a large  
explosion damaged a Serbian Orthodox church in the center of 
Kosovo's capital early Sunday. The Hram Sveti Spasa church was 
under construction and had not yet opened. Despite 35,000 NATO 
troops, violence has continued in Kosovo. The blast occurred after 
British Prime Minister Tony Blair visited Pristina on Saturday and 
urged ethnic Albanians to live in peace with rival Serbs. Officials 
did not know what caused the blast or who was involved. 

</P>
<P>
	Heat May Be Factor in Fatal Plane Crash  
</P>
<P>
	COTTRELLVILLE TOWNSHIP, Mich. (AP) -- Federal investigators say  
heat may have been a factor in the plane crash that killed nine 
skydivers and a pilot today. The National Transportation Safety 
Board says hot weather and high humidity can make takeoff more 
difficult. Temperatures today reached into the 80s. The plane, a 
twin-engine Beech King Air 200, came down in a grassy field near 
Marine City Airport, about 40 miles north of Detroit, police said. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Sets Deadline for Tax Cut Deal  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans have set a Tuesday deadline to  
sculpt a $792 billion tax cut compromise that can clear the House 
and Senate by week's end and set the stage for a fall veto showdown 
with the White House. With the hurry-up compromise effort scarcely 
under way, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott criticized President 
Clinton for opposing the measure. ``We should reduce taxes, with 
the largest middle-class tax cut since Ronald Reagan was 
president,'' Lott said in today's weekly GOP radio address. 

</P>
<P>
	Europeans Skeptical on Balkans Pact  
</P>
<P>
	SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- Europeans reacted largely  
with skepticism to the Sarajevo summit on Balkan stability with 
commentators suggesting today that little was accomplished at the 
one-day conference. Most European countries shied away from 
pledging funds for the peace reforms before another conference is 
held later in the year. Balkan states, which stand to gain 
economically if they can show they are committed to democracy, were 
more positive. 

</P>
<P>
	Deals Shape Up As Deadline Looms  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Oakland Athletics shuffled their staff,  
getting Kevin Appier from the Kansas City Royals and sending Billy 
Taylor to the New York Mets. The Mets also made a five-player swap 
with Colorado, getting outfielder Darryl Hamilton and reliever 
Chuck McElroy for outfielder Brian McRae and two minor leaguers. 
Also moving to New York -- again -- was Jim Leyritz, a 
former-postseason hero for the Yankees who was reacquired from the 
San Diego Padres for a minor league pitcher. Oakland traded three 
young pitchers for Appier: Blake Stein, Jeff D'Amico and Brad 
Rigby. Oakland, 3 1/2 games behind Toronto in the AL wild-card hunt, 
got pitcher Jason Isringhausen for the 37-year-old Taylor, who has 
26 saves. 


</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  
  	   	
</P>
