<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Compton on Pole for NASCAR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUDON, N.H. (AP) -- Stacy Compton, who'll start Sunday's NASCAR  
Craftsman Truck Series Pennzoil 200 from the pole position, is 
running out of chances to close the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Compton, winner of his fourth pole of the season in Friday's  
qualifying at New Hampshire International Raceway, has yet to 
parlay a single lap's speed into a victory as the season moves into 
its final nine races. 
</P>
<P>
	He's been close but, without wins, also has began to lose  
contact with the tour's championship leaders. Compton, whose Dodge 
qualified at 126.745 mph to edge Impact Motorsports partner Randy 
Tolsma for the pole, is 182 points behind leader Jack Sprague and 
97 behind second-place Greg Biffle. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's race isn't a must-win situation. But it's close.  
</P>
<P>
	``If we'd have been struggling, sure, it would be aggravating,''  
agreed Compton, who counts two second-place finishes among eight 
top-five efforts in the season's first 16 races. ``We've run up 
front every week. We just need a little luck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Compton also qualified first a week ago at Michigan Speedway,  
where he was in contention until damaging his truck's radiator in 
the waning laps. He finished sixth. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coming up short, when we knew we had a truck that could win,  
that was aggravating,'' said Compton, who finished 15th in last 
year's Pennzoil 200 when he qualified 23rd. The two-time series 
winner hasn't won in 25 starts. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's qualifying marked the second time in 1999 that Compton  
and Tolsma share the front row. Tolsma, whose nearly identical 
Dodge was nine-thousandths of a second slower than Compton with a 
speed of 126.707, was the pole winner in the year's opening race at 
Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	Tolsma is also looking to break a lengthy losing streak, a run  
of 46 races dating to October 1997 in Bakersfield, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending series champion and 1996 Pennzoil 200 winner Ron  
Hornaday qualified a Chevrolet third at 126.194 mph. He'll share 
row two of Sunday's race with Rick Crawford, whose Ford lapped at 
126.115. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Harvick, who has three runnerup finishes in 1999, grabbed  
fifth in a Ford at 126.098. The year's hottest competitor, Biffle, 
was sixth in a Ford at 126.069. Biffle has won two races in a row 
and four of the last six. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprague was seventh in a Chevrolet, followed by Rob Morgan, Mike  
Bliss and Dennis Setzer. Last year's Pennzoil 200 pole winner, Mike 
Wallace, qualified 11th. 
</P>
<P>
	Also making the 33-driver field was NASCAR Winston Cup veteran  
Joe Ruttman, who'll start 14th in a Dodge. Last year's race winner, 
Andy Houston, starts 16th, just ahead of Jay Sauter, who won the 
1997 event at the 1.058-mile superspeedway. 
</P>
<P>
	Former NFL coach Jerry Glanville, recovered from injuries during  
qualifying for last week's NASCAR Busch Series race at Colorado 
Springs, Colo., starts 29th. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
