<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Hurt by Illegal Gas Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia must crack down on illegal gasoline exports  
that are contributing to gas shortages and rising prices, the 
country's fuel and energy minister said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Viktor Kalyuzhny said the main reason for the shortage is rising  
global oil prices, which have prompted Russian oil companies to 
funnel their goods to lucrative foreign markets instead of selling 
them at home, where prices are lower. 
</P>
<P>
	But in addition to the illegal exports, small traders are also  
buying gasoline and secretly exporting ``significant volumes,'' 
Kalyuzhny said, according to Russian television and news agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	Kalyuzhny spoke during a visit to the Black Sea resort of Sochi,  
which has been hit particularly hard by gasoline shortages. 
</P>
<P>
	He and other officials blamed Sochi's problems on a dramatic  
rise in tourists this year. Many Russians hurt by last year's 
financial meltdown are abandoning expensive foreign resorts for 
cheaper vacation spots like Sochi. 
</P>
<P>
	But the shortage may also be acute in Sochi because the region  
is close to Black Sea ports used to ship gasoline illegally to 
foreign buyers, analysts say. 
</P>
<P>
	The gasoline shortage puts the cash-starved government in a  
precarious spot. Oil exports are the government's main source of 
hard currency and rallying oil prices bring a welcome boost in tax 
revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	But with parliamentary elections in December, the government is  
keen to avoid public anger over rising gasoline prices. It has 
threatened to restrict oil exports to guarantee enough gasoline for 
domestic markets. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 14:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
