<DOCNO> APW19990731.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 16:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Padres' Leyritz Returns to Yanks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Jim Leyritz is going back to the New York  
Yankees, meaning he once again could be hitting clutch October home 
runs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees reacquired the former World Series hero by sending  
minor league right-hander Geraldo Padua to the San Diego Padres on 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Leyritz denied requesting a trade to New York, but thanked the  
Padres for sending him there. 
</P>
<P>
	``They could have traded me anywhere, but it shows the class of  
this organization to give me another opportunity back in New 
York,'' said the 35-year-old utility player, who will be eligible 
for free agency after this season. 
</P>
<P>
	There's a big reason the Padres had more than just the Yankees  
calling about Leyritz. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a good hitter and he loves the spotlight,'' Yankees  
manager Joe Torre said before Saturday's game in Boston. ``That's 
half the battle when you've got ability.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of Leyritz's 12 postseason hits, seven are homers. Four have  
come after the sixth inning. 
</P>
<P>
	None was bigger than his three-run homer off Atlanta's Mark  
Wohlers that helped change the course of the 1996 World Series. His 
eighth-inning shot tied Game 4 at 6, and the Yankees went on to win 
in 10 innings and defeated the Braves in six games. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you play for teams that win, you get that little fire,''  
said Leyritz, who will join the Yankees in Boston for Sunday 
night's game. ``Playing in New York for as many years as I did, 
it's almost like being in the World Series every day. I thrived on 
it while I was there. My focus just seems to get better when the 
at-bat matters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees, who swept the Padres in last year's World Series,  
had the best record in the majors going into Saturday's games but 
lost to the Red Sox, 6-5. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a friend of all of ours,'' Yankees shortstop Derek Jeter  
said of Leyritz. ``He was part of the '96 team. He's valuable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leyritz's first dramatic playoff homer came in 1995, a two-run  
shot in the 15th inning at Yankee Stadium off Seattle's Tim Belcher 
that ended the longest AL division series game. 
</P>
<P>
	Leyritz began his career with the Yankees in 1990 and was traded  
to Anaheim in December 1996. He also played for Texas and Boston 
before being traded to San Diego on June 21, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	In last year's first-round playoff series, Leyritz homered in  
three straight games against the Houston Astros, providing the 
winning run in Game 3 and then connecting off Randy Johnson for a 
1-0 lead in the clinching fourth game. 
</P>
<P>
	He homered once in the NL championship series against Atlanta,  
but went 0-for-10 in the World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was terrific here,'' Padres general manager Kevin Towers  
said. ``He's a great player and had some big hits for us. I'm sure 
he'll be very successful for the New York Yankees.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leyritz broke a bone in his left hand June 22 and was activated  
from the disabled list Friday night. He admitted that he's only 
about 80 percent of full strength and is 10-12 days away from being 
able to catch. He can also play first or third base, or be used as 
the designated hitter. 
</P>
<P>
	Leyritz is hitting .239 with eight home runs and 21 RBIs. He won  
two of the Padres' first eight games this year with homers. 
</P>
<P>
	Leyritz's injury opened the way for the Padres to promote rookie  
catcher Ben Davis, who's been living up to his billing as the 
Padres' top non-pitching prospect. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't view this as just because we moved Jim Leyritz we're  
conceding the season and throwing in the towel,'' said Towers, 
whose club has gone from two games out of first place in the NL 
West to eight back after losing eight straight. 
</P>
<P>
	The Padres were attempting to trade for a third baseman before  
Saturday night's deadline. On Friday night, they designated 
struggling George Arias for assignment. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Padres can't land a third baseman, they'll take a look at  
Phil Nevin, the top pick in the June 1992 draft who's now with his 
fourth big league club, and outfielder Eric Owens. They also have 
Carlos Baerga. 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego has traded two catchers in six days for pitching  
prospects. On Monday, they sent Greg Myers to Atlanta for 
right-hander Doug Dent. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel we've added two very good arms to the system,'' Towers  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Padua, a 22-year-old from the Dominican Republic, was 9-4 with a  
2.86 ERA in 21 starts with Class A Greensboro. He was second in the 
South Atlantic League with 155 strikeouts in 139 2-3 innings, with 
only 35 walks. He'll report to Class A Rancho Cucamonga. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
