<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Braves Get Mulholland, Hernandez </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Atlanta Braves, facing a serious challenge in  
the NL East, acquired infielder Jose Hernandez and pitcher Terry 
Mulholland from the Chicago Cubs just before Saturday's midnight 
EDT trading deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves sent pitcher Micah Bowie, minor league pitcher Ruben  
Quevedo and a minor leaguer to be named later to the Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We made the deal with 30 seconds to go ... or less,'' said  
Braves general manager John Schuerholz, who talked with four or 
five teams during the night. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta dropped to second place in the NL East on Friday, the  
latest they've been out of first since 1994. The Braves regained 
the top spot by a half-game over the New York Mets with an 8-6 
victory Saturday night over the Philadelphia Phillies. 
</P>
<P>
	The Phillies are 5 1/2 games back.  
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez, who is hitting .272 with 15 homers and 43 RBIs,  
bolsters a lineup that has been without first baseman Andres 
Galarraga all season and learned Monday that catcher Javy Lopez 
would be out for the rest of the year with a knee injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Bobby Cox can use Hernandez at either second, short,  
third and the outfield. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you lose offensive production like we have with Galarraga  
and Lopez, it's hurtful,'' Schuerholz said. ``I don't mean to 
suggest that Hernandez will replace that. But it will give Bobby 
another weapon offensively.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez, 30, also provides insurance at short, where starter  
Walt Weiss has been plagued by leg problems since joining the 
Braves before the 1998 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Mulholland, who is 6-6 with a 5.15 ERA, adds depth to a pitching  
staff that has struggled to find a fifth starter and has managed to 
get by with a nondescript bullpen. The 36-year-old can start or 
relieve. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our people have high regard for his competitiveness and his  
ability to perform a variety of roles,'' Schuerholz said. ``He 
affords us some protection if John Smoltz's elbow bothers him the 
rest of the season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smoltz has been on the disabled list twice this season -- just  
one in a series of problems that have plagued a team seeking to 
extend its own record of seven straight postseason appearances. 
</P>
<P>
	It began in spring training when Galarraga was diagnosed with  
cancer in his back, forcing him to miss the season while undergoing 
treatment. Shortly afterward, closer Kerry Ligtenberg suffered a 
season-ending elbow injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Weiss and Smoltz have struggled with injuries all season, but at  
least they are still able to play. On Monday, the Braves learned 
that Lopez partially tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his 
right knee and 21-year-old fifth starter Odalis Perez tore the 
medial collateral ligament in his left elbow. Both needed 
season-ending operations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had to suffer through losses to some very key guys,''  
Schuerholz said. ``To get two players who have been productive and 
are very experienced will help make up for the loss of those 
guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bowie, 24, was 0-1 with a 13.50 ERA for the Braves after being  
called up recently from Triple-A Richmond. Quevedo, who is not on 
Atlanta's 40-man roster, was 6-5 with a 5.37 ERA in 21 games at 
Richmond. 
</P>
<P>
	Mulholland has another year on the contract that pays him $2.925  
million this season. Hernandez is making $2.4 million in the final 
year of his contract. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
