<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 18:21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 1,010 Gypsies Seek Refuge in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BARI, Italy (AP) -- More than 1,000 illegal immigrants in an old  
tugboat landed in southern Italy on Saturday under Italian military 
escort, the biggest single arrival in a weeks-long influx of 
Gypsies from Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said 489 of the 1,010 aboard were children. The  
would-be refugees burst into applause when they docked at the 
southern port of Bari. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of Gypsies have landed illegally in Italy since the  
war in Kosovo ended, with many saying they were fleeing revenge 
attacks by ethnic Albanians in the Serbian province. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Albanians are hunting us,'' one man, identified only as  
Ekrep, was quoted as telling Italy's ANSA news agency. ``We have 
nothing, we have no homes, we have nothing to eat, and above all, 
we're afraid. Afraid of being killed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Italy declared in mid-July it would treat the Gypsies as illegal  
immigrants rather than refugees, and return them immediately. But 
most have been taken to reception centers, which are often just 
first stops en route to points elsewhere in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	The new arrivals had left Friday from the coast of Montenegro,  
Serbia's smaller partner in the Yugoslav federation. 
</P>
<P>
	Once docked, the passengers were taken for medical examination  
and for identification and then on to reception centers. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities took into custody two men from Romania suspected of  
being immigrant traffickers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 19:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Umpires Warned Against Harassment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Baseball warned the bickering umpires not to harass each other  
as the infighting over their failed mass resignation plan got 
nastier and more emotional. 
</P>
<P>
	The wife of a union supporter sent an angry letter to another  
umpire's wife saying her husband was a ``Judas'' for betraying his 
fellow umps. And one of the game's most respected umpires broke 
down in tears as he was interviewed on television before Saturday's 
``Game of the Week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to give up my job of 25 years and sit down,''  
said Richie Garcia, one of the 22 umpires whose resignations were 
accepted, effective Sept. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to let people that have been in baseball 15  
years or 10 years or five years or three years take my job. I love 
this game,'' Garcia said on Fox's broadcast, wiping tears from his 
eyes and cutting the interview short. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the umpires who support union head Richie Phillips are  
angry with the 13 who refused to resign and the 14 who withdrew 
their resignations before last Tuesday. The union hoped the threat 
of a mass walkout would force baseball to immediately negotiate a 
labor contract to replace the one that expires Dec. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	AL president Gene Budig and NL president Len Coleman sent a memo  
to umpires warning them of possible discipline. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have received several reports suggesting that umpires may  
have been involved in illegal threats, intimidation or harassment 
of other umpires who may have a different point of view regarding 
the issues raised by the illegal mass resignation plan instigated 
by the Major League Umpires' Association,' said the memo, dated 
July 29. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to be absolutely clear with you on one point -- we will  
not tolerate any threats, intimidation or harassment against any 
umpire. Anyone who is found to have engaged in such conduct will be 
disciplined immediately. Every umpire is entitled to have his own 
view on these issues but we will not allow any umpire to be 
threatened, intimidated or harassed because of his point of view.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A letter from Marcia Montague, wife of NL ump Ed Montague, to  
Denise Hirschbeck, wife of AL ump John Hirschbeck, was an example 
of the kind of anger and emotion that has split the union. 
Phillips' supporters blame Hirschbeck and AL ump Joe Brinkman for 
organizing the opposition group. 
</P>
<P>
	``You must be very proud of your husband for undermining 20  
years of work from an association that has reaped him so many 
benefits,'' wrote Mrs. Montague, whose husband still has his job. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a shame because it would have been a good fight against  
what's wrong in baseball. Maybe we all could have made a difference 
in the fight to restore real leadership to the game. I would have 
liked to see us take on the MLB, the commissioner and the media. 
For promoting the myths that umpires are arrogant, when they are 
actually proud; that they are not accountable, when they always 
have been, to the leagues and to themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	``But we didn't see the Judas in our midst, who sold us out for  
20 pieces of gold. I guess you'll have to live with that. And John, 
every time he walks out on that field. And your kids, when you 
teach them about ethics and morals. And all the other umpires and 
their wives and children who followed John because they believed in 
... what? ... 
</P>
<P>
	``John is an embarrassment to all real umpires and baseball  
because he forgot the quintessential -- baseball is a team sport, 
and he thinks he is bigger than the team. He shamed us all. I can 
say my husband was good for the game -- can you?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hirschbeck did not respond to a telephone message left at his  
home in Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	``I read the letter and I cried,'' Phillips said. ``I cried and  
I don't cry very much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The split of Phillips' supporters and backers has disrupted  
umpires' families, friendship and working relationships. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Reilly, one of the other umpires' on Garcia's crew, opposes  
the union leadership; the two others, Laz Diaz and Brian O'Nora, 
are among 25 umpires hired from the minor leagues who will become 
permanent replacements on Sept. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got three guys that he practically raised that clinged to  
him, like babies to a mother,'' Phillips said. ``Now he doesn't go 
to the ballpark with them, he doesn't eat with them. He considers 
them scabs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dave Phillips, an AL ump in his 29th season, said he didn't  
fault umpires in the other faction but blamed the leadership for a 
negotiating stance that backfired. 
</P>
<P>
	``Richie Phillips has got to resign and go away because he's  
hurt the Major League Umpires Association so much,'' said Dave 
Phillips, who is not related to the union leader. 
</P>
<P>
	``I adamantly and strongly disagree with every bone in my body  
with the direction this leadership advised my union members to 
follow,'' Dave Phillips said. ``Richie Phillips led him into this 
kind of situation. This is like the Jonestown, Koolaid thing. Not 
everybody was going to be that stupid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if there had been threats, Brinkman said:  
</P>
<P>
	``Just a couple of things said in the dressing room, nothing  
serious.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And commenting on Garcia's emotional TV appearance, he said:  
</P>
<P>
	``Richie's got to be hurt, I feel as bad for them as they do  
themselves, these are my friends, but they were just ill advised. I 
know how he feels, I know what he is going through, and I hope 
somehow somebody takes mercy on them.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
