<HEADLINE> Quayle Proposes 30 Percent Tax Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WOODSVILLE, N.H. (AP) -- Former Vice President Dan Quayle  
proposed 30 percent tax cuts and flexible tax-free savings accounts 
Saturday, saying dramatic tax reductions are needed to strengthen 
American families. 
</P>
<P>
	``The American family is overtaxed, and this rate reduction will  
enable parents to keep more of their paycheck, which just might be 
the difference that allows more time with the children, rather than 
more time working,'' he said at a reception in Orford. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, in Woodsville, the Republican presidential hopeful met  
with voters at a restaurant and discussed goals: 
</P>
<P>
	--Strengthening family values. ``I am back on my feet fighting  
for you and your families, and I am not going to back down,'' 
Quayle said. 
</P>
<P>
	--Voluntary term limits in Congress. He said that once elected,  
lawmakers get closer to lobbyists and to Washington, at the expense 
of their constituents. To discourage career politicians, Quayle 
said he would favor cutting free health care and additional 
retirement benefits for lawmakers serving more than 12 years. 
</P>
<P>
	--Enforcing gun laws. ``That will do a lot to deter gun  
violence,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
 *With AP Photos    	
</P>
<P>
	NOVI, Mich. (AP) -- Michigan Democrats voted Saturday to hold  
their presidential caucus March 11. 
</P>
<P>
	They rejected a plea by U.S. Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., to defy  
the national committee and break Iowa and New Hampshire's pride of 
place in the presidential selection process. 
</P>
<P>
	Levin asked about 250 members at the Democratic State Central  
Committee meeting to hold the 2000 caucuses on Feb. 12. National 
party rules ban states other than New Hampshire and Iowa from 
holding their primaries and caucuses before March 6, 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa's party caucuses are expected to be Feb. 7, with the New  
Hampshire primary about a week later. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why should two small states, unrepresentative in their  
character of the American people, determine how the politics of 
this country should be played every four years?'' asked Burke Webb, 
chairman of the Cass County Democrats, speaking in support of 
Levin's cause. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan Democrats asked the national committee for a waiver  
from the March 6 rule but were turned down. If the State Central 
Committee had ignored the rejection, the decision would have 
sacrificed Michigan's seats at the 2000 national convention. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is only one way to win this fight,'' Levin said, ``and  
that is if some state or states have the courage to pick their 
delegates in a way that allows that state to compete ..., and if 
penalized to take that fight to the national convention.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
 *AP Photos NAI101-102    	
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Prominent Indiana Democrats told Tipper Gore  
on Saturday they support her husband's 2000 presidential election 
bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Frank O'Bannon, Attorney General Jeff Modisett and U.S.  
Rep. Julia Carson were among those who endorsed Vice President Al 
Gore at a rally. 
