<P>
 *With AP Photo    	
</P>
<P>
	ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton took her summer-long  
New York ``listening tour'' to an agricultural seminar at Cornell 
University on Saturday and heard upstate farmers' worries. 
</P>
<P>
	Their list was varied: low milk prices, high inheritance taxes,  
subsidized foreign competition, tough rules on manure storage, 
genetic engineering of crops. And the drought. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do eight acres, and it's iffy now how many of those acres  
will make it this year because of the drought,'' Carol Stull, an 
organic vegetable farmer, told the first lady. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the farmers spoke not only about current uncertainties  
but of the future and whether their children would be able to 
follow them into a business where financial risks are growing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Generally, you're not getting sufficient returns to justify  
investing in that business,'' said Mary Beth Holub, a Cornell 
graduate and dairy farmer with 75 cows. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton is considering a run for New York's Senate seat  
being vacated next year by fellow Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan. 
  	   	
</P>
