<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Businesswomen Give Dole a Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- For her 63rd birthday, Elizabeth Dole scooped  
up $200,000 courtesy of a small army of businesswomen angry that 
one of their own -- and the first to seek the presidency -- was not 
faring better in a field of men. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're keeping her in the running,'' declared Bonnie McElveen  
Hunter, the newly political entrepreneur now in charge of building 
Dole's $2 million bankroll. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a Wall Street Journal article late in the winter that  
ticked off Mrs. Hunter just enough to reach for her checkbook for 
the first time in any political race. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was Elizabeth Dole dead last behind someone named Gary  
Bauer,'' Mrs. Hunter recalled about the story ranking the 
presidential candidates' fund-raising fortunes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought to myself, how could a woman who's dedicated her  
life to public service and turned around the Red Cross be behind 
someone I'd never even heard of?'' 
</P>
<P>
	That was in the year's first three months, when Dole, despite a  
heady lead in some polls, drew just $700,000 in contributions. By 
July, she raised $3.5 million and socked $1.8 million in the bank -- 
compared with the $30 million Texas Gov. George W. Bush has on 
hand. 
</P>
<P>
	New York fashion designer Jhane Barnes -- who has not voted since  
her parents pushed her to the polls for Richard Nixon and no longer 
is even registered -- was angered into helping Dole when one of the 
30-year-old women in her studio said the country is not ready for a 
woman president. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was dead in my tracks. How could one of MY employees say  
that to ME? It made me mad,'' Barnes said. ``You create your own 
reality and I want to believe it's possible to be president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Where New Hampshire horserace polls once showed Dole ahead of  
Bush, she now pulls well under 20 percent of the vote in surveys, 
compared with Bush's 40 percent or better. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington lobbyist and Dole fund-raiser Wayne Valis said  
winning has taken a back burner to getting heard. His pitch to 
would-be donors: ``Give Elizabeth a chance, let her make her 
case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether she is the most nominate-able, we'll see. But we'll  
only see if she has the resources to stay in the race,'' Valis 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole owes to women whatever gains she's made and political  
strategists say she must pin her hopes to women as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole, whose support for gun control and dismissal of a  
constitutional amendment banning abortion appears aimed at women, 
wins twice as many women as men in polls. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's high on the wishful-thinking scale that anyone can catch  
up to Bush,'' said pollster Lee Miringoff of the Marist Institute 
for Public Opinion. ``But there is leverage for her being the only 
woman candidate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dole, among homestate contributors in North Carolina for her  
63rd birthday on Thursday, bristled at any notion that her gender 
was her greatest appeal. ``I'm not running because I'm a woman, and 
I don't want people to vote for me because I am a woman,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Her campaign slogan, however, is a wink to the fact that the  
United States has not yet had a woman president. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's make history!'' cry her banners and pamphlets.  
</P>
<P>
	In the first half of this year, women gave Dole 43 percent of  
her big donations, compared with the 25 percent women contribute in 
a typical political campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, three dozen female executives from around the country  
signed up to raise $10,000 apiece or more. 
</P>
<P>
	One of them, Janey Moores, president of BJM &AMP; Associates in  
Lexington, Ky., said she is tapping fellow professional women -- no 
men yet, not even her husband -- on Dole's behalf. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hear from some, 'She will do us proud' and 'Let's get a  
woman in there,''' Moores said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though each of the half-dozen Dole fund raisers interviewed  
professed to like Bush, all expressed an indignance that Dole, a 
two-time Cabinet secretary and former president of the American Red 
Cross, is running so far behind him. 
</P>
<P>
	``If she has not earned a place in upper, upper leadership in  
this country, I don't know who has -- male or female,'' Moores said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Women have never had an opportunity such as we have with  
Elizabeth Dole,'' said Nancy Donovan, owner of Cincinnati's Ames 
Travel Service with $20 million in annual sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's pretty exciting to me to think we can have a woman  
running our country who understands what it means to be a woman in 
the workplace.'' Donovan called first reports last month of Bush's 
cash pile ``a downer'' to her fund-raising efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	But McElveen-Hunter, in a North Carolina drawl rivaling Dole's,  
makes a special pitch to friends who already gave to Bush: ``I've 
never seen a pair of pants with one pocket.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 13:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NAACP President Not Upset by Prank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- As the president of the Cleveland NAACP looked  
on, Indians owner Richard Jacobs donned a makeshift white hood and 
made fun of an upcoming Ku Klux Klan rally. 
</P>
<P>
	George L. Forbes, president of the Cleveland chapter of the  
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, said he 
was not offended by Jacobs' prank, which took place as Jacobs was 
flying a group to the July 13 All-Star Game in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes has been publicly feuding with Mayor Michael R. White  
over the city's plans for a KKK rally in the city scheduled for 
Aug. 21. And as the plane headed for Boston, Jacobs put on the 
white hood as a joke, The Plain Dealer reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He came a third of the way down the plane. He didn't say  
anything. People seemed amused,'' said Plain Dealer editorial page 
director Brent Larkin, who was also on the plane. 
</P>
<P>
	Larkin said Jacobs was carrying a sign that said, ``How do we  
get to the Justice Center?'' -- the planned location for the KKK 
rally. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everyone put it into the context that this was  
something between two people who are very close to one another,'' 
Larkin said. ``As far as I know, everybody got a kick out of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes said Jacobs invited him on the trip as a brief escape  
from the controversy over the rally. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no offense meant. There was no offense taken,''  
Forbes said of Jacobs' actions. ``It was not offensive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Larkin said Forbes and Cleveland Cavaliers President Wayne Embry  
were the only blacks on the flight. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacobs, who announced he was putting the Indians up for sale in  
May, was not available for comment Saturday. Neither Bob DiBiasio, 
Indians vice president of public relations, nor Dennis Lehman, the 
team's executive vice president of business, had a phone number for 
Jacobs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were unaware of the incident. The organization has no  
comment,'' DiBiasio told The Associated Press Saturday at Jacobs 
Field. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Jacobs' company, the Richard E. Jacobs Group,  
settled out of court with two businessmen who claimed their kiosk 
at a Columbus mall owned by the company was evicted because it 
attracted too many black customers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
