<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  US, Mexico Baseball Teams Advance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- It comes down to beating Mexico for a  
spot in the Sydney Olympics for the U.S. baseball team. 
</P>
<P>
	John Patterson pitched 5 2-3 hitless innings Saturday night and  
the United States advanced to the Pan American Games semifinals by 
beating Panama 5-2, leaving the Americans one victory away from 
clinching a trip to the 2000 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States will meet Mexico on Sunday for a trip to  
Sydney. Mexico tripped Nicaragua 5-1 Saturday, joining Canada and 
Cuba in the semifinals. The Americans beat Mexico 5-1 in the 
prelimnaries. 
</P>
<P>
	The gold medal game is Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-5 Patterson, a Double-A pitcher in the Arizona  
Diamondbacks' organization, had not given up a hit when he fumbled 
Earl Agnoly's bunt to mound for an error with two outs in the 
sixth. Audes De Leon followed with a two-run homer to right for 
Panama's first hit. 
</P>
<P>
	He allowed two hits in eight innings.  
</P>
<P>
	The United States scored four times in the third, capped by Jon  
Zuber's two-run double. Craig Paquette homerd to make it 5-0 in the 
fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	Host Canada stayed unbeaten and set up an emotional semifinal  
rematch with Cuba, routing Guatemala 12-2 behind four homers and 
the pitching of Yan LaChapelle. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner of Sunday's semifinal between the Canadians and the  
world champion Cubans also qualifies for the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuba, which lost its final two games in pool play amid rumors of  
impending defections, advanced Saturday by beating the Dominican 
Republic 3-1 as Gabriel Pierre Lazo and Luis Ulacia homered. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very happy and now I have the possibility of playing for  
the gold medal,'' Ulacia said 
</P>
<P>
	Cuban reliever Luis Lazo pitched out of a bases loaded jam in  
the seventh to preserve the victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anybody can win the tournament now,'' Dominican manager Felix  
Fermin said. ``We had confidence we could go farther, but that's 
baseball. Cuba just played better than us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Canada got homers from Jeremy Ware, Ryan Radmanovich, Troy  
Fortin and Andy Stewart to beat Guatemala in a game stopped by the 
10-run mercy rule in the bottom of the seventh when the Canadians 
scored four runs. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada, with five straight wins, beat Cuba won 8-1 in the  
opening round-robin series, a rough game that featured two home 
plate collisions between Canada's Aaron Guiel and Cuban catcher 
Ariel Pestano and brought both teams to the top of their dugouts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can play with anyone and we know we can beat Cuba,'' said  
Radmanovich, who played in the major leagues with Seattle in 1998 
and is now at Triple-A Tacoma. 
</P>
<P>
	``We really wanted to play Cuba rather than the Dominican. ...  
It's een fun having all these guys come from different teams to 
represent their country. Tomorrow will be the biggest game of my 
life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	LaChapelle survived a bases-loaded situation in the second,  
giving up just one one run. Ware hit a two-run homer in the third 
and three batters later, Radmanovich connected for a three-run shot 
to make it 5-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Jorge Gutierrez homered for Guatemala in the sixth.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 20:30:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
