<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Resendiz Charged in 2 More Murders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- The Mexican drifter suspected of killing nine  
people in three states has been indicted on two more capital murder 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Indictments returned Friday allege that Angel Maturino Resendiz  
bludgeoned the Rev. Norman ``Skip'' Sirnic and his wife Karen, both 
47. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sirnics were killed as they slept inside their parsonage in  
Weimar about 80 miles west of Houston. Their bodies were discovered 
May 2. 
</P>
<P>
	Maturino Resendiz already faced five charges that carry possible  
death sentences: two in Texas, two in Illinois and one in Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know that one death sentence is enough,'' said  
prosecutor Joe Fling. ``They all go up on automatic appeal, and 
they probably get overturned more than any other kind of sentence. 
There's something to be said for multiple sentences from multiple 
jurisdictions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A month after the Sirnics' bodies were discovered, the community  
was terrorized again by the similar killing of Josephine Konvicka, 
73. 
</P>
<P>
	Maturino Resendiz, awaiting trial in the beating and stabbing  
death of 39-year-old Dr. Claudia Benton in the Houston area, also 
is suspected of killing Ms. Konvicka. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney Allen Tanner said he was unaware the grand jury  
was considering the indictments. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's interesting that they're doing this now,'' Tanner  
said. When asked to elaborate, he replied, ``It's just 
interesting.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 12:16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Wave Death Toll Climbs to 93 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Guzzling down bottled water under the searing  
midday sun, police Officer Mike Sanders began his shift Friday 
checking to see how senior citizens were faring in the heat. 
</P>
<P>
	Knocking on the door of one high-rise apartment, he got no  
answer. Inside, he found 81-year-old Mary Powls lying on the floor 
of her sweltering home. Her windows were closed, and she had no 
fans or air conditioning. 
</P>
<P>
	The groggy woman said she had fallen and couldn't get help.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a good thing that we came around when we did,'' Sanders  
said. He later checked on her in the hospital, where she was 
admitted in stable condition with a 104-degree temperature. 
</P>
<P>
	As an unrelenting heat wave kept its grip on much of the nation  
-- from the Plains to the East Coast -- Chicago officials deployed 
hundreds of workers on the streets to avoid a repeat of 1995, when 
scorching summer heat was blamed for more than 700 deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	The current heat wave has been linked to at least 94 deaths in  
18 states across the country since July 19. The Midwest has been 
hit hardest, with Missouri logging 29 heat-related deaths, Illinois 
23 and Ohio 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures neared 100 degrees in many cities, and the heat  
index -- a measure of temperature and humidity -- rose past 110 in 
several places. The heat index neared 120 in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	The temperature was 103 at Chicago's Midway Airport, and by  
midday it was 99 in Kansas City, Mo. -- the 15th straight day that 
state had seen temperatures in the 90s. 
</P>
<P>
	The misery was spread all over. It was 106 in Louisville, Ky.,  
one degree short of the city's record, and 104 in Fort Knox. 
Kenosha, Wis., reached 102, and Winona, Minn., reported a high of 
99. Nashville, Tenn., broke a record at 101. 
</P>
<P>
	Little Rock, Ark., registered 102. It's been so bad in central  
Arkansas that Danny Mahan, safety director for a construction 
company there, said workers pouring concrete have been arriving at 
work at about 3 a.m. to avoid laboring in the afternoon heat. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago had no formal heat emergency plan until the death tolls  
started mounting during the 1995 heat wave, when temperatures 
soared as high as 106 degrees, with humidity that made it feel like 
125. 
</P>
<P>
	The city issued an extreme heat warning Friday, sending workers  
door-to-door checking on senior citizens and urging people to take 
advantage of 30 air-conditioned cooling centers. Officials hired 
extra ambulances and sternly warned people to stay inside. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there was ever a day that hot weather threatened the lives  
of people in Chicago, it is today,'' said Fire Commissioner Edward 
Altman, who has been coordinating the city's heat relief efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	At Wrigley Field, ushers sprayed water onto Chicago Cubs  
baseball fans in the bleachers and two players had to leave the 
game because of the heat. Across town, Jimmy Connors also was 
forced to withdraw from a seniors tennis tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	But by late Friday, a glimmer of relief appeared in the form a  
Canada cool front moving into Minnesota and Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures in Minnesota fell into the 70s and even into the  
mid-60s. 
</P>
<P>
	Northern Wisconsin saw severe storms with violent lightning,  
rain and wind gusts of about 50 mph to 70 mph that toppled trees 
and ripped down power lines, the National Weather Service reported. 
Scattered power outages were reported. 
</P>
<P>
	More of the Midwest was expected to get relief by Saturday, with  
thunderstorms expected to help cool things off along the central 
Great Lakes and through the mid-Atlantic states. 
</P>
<P>
	In South Carolina, temperatures were in the 90s for the 14th  
straight day on Friday, with the National Weather Service bureau in 
Raleigh reporting the heat index as high as 110 in some areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, produce farmer Tony Southerland of Wilson's Mills,  
S.C., said he didn't have much to complain about, considering his 
field had been ``blessed with rain'' for most of the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``The heat's tough, but it's July,'' Southerland said. ``You get  
out and load watermelons, and you'll have a new appreciation for 
heat in the sunshine.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 10:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Farm Economy Not All Gloom and Doom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The problems in the agricultural economy would  
seem far removed from John E. Miller's farm in the Arkansas Ozarks. 
Miller is turning out chickens as fast as his buyer, Conagra Inc., 
can take them -- probably 2 million this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a stable business, the chicken business. ... The demand  
has been strong,'' Miller said. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller is not alone.  
</P>
<P>
	Prices for corn, soybeans, wheat and other field crops have  
slumped to lows not seen by farmers in years. But government 
subsidies have softened the impact and much of the agricultural 
economy is relatively healthy, nowhere close to its perilous state 
during the farm crisis of the early 1980s, economists say. 
</P>
<P>
	In its latest economic forecast, the Agriculture Department  
projects net farm income to dip to $43.8 billion this year, down 
slightly from last year and off 3.7 percent of the 
inflation-adjusted average for the 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have some sectors in agriculture where our income and  
revenue have continued to rise in the last couple of years -- 
poultry, dairy, fruits, vegetables, nursery and greenhouse 
products. They just seem to trend upward,'' said Keith Collins, 
USDA's chief economist. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the low commodity prices, federal farm subsidies are  
expected to reach a near-record $16.6 billion this year. That total 
does not include any emergency aid Congress is likely to approve 
this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate is set to debate a farm-economy bailout this week  
that could reach $10 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, the Arkansas poultry farmer, is unlikely to benefit. As  
with most federal farm aid, virtually all of the money would go to 
grain and cotton growers because fruits, vegetables, livestock and 
poultry receive little if any federal subsidies. 
</P>
<P>
	The overall financial position of farmers is relatively sound,  
according to USDA statistics. 
</P>
<P>
	Average farm equity, adjusted for inflation, is up 1 percent  
from 1998 and has risen 50 percent since the mid-1980s, when 
skyrocketing interest rates and huge grain surpluses sent farmland 
values plummeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Farm debt is down 12 percent since 1984 and declined slightly  
from last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't see a 1980s-type crisis'' this year, said Collins.  
</P>
<P>
	The chairman of the Senate Agriculture Committee, Sen. Dick  
Lugar, R-Ind., is trying to slow the rush in Congress to pass a 
large bailout. 
</P>
<P>
	He is sending his colleagues a series of mailings pointing out  
how much the government is already doing for growers. Among other 
things, the government guarantees farmers a minimum return for 
their crops no matter how low prices go. This year those subsidies 
are expected to total $6.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	While conceding that ``emotions are understandably running high  
from areas in our country where farmers are hurting,'' whatever 
Congress does to help them should be based on an ``assessment of 
actual farm income needs,'' Lugar said in one letter. ``Rural 
America deserves no less. Taxpayers expect as much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Democrats are proposing $10 billion in emergency aid, and  
Republicans are working on a package of between $7 billion and $10 
billion. Sen. Tom Harkin, who is leading the Democratic effort, 
says many farmers will go out of business unless they get 
additional help soon. 
</P>
<P>
	``Farm families and rural communities are in the worst economic  
crisis of at least a decade, and perhaps since the Great 
Depression,'' said Harkin, D-Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	The overall economic numbers mask the problems facing many  
farmers who grow grain and cotton. Cash receipts for soybeans are 
expected to fall 17 percent this year, 11 percent for wheat, 10 
percent for cotton, and 9 percent for corn. 
</P>
<P>
	By comparison, cash receipts for broiler chickens, Miller's  
business, are holding steady this year and are up more than 25 
percent over the past five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmland values are down 6 percent in Illinois this year and 3  
percent in Indiana and Iowa, according to the Federal Reserve Bank 
of Chicago. In parts of the region the drop is greater -- 11 percent 
in central Iowa, for example. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Lugar, Congress' most prominent farmer, acknowledges that  
income from his 600-acre corn and soybean operation in Indiana 
dropped 18 percent last year from 1997. He does not expect this 
year to be any better. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem is a worldwide glut of grain.  
</P>
<P>
	The 1996 farm law was supposed to prevent price-depressing  
surpluses of U.S. grain and other crops by scaling back on 
production-based subsidies, but prices fell anyway because of 
strong crops worldwide and economic problems in Asia and Russia. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 18:21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Franciscan Order Birthplace Reopens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ASSISI, Italy (AP) -- The 17th-century church on the site where  
St. Francis of Assisi died reopened Saturday, two years after 
earthquakes crumbled it and other priceless structures across 
central Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighters helped with one of the last repairs before the  
reopening of St. Mary of the Angels: putting a gold-leaf-covered 
statue of the Madonna back atop the basilica. 
</P>
<P>
	``A sign of hope,'' the Rev. Massimo Reschiglian of the  
Franciscan order said of the reopening. Italy's minister of public 
works and other officials attended, and listened to a message sent 
by Pope John Paul II. 
</P>
<P>
	The church, on a plain below Assisi, surrounds a chapel dating  
to the 4th century. The chapel was the first center of the 
Franciscan order; St. Clare was consecrated there, and St. Francis 
died there in 1226. 
</P>
<P>
	Repairs took 10 months.  
</P>
<P>
	Two quakes hit the hill towns of central Italy on Sept. 26,  
1997, killing 10, rendering thousands homeless and damaging an 
estimated 100,000 buildings in Italy's Umbria and Marche regions. 
</P>
<P>
	In Assisi alone, 373 public works projects for earthquake repair  
are under way. Engineers are working on seismic reinforcement as 
they piece together and prop up the buildings, authorities say. 
</P>
<P>
	Work is still under way at the hard-hit upper church of the  
13th-century St. Francis Basilica in Assisi. The lower level 
reopened soon after the quakes. The upper level is expected to 
reopen in 2000, but without -- at least temporarily -- frescoes 
shaken down by the quakes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 18:21:10 </DATE_TIME>
