<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Saints Turn to Computers To Train </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LA CROSSE, Wis. (AP) -- Although the New Orleans Saints' offense  
may have been last in the NFL last season, it's among the first now 
-- at least in the classroom. 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort to boost their ability to pass, catch, run and  
score, the Saints have ditched their playbooks. Instead, they're 
using mice to work the bugs out of their offense, computerizing 
everything from plays to game plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in the business of training people and there's no  
difference in training stockbrokers or salesmen or football 
players,'' said Sean Lundy of Knowledge Inc., a Denver-based 
software development firm. ``This program breaks down what they 
have to learn and presents it in a clear manner that's 
user-friendly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hall of Fame receiver Raymond Berry, a longtime friend of coach  
Mike Ditka and a consultant for Knowledge Inc., tipped Ditka off to 
the program. Lundy said the Saints coach was sold immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	``When Mike Ditka was with the Bears, they were one of the first  
teams to go from film to video,'' Lundy said. ``He's the innovator 
here too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Saints were the first NFL team to convert their playbooks to  
software. This season only the offense is on CDs. Next season the 
team will add defense and special teams. 
</P>
<P>
	The New England Patriots have since computerized their offense,  
and the Dallas Cowboys will use the program for offense, defense 
and special teams next year. 
</P>
<P>
	New Orleans bought 65 laptops for the offensive players and  
coaches. The players' programs are tailored for their specific 
positions, plays, and responsibilities. Players can test 
themselves, to see how much they've learned, and the program charts 
how much time they spend studying. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't know what type of computer literacy the players  
would have,'' Lundy said. ``But it's been very, very high.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The players' fascination with computers was one of the factors  
that sold Ditka. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think this is the wave of the future,'' Ditka said. ``We  
think everybody is going to go with it. The reason we did it is 
it's not easy to get these guys to read, but I think it's easy to 
get them to play video games. That's basically what this is -- a 
video game. But it also teaches the process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For instance, a player draws out his route on a play. If he's  
wrong, the computer shows where he should have gone. 
</P>
<P>
	Players can see both diagrams of plays and how they work, or the  
actual video of the play from a game. 
</P>
<P>
	The program also provides the quarterback calls and even crowd  
noise. In fact, receivers study part of their program with 
earphones to get used to the clamor of noisy games. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is great,'' tight end Cam Cleeland said. ``I can have  
this in front of me at all times. I can take it home. I can use it 
on my television. I can take it with me on the plane on road trips. 
Who needs to open a playbook and flip through pages when I'm one or 
two clicks away from learning?'' 
</P>
<P>
	And unlike a playbook, Lundy pointed out, the computers are  
secure. If one is left behind or stolen, the program is protected. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 18:30:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Superstitious Boggs Nears 3,000 Hits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Wade Boggs eats chicken and  
cheesecake before each game and likes two hot dogs, a bag of 
barbecue potato chips and an iced tea after a night's work. 
</P>
<P>
	He follows a ritual between meals, too.  
</P>
<P>
	The Tampa Bay Devil Rays third baseman might not be able to  
predict exactly when he'll get his 3,000th hit, but he certainly 
won't change his routine in the final days of the quest. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whatever he's done, it's worked for 23 years. So I figure I'm  
not messing with superstitions,'' his wife, Debbie, said. ``I don't 
have any. They're all his.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boggs leaves home at the same time, 1:47 for a 7:05 game; runs  
at 6:47 for a 7:05 game or 7:17 for a 7:35 game; takes 100 ground 
balls during warmups and will try on dozens of batting gloves to 
find a pair that seem right for the night. 
</P>
<P>
	Once the scoreboard operator in Toronto flipped the clock from  
7:16 to 7:18 to try to throw him off. It didn't matter, Boggs ran 
anyway and got two hits. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you try to interrupt my routine, then sorry,'' the  
five-time AL batting champion said. ``If you can't respect that, 
then I feel sorry for the person trying to upset the routine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The superstitions aren't limited to his pregame ritual.  
</P>
<P>
	Boggs steps over the foul line when he sprints on the field to  
play third base and steps on it when he returns to the dugout. He 
never stands on the mound during a pitcher's conference, draws a 
good-luck symbol in the dirt before each plate appearance, and 
changes the gum he's chewing when he doesn't get a hit. 
</P>
<P>
	But don't bother asking him to help compile a list of his  
superstitions. The 12-time All-Star says it would take too long. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why so many? To make the day go by,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	``If I had one or two, I wouldn't have anything to do. So I have  
80 or 100 that I go through during the day, and they fall into 
place. I know exactly what I'm going to do along the way. That 
makes me relax and get into a frame of mind that I need to be in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After going hitless in the first two games of Tampa Bay's  
current six-game road trip, Boggs still needs eight hits to reach 
3,000. Ideally, the Devil Rays would like him to reach the plateau 
during a six-game homestand that begins Aug. 6. 
</P>
<P>
	The 41-year-old third baseman grew up in Tampa, and the chance  
to get the magic hit before family and friends was one of the 
reasons he signed with an expansion team after spending his first 
16 seasons with the Boston Red Sox and New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	He's being chased to the 3,000-hit mark by San Diego's Tony  
Gwynn, who needed nine going into Saturday night's game against 
Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	Barring injuries, they'll be the first players to reach the  
milestone in the same season since Robin Yount did it three weeks 
before George Brett in 1992. They were the fifth pair to get No. 
3,000 in the same season. 
</P>
<P>
	Boggs said it would be fitting if he and Gwynn did it in the  
same year and that it didn't matter who got there first. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our careers have paralleled each other,'' Boggs said.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's not going to be an asterisk at the end of my career  
that says, `Tony Gwynn beat Wade Boggs to 3,000.' If he gets there 
first, more power to him. I just want to get there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn, who broke into the majors shortly after Boggs, said his  
counterpart set the standard for players who make their mark as 
contact hitters. 
</P>
<P>
	The two never considered themselves rivals because they play in  
different leagues. Yet they feel a connection as players who helped 
put ``line-drive hitters on the map'' during a time when most young 
players came into the majors wanting to hit home runs. 
</P>
<P>
	``He came out of the blocks with seven straight 200-hit seasons,  
just rolling along,'' the eight-time NL batting champion said of 
Boggs. ``He was the type of hitter I really wanted to be like.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boggs is especially proud of his ability to remain productive.  
</P>
<P>
	His lifetime batting average of .329 ranks third among major  
leaguers who have played since World War II, behind Ted Williams' 
.344 and Gwynn's .340. Heading into the weekend series in Oakland, 
Boggs was hitting .295 this season. 
</P>
<P>
	His biggest adjustment has been to what he calls a new  
generation of pitchers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guys I used to face in the early to mid-80s have all  
retired. ... Now you're trying to learn guys that are 23, 24, 25 
years old coming up from the minor leagues,'' Boggs said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's sort of like going from the PGA Tour to the Senior Tour.  
Your golf swing remains the same. It's just that the courses 
change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boggs entered the season needing 78 hits to join the other 21  
members of the 3,000 club, and he was determined to have fun. He 
sought advice from Paul Molitor on how to handle the experience and 
says the hype surrounding the chase hasn't been a distraction. 
</P>
<P>
	The Devil Rays, though struggling through another last-place  
season, are enjoying the ride, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was a perfect fit when we were starting up this expansion  
club for two reasons. He could still play the game and we were 
bringing him back home,'' general manager Chuck LaMar said. 
</P>
<P>
	Teammate Bobby Witt is one of the more than 700 pitchers who  
have given up hits to Boggs. He remembers facing him in Boston and 
nearly being hit in the face by a line drive. 
</P>
<P>
	``The next thing I know I was upside down,'' said Witt, who's  
pitched in the majors for 13 seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just watching him hit was amazing. Watching how he was able to  
go out there and get three one night and come back with two the 
next night. He's just a great hitter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	LaMar said it's the result of all Boggs' hard work and  
determination. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's players that are in the Hall of Fame that are more  
gifted. But I'm not sure there's anybody there that has taken the 
game any more seriously and has truly come to the ball park every 
day ready to play.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
