<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Goes Door-to-Door in N.H. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DERRY, N.H. (AP) -- Democrat Bill Bradley went door-to-door in  
three New Hampshire towns Saturday, joining volunteers who spent 
the past week canvassing this key primary state on behalf of his 
presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The former New Jersey senator said the effort was ``massive,  
early and intentional,'' a bow to the independent streak of New 
Hampshire voters. 
</P>
<P>
	His campaign said more than 500 Bradley supporters from 14  
states spent seven days visiting 100,000 front doors in 31 New 
Hampshire cities and towns. 
</P>
<P>
	On doorknobs they hung handbills describing Bradley's career on  
the basketball court and in the Senate, and promising that as 
president he ``will work on the big, unfinished business of 
America'' -- racial equity, health care for all, reducing poverty 
and reforming campaign finances, among other issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Voters showing an interest in learning about the candidate were  
invited to have coffee Saturday morning coffee with Bradley at a 
Manchester restaurant, where a blue Bradley for President banner 
declared, ``He has made the long shot before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason we're (going door-to-door) so early is to show  
respect to the voters of New Hampshire and to invite them into the 
process of running for president,'' Bradley explained. ``I'm trying 
to do this campaign in a different way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A victory in New Hampshire's leadoff primary is critical if  
Bradley is to beat Vice President Al Gore. Bradley said the state 
is a good place to test his low-key, open-ear campaign style. 
</P>
<P>
	But New Hampshire pollster Kelly Myers said ``retail politicking  
is less important than it used to be,'' even in a state known for 
its retail politics. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he said, ``a big canvassing effort at this point in the  
race can be very effective. You can get introduced to voters, you 
can get your platform to them in writing, and you can get your name 
recognition up. For a person like Bill Bradley, that's very 
important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley set the tone for his run when he selected Gina Glantz as  
his campaign manager. She specialized in grass-roots campaigns, and 
her consulting firm helped create Hands Across America, the 1986 
nationwide demonstration in support of the hungry and homeless. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley's campaign Web site includes a ``community involvement''  
section that encourages people to get involved in any of 15 ways, 
from writing to a local newspaper to rounding up votes personally 
in New Hampshire or Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	James Bradfield logged in from Bend, Ore., and was inspired. A  
registered Republican until decided to back Bradley, he flew to New 
Hampshire last week and spent seven days walking door-to-door for 
his candidate of choice. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was sucked in by the Web site,'' he explained, adding that  
he likes Bradley's commitment to campaign finance reform. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure there were a lot of other things I could have done  
this week,'' said Susan Wilson, a Bradley activist who flew in from 
Santa Monica, Calif. ``There's not been somebody who's made me feel 
this way since Bobby Kennedy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders of the New Hampshire volunteers were dubbed ``brigade  
captains.'' Bradfield and others in the state's northern reaches -- 
including the tiny town of Dixville Notch, whose residents cast the 
first votes in the state's primary -- were called the ``road 
warriors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Volunteers said they were encouraged about Bradley's chances.  
</P>
<P>
	``We encountered an awful lot of uncommitted people,'' said Mike  
Dowling of Ocean Grove, N.J., who went door-to-door in Londonderry. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
