<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 10 Die in Plane Crash in Michigan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COTTRELLVILLE TOWNSHIP, Mich. (AP) -- A plane carrying nine  
members of a skydiving group that was holding its annual campout 
crashed shortly after takeoff Saturday, killing all the passengers 
and the pilot, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane, a twin-engine Beech King Air 200, came down less than  
a mile from Marine City Airport at 8:20 a.m. in this township about 
40 miles north of Detroit, said State Police Sgt. Craig Nyeholt. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause wasn't known.  
</P>
<P>
	The pilot of the plane, Paul Myks, was a Spirit Airlines pilot  
who flew DC-9's for the airline, said Gary Cooper, regional 
director of the U.S. Parachuting Association. 
</P>
<P>
	All the skydivers on board were members of the Parahawks, a  
skydiving group that apparently had gathered at the airport for its 
three-day annual pig roast and campout. The event reportedly was to 
end Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	A woman who answered the telephone at the Parahawks skydiving  
center at Marine City Airport refused to discuss the club or the 
crash. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a very extended family,'' said James Relken, the local  
Red Cross chapter director, who was at the crash site counseling 
families of the victims. ``The immediate family may not be here, 
but they're extended family to each other. That's very evident.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Sers, who said he was the brother of one of the victims,  
said the Parahawks jumped weekly. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is where my brother loved to be. This is his passion.  
That's what he loved to do,'' said Sers, who declined to give his 
brother's name. ``If you've got to die doing something, it ought to 
be something you have a passion for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Raymond Wilson said his 22-year-old nephew Roger Engle III had  
made more than 100 jumps and was also an expert at 
parachute-packing. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was out here all the time. He jumped a whole lot. We were  
hoping that he wasn't (on the plane), but his grandpa knew he 
was,'' Wilson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Macomb County Medical Examiner Werner Spitz said the plane,  
which reportedly crashed shortly after takeoff, broke into three 
parts and the victim's bodies were strewn across a 50-yard area of 
wreckage. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Spitz, one body found in the cockpit was not  
wearing a parachute and is believed to be that of the pilot. The 
other nine victims were wearing parachutes, but they never had an 
opportunity to jump, Spitz said. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Franz, who lives near the airport, said he heard the  
plane taking off -- then the engine went dead. A second or two 
later, he said, there was a loud crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Miller, 45, and his son Dustin were sitting in their living  
room when they saw the plane coming toward the airfield. 
</P>
<P>
	``Planes come in and out all the time. But this one was a sharp  
bank that was more than usual. We could see the bottom of the 
plane,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Said Dustin: ``It was coming in awfully fast. I heard a  
crunching sound like a can being crunched. Then the ground shook a 
little and we saw the black smoke and called 911.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 22:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mets Get Taylor for Isringhausen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Mets bolstered the strongest part  
of their team Saturday, acquiring closer Billy Taylor from the 
Oakland Athletics for right-handers Jason Isringhausen and Greg 
McMichael. 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor, 37, was fourth in the AL with 26 saves, but will likely  
join Turk Wendell and Dennis Cook as set-up men for Armando Benitez 
in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets bullpen has been the second stingiest in the majors  
this season and is a major reason why the team was only a half-game 
behind Atlanta in the NL East. 
</P>
<P>
	But the relievers have been overtaxed all season, especially  
since closer John Franco was sidelined four weeks ago with a 
partially torn tendon on the middle finger of his left hand. Franco 
is expected to miss about one more month. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets have gone 126 games without a complete game -- 14 short  
of the major league record held by Anaheim -- and Mets relievers are 
averaging more than 3.2 innings per game. Wendell leads the league 
with 55 appearances, followed by Benitez (53) and Cook (50). 
</P>
<P>
	New York also acquired left-hander Chuck McElroy in a  
five-player deal from Colorado hours before the trading deadline. 
The Mets sent outfielder Brian McRae, reliever Rigo Beltran and 
minor league outfielder Thomas Johnson to the Rockies for McElroy 
and outfielder Darryl Hamilton. 
</P>
<P>
	``We set out to strengthen our bullpen and we certainly did  
that,'' Mets GM Steve Phillips said. 
</P>
<P>
	And in a third deal, the Mets traded minor leaguer Craig  
Paquette to St. Louis for infielder Shawon Dunston. 
</P>
<P>
	Isringhausen, once one of the Mets brightest pitching prospects,  
has been hampered by injuries throughout his career and was sent to 
the bullpen earlier this year. He is 1-3 with a 6.41 ERA this 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We love Isringhausen's arm, period,'' A's general manager  
Billy Beane said. ``We have to find some power arms in the bullpen. 
He can throw 95-97 MPH and it's hard to find that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Isringhausen, 26, went 9-2 with a 2.81 ERA as a rookie in 1995.  
Along with Paul Wilson and Bill Pulsipher, Isringhausen was 
supposed to anchor the Mets' pitching staff for years to come. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, all three have been beset by injury and  
ineffectiveness. Wilson underwent reconstructive surgery on his 
right elbow in March, and Pulsipher was traded to Milwaukee last 
season after reconstructive surgery of his own. 
</P>
<P>
	Isringhausen's once-promising career has been slowed by a  
succession of injuries including a broken wrist in 1997, 
arthroscopic surgery on his right shoulder and elbow in 1996, and 
reconstructive surgery on his right elbow last season. He also 
battled through a 1997 bout with tuberculosis. 
</P>
<P>
	McMichael was 1-1 with a 4.82 ERA in 19 appearances this year.  
</P>
<P>
	This is the second major deal between the two teams in the last  
eight days. On July 23, Oakland sent their ace Kenny Rogers to New 
York for two minor leaguers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Athletics also acquired Kevin Appier from the Royals for  
pitchers Blake Stein, Jeff D'Amico and Brad Rigby. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 17:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Broncos' Jones Is Fashion Statement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREELEY, Colo. (AP) -- He has two Super Bowl rings to go with 70  
suits ranging in color from peach to lime-green, and he's a 
romantic who married his wife on Valentine's Day. 
</P>
<P>
	Denver offensive lineman Tony Jones even has a street named  
after him in Ty Cobb's hometown of Royston, Ga. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one of those things you usually get when you're dead, not  
when you're alive,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones knows what it's like to be both. He died and came back to  
life during seemingly routine elbow surgery four years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had an allergic reaction to some of the medicine they gave  
me and had a heart attack,'' Jones said. ``My heart stopped. They 
tried to shock me, and it didn't work. They gave me adrenaline and 
brought me back. I think it was just God's way of telling me he can 
stop me when he wants.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If someone was looking out for him, Jones has an appropriate way  
of returning the favor as he makes an anonymous living protecting 
quarterbacks and opening holes for MVP running back Terrell Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	The unassuming work was rewarded last season when Davis became  
the fourth back in NFL history to run for 2,000 yards and Jones was 
selected to his first Pro Bowl after 11 seasons with Cleveland, 
Baltimore and Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a huge man, a massive man,'' said Davis, who bought Jones  
and the other linemen golf clubs for their efforts. ``Having him on 
that left side means a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his lack of notoriety, Jones dresses like a 6-foot-5,  
290-pound movie star trying to impress the paparazzi at a Hollywood 
premiere. 
</P>
<P>
	His wardrobe consists of suits for all occasions, including a  
team-spirit ensemble with navy blue pants, a Broncos-orange jacket 
and orange alligator-skin shoes. 
</P>
<P>
	If Crayola makes the color, Jones wears it.  
</P>
<P>
	``I have different colors for different moods,'' he said. ``I  
like to dress flamboyantly because I like a lot of colors. I'm not 
scared to throw on peach or red or lime-green. A lot of big guys 
are, and I'm not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fashion statement has not carried over to other Broncos  
lineman and Jones has long given up trying to turn his teammates 
into a weighty group of Deion Sanders impersonators. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's unique,'' said guard Mark Schlereth. ``He knows none of  
us could pull off the wardrobe that he has. He's the only guy that 
could pull that off.'' 
</P>
<P>
                              *Eagles    	
</P>
<P>
	Quarterback Donovan McNabb, who ended his holdout by signing a  
seven-year, $54 million contract, missed both of the Eagles' 
workouts. 
</P>
<P>
	McNabb's 32-page contract was so long and complicated that by  
the time the NFL let him sign it, it was too late to join his new 
team on the field. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Giants    	
</P>
<P>
	Wide receiver Amani Toomer, whose last-minute touchdown catch  
knocked the Denver Broncos from the undefeated ranks last season, 
signed a four-year, $11.2 million contract with the New York 
Giants. 
</P>
<P>
	The fourth-year player received a $3.5 million signing bonus.  
</P>
<P>
                             *Jaguars    	
</P>
<P>
	The Jaguars signed free-agent linebacker Lonnie Marts to take  
the place of Bryce Paup, who is recovering from a torn pectoral 
muscle. 
</P>
<P>
	Marts, a nine-year veteran, started 15 games with the Tennessee  
Oilers last season. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Bills    	
</P>
<P>
	Wide receiver Andre Reed, the team's only holdout, is expected  
to arrive at camp in time for Sunday night's team meeting. Reed is 
said to be in agreement with the Bills on a contract extension, 
although the team wouldn't comment. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Steelers    	
</P>
<P>
	Running back Jerome Bettis, whose troublesome left knee swelled  
at Friday's practice, said he felt better after a brief running 
session during Saturday's morning practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, center Dermontti Dawson was injured during a pileup during  
the afternoon practice. The preliminary prognosis was a sprained 
medial collateral ligament in his right knee. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Chargers    	
</P>
<P>
	Free safety Darren Perry retired, the day before the Chargers  
were to fly to Australia for their exhibition opener. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Mike Riley said the seven-year veteran knocked on his door  
at 7:30 a.m. and told him he was retiring due to an ailment in his 
right shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Falcons    	
</P>
<P>
	The Falcons learned that running back Gary Downs and rookie  
center Todd McClure both suffered season-ending knee injuries at 
practice a day earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Downs sustained a torn lateral collateral ligament, while  
McClure tore an anterior cruciate ligament. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Patriots    	
</P>
<P>
	Coach Pete Carroll and starting strong safety Lawyer Milloy said  
they've buried the hatchet, one day after the Pro Bowl defensive 
back blasted team management for releasing veteran safety Willie 
Clay. 
</P>
<P>
	Milloy, a fourth-year veteran, apologized for having expressed  
private feelings publicly. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Panthers    	
</P>
<P>
	Wide receiver Rae Carruth, making a comeback from a fractured  
right foot last season that required surgery, has looked very good 
two days into training camp. Carruth has made one impressive catch 
after another in a push to recover from a lost season in which he 
played only two games. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Broncos    	
</P>
<P>
	The Broncos have waived punter Jeff Baker and quarterback Chuck  
Clements, coach Mike Shanahan said. Baker and Clements both joined 
the team as free agents during the offseason. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
