<DOCNO> APW19990731.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 09:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll From Heat Wave at 96 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- As Chicago baked in 100-degree weather, thousands  
of hot and sweaty residents were forced to endure the heat without 
air conditioning or fans, due to sporadic power outages and 
brownouts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every hour they say it's going to be back on. Nothing,'' Anna  
Losada, who lost power in her home, said Friday. ``It's ridiculous. 
We got to pay them every month.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago residents were not the only ones suffering in extreme  
heat. A wide strip of the nation, from the central states to the 
East Coast, baked for another day Friday with some temperatures 
over 100 degrees and a heat index -- the combination of heat and 
humidity -- near 120. 
</P>
<P>
	The current heat wave has been linked to at least 96 deaths  
across the country since July 19. The Midwest has been hardest hit, 
with Missouri logging 29 heat-related deaths, Illinois 23 and 10 in 
Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	The death toll rose from 94 to 96 today.  
</P>
<P>
	In Alabama, Chambers County coroner Dave Collier said today that  
Odell Walker, 84, died Friday at her home in Lafayette, Ala., the 
state's first heat-related death. Ms. Walker had air conditioning 
in her home but had not turned it on, he said. The high temperature 
in the state was 99 degrees on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Also today, the News &AMP; Observer (of Raleigh, N.C.,) reported  
that a migrant farm worker died after collapsing while working last 
week in 98-degree heat. The worker had a body temperature of 108 
degrees when he was brought to Duke University Medical Center. His 
death had not been reported earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Across the country Friday, the heat wave was widespread and  
relentless. In Missouri, several cities recorded the 15th straight 
day of temperatures in the 90s. Nashville set a record high of 101, 
breaking the old mark set in 1954. It was 99 in Chattanooga, Tenn., 
tying the mark set in 1952. In other areas, it was 104 degrees in 
Louisville, Ky., 102 degrees in Kenosha, Wis., and 99 degrees in 
Winona, Minn. 
</P>
<P>
	While some areas were due to get some relief from the heat,  
other cities braced for more of the same over the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	As the temperature peaked at 104 degrees Friday at Chicago's  
Midway Airport, up to 100,000 homes and businesses began feeling 
the electricity -- along with cool stream of air conditioning -- shut 
off. Power companies blamed excessive demand for the outage. Full 
power was not expected to be restored until later today. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had a week of temperatures that were just building up  
every day going toward 100 degrees. We're setting peak demand 
records every day,'' said Chicago's Commonwealth Edison spokesman 
Keith Bromery. ``That's put a real strain on the system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While other states were able to avoid such problems, utilities  
issued warnings asking consumers to cut back on usage to prevent 
possible outages. 
</P>
<P>
	The heat was so bad in central Arkansas that Danny Mahan, safety  
director for a construction company there, said workers pouring 
concrete have been going to work at about 3 a.m. to avoid the 
afternoon heat. He's been encouraging workers to drink plenty of 
water before they hit the streets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the younger guys think they can get a drink when it  
starts heating up,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even pro athletes had trouble playing outdoors. In Chicago,  
Jimmy Connors withdrew from a seniors tennis tournament and two 
Cubs players took themselves out of a baseball game with the New 
York Mets because of the heat. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was ready to quit. I called the trainer and said, `I can't  
take it,''' Chicago Cubs outfielder Sammy Sosa said after the game. 
</P>
<P>
	But the outages were the biggest worry in Chicago Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	``Several high-rise buildings with elderly were (partially)  
evacuated. Some of our cooling centers were down, and our 311 
number was overwhelmed by calls from people who couldn't get 
through to Commonwealth Edison and they wanted to report the 
outages,'' said city spokesman Terry Levin. 
</P>
<P>
	The city also made special efforts to get to the elderly, trying  
to avoid a repeat of the summer of 1995, when more than 700 elderly 
residents died in extreme heat. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago Police Officer Mike Sanders began the day checking to  
see how senior citizens were faring in the heat. He had to rescue 
81-year-old Mary Powls, lying on the floor of her apartment with 
her windows closed, fan off and no air conditioning. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders later checked on her in the hospital, where she was  
admitted in stable condition with a 104-degree temperature. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a good thing that we came around when we did,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Besides the elderly, intense heat can also be daunting for the  
homeless, if they have no shelter from the sun's rays. But in 
Louisville, Ky., which hit 106 on Friday, Bill Tracy has managed to 
find some places to keep cool during the day, such as the library. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like to keep myself dressed well so I can slip into  
places,'' said Tracy, who goes to a shelter at night. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 00:20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shrivers Producing NBC Movie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- Bobby Shriver played the politician when  
asked how he and his mother, Eunice Kennedy Shriver, were getting 
along as producers of the NBC movie ``Mary &AMP; Jesus.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We never fight. ... We've had some lively conversations.  
Father Heet mediated them all and heard confession afterward,'' he 
joked. The Rev. Donald Heet is a consultant on the project. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-hour movie, airing Nov. 14, gives the mother of Christ  
her due as a historically important woman, the Shrivers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think she's a more significant figure than any female in the  
last 2,000 years,'' Mrs. Shriver told the Television Critics 
Association on Friday. ``I think she's had enormous impact all over 
the world ... and she's very timely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Shriver, the sister of President John F. Kennedy, brought  
the idea for ``Mary &AMP; Jesus'' to her son, who has produced TV 
programs and films including Arnold Schwarzenegger's ``True Lies.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 18:16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Giants' Johnson Back After Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- LeShon Johnson had a special reason for  
following Lance Armstrong's victory in the Tour de France last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	It was inspirational story of an athlete who not only overcame  
cancer, but then got back into shape and won cycling's greatest 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson can identify with someone like that.  
</P>
<P>
	Just five months ago, the New York Giants' running back posted  
his victory over cancer. Now the 28-year-old wants his professional 
life back, and he's going through twice-a-days workouts with the 
Giants at the University at Albany to get it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am determined to got out there and show people with the same  
sickness that I had that you can always come back,'' Johnson said 
Saturday. ``Just because I was sick, I didn't throw in the towel 
and say, `Hey, this is it.''' 
</P>
<P>
	That might have been easy with the discovery of his lymphoma  
cancer in May 1998. It came just two months after Johnson had left 
the Arizona Cardinals and signed with the Giants as a free agent. 
</P>
<P>
	While his new teammates were at training camp at this time last  
year, Johnson was preparing to start chemotherapy to treat a 
grapefruit-sized tumor in his chest. Radiation would follow in 
January. 
</P>
<P>
	The chemotherapy was bearable. Johnson even worked out during  
his treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Radiation lasts five or 10 minutes, and after the first one I  
said, `This is easy,''' Johnson said. ``By the third and fourth 
one, I found myself getting tired. It kicked my butt, but I had to 
keep pushing myself to work out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The last radiation treatment came on Jan. 27. Johnson doesn't  
hesitate in recalling the date. On Feb. 21, he was diagnosed as 
cancer free. 
</P>
<P>
	After months of workouts, Johnson reported to camp Thursday at  
212 pounds, four over his playing weight. And with starting 
halfback Gary Brown sidelined with an injury resulting from a 
motorcycle accident last month, Johnson is running with the first 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	He's also looking to write a story as improbable as Armstrong's.  
</P>
<P>
	``Just to see him back on the field after the year he's had,  
it's good,'' Giants coach Jim Fassel said. ``I think he can be an 
inspiration to other people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reading about Armstrong's experiences over the past month also  
helped Johnson prepare for training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stuff like that pushes you to strive a lot harder to reach a  
goal,'' Johnson, a six-year veteran whose best season was in 1996 
when he gained 634 yards on 141 carries. ``He's a great guy to look 
up to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A former bull rider in rodeos, Johnson admitted he's been a  
little fatigued working out in temperatures in the 90-degree range 
the past few days. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm prepared to get beat up on and carry the load 25-30 times  
a game,'' Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Giants aren't going to let that happen right away.  
</P>
<P>
	``After we get through with the preseason, we'll have a better  
indicator,'' offensive coordinator Jim Skipper said. ``It's still a 
little early, but, hey, he's looking the same as he was in Arizona. 
We have to see his endurance.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 18:16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
