<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Superstitious Boggs Nears 3,000 Hits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Before the game, before every  
baseball game, Wade Boggs eats chicken and cheesecake. 
</P>
<P>
	After the game, after every game, he downs two hot dogs, a bag  
of barbecue potato chips and an iced tea. 
</P>
<P>
	Between meals, the 41-year-old Tampa Bay Devil Rays third  
baseman follows a ritual that involves scores of superstitions, and 
he's not about to change it as he zeroes in on his landmark 3,000th 
hit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whatever he's done, it's worked for 23 years. So I figure I'm  
not messing with superstitions,'' says his wife, Debbie. ``I don't 
have any. They're all his.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boggs leaves home at the same time, 1:47 p.m. for a 7:05 game.  
He runs before each game, at 6:47 for a 7:05 start, at 7:17 for a 
7:35 start. He takes exactly 100 ground balls in warmups. He tries 
on dozens of batting gloves to find a pair that seems right for the 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	One time, the scoreboard operator in Toronto advanced the clock  
from 7:16 to 7:18 to try to throw him off his ritual. Boggs ran 
anyway and got two hits. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you try to interrupt my routine, then sorry,'' says the  
12-time All-Star and five-time American League batting champion. 
``If you can't respect that, then I feel sorry for the person 
trying to upset the routine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More parts of the ritual:  
</P>
<P>
	Boggs steps over the foul line when he sprints onto the field  
and steps on it when he returns to the dugout. He never stands on 
the mound during a pitcher's conference. He draws a personal 
good-luck symbol in the dirt before each plate appearance. He 
changes the gum he's chewing when he doesn't get a hit. 
</P>
<P>
	But don't bother asking him to compile a list of his  
superstitions. The 12-time All-Star says it would take too long. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why so many? To make the day go by,'' he says.  
</P>
<P>
	``If I had one or two, I wouldn't have anything to do. So I have  
80 or 100 that I go through during the day, and they fall into 
place. I know exactly what I'm going to do along the way. That 
makes me relax and get into a frame of mind that I need to be in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After going hitless in the first two games of Tampa Bay's  
current six-game road trip, Boggs still needs eight hits to reach 
3,000. Ideally, the Devil Rays would like him to reach the plateau 
during a six-game homestand that begins Aug. 6. 
</P>
<P>
	Boggs grew up in Tampa, and the chance to get No. 3,000 before  
family and friends was one reason he signed with the expansion team 
after spending 16 seasons with the Boston Red Sox and New York 
Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	He's being chased to the 3,000-hit mark by San Diego's Tony  
Gwynn, who still needs nine hits after going 0-for-3 against the 
Houston Astros on Friday and 0-for-3 in the rematch Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Barring injuries, they'll be the first players to reach the  
milestone in the same season since Robin Yount and George Brett did 
it three weeks apart in 1992. Only 21 other players have 3,000 
hits. 
</P>
<P>
	Boggs says it didn't matter who gets there first.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's not going to be an asterisk at the end of my career  
that says, `Tony Gwynn beat Wade Boggs to 3,000.' If he gets there 
first, more power to him. I just want to get there,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	The two never considered themselves rivals because they play in  
different leagues. Yet they feel a connection as players who helped 
put line-drive hitters on the map at a time when most young players 
came into the majors wanting to hit home runs. 
</P>
<P>
	``He came out of the blocks with seven straight 200-hit seasons,  
just rolling along,'' Gwynn, the eight-time National League batting 
champion, says of Boggs. ``He was the type of hitter I really 
wanted to be like.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boggs started the season 78 hits short of the 3,000 milestone,  
and he was determined to have fun. He says the hype surrounding the 
chase hasn't been a distraction. The Devil Rays are enjoying the 
ride, too, despite struggling through another last-place season. 
</P>
<P>
	Teammate Bobby Witt is one of the more than 700 pitchers who  
have given up hits to Boggs. He remembers facing him in Boston and 
nearly being hit in the face by a line drive. 
</P>
<P>
	``The next thing I know I was upside down,'' says Witt, who's  
pitched 13 seasons in the majors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just watching him hit was amazing. Watching how he was able to  
go out there and get three one night and come back with two the 
next night. He's just a great hitter.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 20:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Royals Trade Pitcher Kevin Appier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Kansas City ace Kevin Appier, the  
subject of trade rumors since spring training, was traded Saturday 
night from the Royals to the Oakland Athletics for three young 
pitchers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Royals got right-handers Blake Stein, Jeff D'Amico and Brad  
Rigby for the 31-year-old Appier. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal was announced during the Royals' game at Texas, about  
2 1/2 hours before the midnight EDT trading deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're in a step-on-the-gas mode,'' Appier said. ``They think  
they've got a good thing going and they're trying to improve their 
team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oakland was 3 1/2 games behind Toronto for the wild-card spot. The  
Royals were 42-60 going into Saturday, 20 1/2 games behind AL Central 
leader Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm comfortable with it,'' Appier said. ``I'm glad, but I'm  
not saying that I hate Kansas City or the fans. I'm going to miss 
them and it's not like I'm going to leave the city. We're going to 
to continue to live there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Appier, who missed nearly the entire 1998 season because of  
shoulder problems, was 9-9 with a 4.87 ERA. He was 114-89 with a 
3.46 ERA in a major league career that began with Kansas City in 
1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Rigby, 26, was 3-4 with a 4.33 ERA in 29 relief appearances for  
the Athletics. Stein, 25, was 0-0 with a 16.88 ERA in one start for 
Oakland and D'Amico, 24, was 2-2 with three saves and a 2.81 ERA at 
Triple-A Vancouver. 
</P>
<P>
	``We appreciate Kevin's long and loyal service,'' general  
manager Herk Robinson said. ``However, the Royals organization has 
made a commitment to reducing payroll and taking advantage of 
signing the numerous picks we had in this June's amateur draft.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Athletics made another trade, sending closer Billy Taylor to  
the New York Mets for pitchers Jason Isringhausen and Greg 
McMichael. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted to add to the present and future with every deal we  
did,'' Athletics general manager Billy Beane said. ``Kevin has a 
club option. He's still a solid major league starter. He can throw 
200 innings. Each day with our starters we have the ability to 
throw out there, we have a shot to win anywhere. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kevin has been a No. 1 and he brings a No. 1 mentality.  
There's a lot of value in that,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Appier said his first start for Oakland would come Monday night  
against Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	Recently, Oakland traded pitcher Kenny Rogers to the Mets, and  
also got pitcher Omar Olivares and infielder Randy Velarde from 
Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
	Set to earn $5.8 million next season in the option year of his  
contract, Appier had long been mentioned in trade talks as the 
cash-strapped Royals embarked on a payroll purge. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we made all these deals, we had a grand plan in mind,''  
Beane said. ``One had to fall in order for the other to fall. This 
is a big deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Every time he started during the spring, scouts from at least a  
dozen major league teams were on hand. But he obviously had lost 
velocity and effectiveness and the Royals were not able to make a 
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	After a 10-5 loss to Detroit earlier this month when his record  
dipped to 8-9 and his ERA climbed to 5.00, Appier angrily lashed 
out at management and insisted he wanted to play with a contender. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to have a great chance to do it,'' he said. ``But if  
ownership and (the) general manager, if that's not their goal, then 
hopefully they'll get rid of me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Appier was asked if he believed management's goal was to fashion  
a playoff contender with younger players. 
</P>
<P>
	``To keep and sign them? That remains to be seen,'' he said.  
``If we're going to be a much-improved team, then I'd like to be 
part of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Appier ranks among the Royals' career top 10 in a number of  
pitching categories, including wins, innings, ERA, starts, complete 
games, shutouts and innings. He is the team's all-time leader in 
strikeouts. 
</P>
<P>
	He underwent surgery to repair a torn labrum in his right  
shoulder on March 24, 1998, and at the same time doctors trimmed 
some minimally frayed edges of the rotator cuff tendons and 
discovered a fracture line of cartilage in the shoulder socket. 
</P>
<P>
	He spent most of the season on the disabled list and was called  
up to the Royals in September. He finished with a 1-3 record and a 
7.80 ERA and, on Sept. 18, fanned Cleveland's Jim Thome for career 
strikeout No. 1,367, passing Mark Gubicza on the team's career list 
for No. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	He began to slide in 1997 when he was 9-13 with a 3.40 ERA, his  
first losing record since his rookie season in 1989. His finest 
season may have been 1993 when he was 18-8, finished third in Cy 
Young voting behind Jack McDowell and Randy Johnson and led the AL 
with a 2.56 ERA, becoming the first Royal to do so since Bret 
Saberhagen in 1989. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 18:22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rash of Slayings Stun Atlanta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Two decades after the first bodies were found in  
what became known as the Atlanta child murders, violence has once 
again thrust this city into the national eye. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, during a month of bloodshed, few parts of Atlanta  
have been spared: Shootings have struck in the suburbs, the 
inner-city and even in the wealthy Buckhead district. 
</P>
<P>
	The victims have been white, black, Asian, Christian, Jewish,  
Muslim, middle-class, rich, poor, young, old; they have ranged from 
helpless children to SWAT team officers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just mind-boggling,'' said Georgia Hall, who lives across  
the street from the house where a July 12 murder-suicide left seven 
dead. ``It's almost unbelievable that these tragedies are just 
happening all together. You get to the point where you wonder 
what's next?'' 
</P>
<P>
	That slaying was the worst Atlanta mass killing of the century.  
It held the mark for just 17 days, when it was surpassed by Mark O. 
Barton's shooting spree Thursday in the city's Buckhead commercial 
district. 
</P>
<P>
	In July alone, 23 people -- including three gunmen -- have died in  
mass killings in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	The toll is apparent on Mayor Bill Campbell, who appeared solemn  
as he recounted the most recent tragedy to reporters and asked the 
nation to pray for his city. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are unspeakable tragedies. From Colorado to Atlanta,  
these things occur. We don't know why,'' Campbell said. ``In the 
span of 10 days, two deranged individuals have killed 17, perhaps 
more. I don't know if there's any explanation for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell has been one of the most vocal proponents of gun  
control, filing one of the first lawsuits by cities against the gun 
industry. But much of the state is pro-gun rights and the Georgia 
Legislature passed a law blocking cities from filing such suits. 
Campbell has said he will challenge the state law in court. 
</P>
<P>
	Some think he may have more support because of the recent rash  
of shootings. Among the crimes he can point to: 
</P>
<P>
	-- On May 20, 15-year-old T.J. Solomon opened fire on classmates,  
injuring six at Heritage High School in Conyers, just east of 
Atlanta. None of the injuries were fatal. Solomon faces a hearing 
this month to determine if he will be tried as an adult. 
</P>
<P>
	-- On July 12 in southwest Atlanta, Cyrano Marks fatally shot his  
live-in girlfriend, her sister and four children -- aged 9 to 16 -- 
before killing himself. Family members said Marks was upset over 
his girlfriend's intent to break up with him. 
</P>
<P>
	The only survivor in the house was an 11-year-old Santonio  
Lucas, who hid in a closet for eight hours after being shot in the 
elbow. 
</P>
<P>
	-- On July 23, a police sniper shot and killed gunman Greg Smith  
while he was trying to escape from police by climbing out a 
bathroom window in an Austell home. Officers said they feared 
Smith, who had wounded one officer and killed two, was a threat to 
them and his elderly mother -- still in the house. 
</P>
<P>
	The worst was yet to come.  
</P>
<P>
	Six days later, the same day one of the officers was buried,  
gunfire transformed the tinted office buildings and neatly 
manicured lawns of Buckhead into a field of chaos and violence. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the nine dead in two day-trading offices, 13 were  
injured before Barton, a chemist turned stock trader, fled to an 
Atlanta suburb and shot himself five hours later as police closed 
in. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a tragic year for the metro Atlanta area,'' said Tim  
Brazie, 27, a paramedic who responded to the Buckhead killings and 
the Cobb County police shootings. ``I've never experienced a year 
like this before, not this many tragedies in this short amount of 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The spate of killings comes exactly two decades after a string  
of violence that began in 1979 and left 29 young blacks dead. The 
killings ended in 1981. Wayne B. Williams was convicted in two of 
the deaths, and police blamed him for 22 others. 
</P>
<P>
	City officials are quick to point out that in the current crime  
spree, none of the shootings were connected, and note declining 
crime statistics. Preliminary FBI data showed Atlanta recorded a 
1.6 percent decline in violent crimes from 1997 to 1998. Murders 
dropped by one to 149 last year. 
</P>
<P>
	As of July 29, the city has recorded 91 murders compared to 83  
during the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``These kinds of things, unfortunate as they are, can happen  
anywhere,'' Police Chief Beverly Harvard said. ``It doesn't matter 
where you live, it doesn't really matter where you work. This kind 
of tragedy can happen.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 21:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Canadian Athlete Fails Doping Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- An unidentified Canadian athlete  
failed a drug test at the Pan American Games, the host nation's 
Olympic committee confirmed Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Canadian Olympic Association would not say which sport was  
involved or when the doping infraction occurred. But the Pan 
American Sports Organization notified the COA that a Canadian 
athlete tested positive for a controlled substance. 
</P>
<P>
	PASO's Medical Commission said it will render a decision Sunday  
on whether a doping infraction occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the first positive test at these games.  
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. baseball team moved one victory from a spot in the  
Sydney Olympics when it beat Panama 5-2. If it beats Mexico on 
Sunday -- the squad of minor leaguers already did that last Tuesday 
-- it earns a berth in the 2000 Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is what baseball is all about right now,'' said Craig  
Paquette, who homered for the Americans. ``It's a no-lose 
situation. It's something I've never been a part of. Every game is 
a playoff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	American tennis, softball and soccer players were very stingy,  
and the women's basketball team was anything but, leaving it to the 
men to salvage U.S. pride on the court. 
</P>
<P>
	The medals race is a runaway, with the United States at 172 (69  
gold), followed by Canada with 102 (31 gold) and Cuba with 89 (33 
gold). 
</P>
<P>
	Nobody was more dominating than 18-year-old tennis phenom  
Alexandra Stevenson, who routed Francine Harvey of Antiqua 6-0, 
6-0. It was her first double shutout since she was a junior in high 
school. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevenson, the first woman to make the Wimbledon semifinals as a  
qualifier, has lost two games in four sets. She has spent as much 
time concentrating on collecting pins as on her groundstrokes and 
serve. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm mainly looking for pins from other countries,'' said  
Stevenson, whose opponent asked for her autograph after the match. 
</P>
<P>
	The other U.S. woman in action was Lilia Osterloh, who defeated  
Joelle Schad of the Dominican Republic 6-3, 6-3. 
</P>
<P>
	Cecil Mamiitt beat Simon Ebelyn of Trinidad &AMP; Tobago 6-3, 6-4;  
Bob Bryan was a 6-1, 6-1 winner of Felix Insaurralde of Paraguay; 
and Paul Goldstein downed Jermaine Smith of Jamaica 7-5, 6-0 in 
men's play. 
</P>
<P>
	The women's world champions in softball got their third straight  
shutout as they beat the Netherlands Antilles 7-0 behind the 
three-hit pitching of Lori Harrigan. In the three games, the 
Americans have outscored their opponents 21-0, allowing only four 
hits. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrigan, a left-hander, walked only one and struck out nine.  
</P>
<P>
	``Anytime your pitchers go out and don't allow any runs, you  
have to be happy with their performance,'' coach Ralph Raymond 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheila Douty led an 11-hit U.S. attack with two hits and two  
RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. men were just as strong, winning over the Dominican  
Republic 12-0 in six innings. Doug Middleton struck out 16 of 18 
batters and allowed only one hit. 
</P>
<P>
	A 3-0 victory over Canada gave the U.S. women's soccer squad an  
18-1 scoring edge in the preliminary round and first place in its 
group. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our team totally stepped up,'' Marcia Wallis said.  
</P>
<P>
	Despite a 0-0 tie with weak Uruguay, the American men's soccer  
team also advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	In the middle of those strong victories came a poor performance  
from the women's basketball squad, which sustained its worst Pan 
Ams loss ever, 95-64. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cuban women overwhelmed the United States with quickness,  
slashing drives to the basket and a trapping zone defense. They 
jumped to a 14-3 lead in the first five minutes and the Americans 
never recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were good, but we know we're a lot better defensive team  
than that,'' forward Lynn Pride said. ``We had a lot of breakdowns. 
We usually rely on our help, but it wasn't there tonight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No such problems for the U.S. men's squad of CBA all-stars.  
Sparked by the shot-swatting defense of 7-foot Mikki Moore, they 
rolled past Cuba 89-48 
</P>
<P>
	Carl Thomas led the Americans with 17 points. Moore contributed  
seven points, five rebounds and three blocks and generally 
intimidated any Cuban who thought of shooting near the basket. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the first half, I had some jitters early,'' Moore said. ``I  
got a few blocks and that got my blood flowing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Americans won three out of five boxing matches.  
</P>
<P>
	Bantamweight Gerald Tucker, light heavyweight Joe Pastorello and  
light welterweight Corey Bernard easily moved into the second round 
with lopsided victories. 
</P>
<P>
	Tucker, of Cincinnati, romped to a 24-4 win over Cesar Morales  
of Mexico. Pastorello of Colorado Springs, Colo., was an 11-2 
winner against Francisco Garcia of the Dominican. The referee 
stopped Bernard's bout against round Elkena Saunders of the Bahamas 
in the fourth round. 
</P>
<P>
	Tucker forced a standing-8 count in the first round and then  
eased to the victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had so many butterflies before this bout, and then to top  
things off I was the first bout,'' he said. ``I just felt I had to 
continue what was started.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans also won their first two bouts on Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	The losing U.S. fighters were Ron Siler of Cincinnati, beaten by  
Cuba's Maikros Romero in light flyweight, and lightweight Jason 
Ingwaldson of Henderson, Nev.,who was stopped in the second round 
by Fabricio Nieva of Argentina. 
</P>
<P>
	John Patterson pitched 5 2-3 hitless innings Saturday night and  
allowed two hits in eight innings. The 6-foot-5 Patterson, a 
Double-A pitcher in the Arizona Diamondbacks' organization, had not 
given up a hit when he fumbled Earl Agnoly's bunt to mound for an 
error with two outs in the sixth. Audes De Leon followed with a 
two-run homer to right for Panama's first hit. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuba, which lost its final two baseball games in pool play amid  
rumors of impending defections, beat the Dominican Republic 3-1 as 
Gabriel Pierre Lazo and Luis Ulacia homered. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very happy and now I have the possibility of playing for  
the gold medal,'' Ulacia said. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada got homers from Jeremy Ware, Ryan Radmanovich, Troy  
Fortin and Andy Stewart to beat Guatemala 12-2 in a game stopped by 
the 10-run mercy rule in the bottom of the seventh when the 
Canadians scored four runs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 12:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Clark Not Ousted for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is denying that Army Gen.  
Wesley Clark's prosecution of the war in Yugoslavia had anything to 
do with his removal as NATO's supreme commander. Any suggestion to 
the contrary, Clinton said, is ``wrong. Absolutely wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the Pentagon confirmed reports this month that Clark would  
leave his NATO job next May, two months ahead of schedule, it was 
widely reported that he was being pushed aside. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm disturbed about the way (Clark's departure) became  
public,'' Clinton told reporters Friday, during a visit to Bosnia. 
``It opens the way to an inference that is absolutely false.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon and Clinton administration officials explained they  
were acting under legal constraints to allow for the appointment to 
the NATO post of Air Force Gen. Joseph Ralston, now vice chairman 
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff. By law, Ralston must get another 
four-star position within 60 days of leaving that job or retire. 
</P>
<P>
	Many NATO commanders have been offered an additional year in the  
job, and speculation mounted about tensions between Clark and his 
superiors. 
</P>
<P>
	In Bosnia, Clinton repeated the explanation about the necessity  
for Clark to leave the NATO job two months early to make room for 
Ralston. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any inference that it amounts to early retirement or  
dissatisfaction with his service is wrong. Absolutely wrong,'' 
Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the change is being made because ``there is a need to  
get an equally strong person to come in behind him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``That's all this is about,'' Clinton said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 21:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Canadian Athlete Fails Doping Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
