</P>
<P>
	The other U.S. woman in action was Lilia Osterloh, who defeated  
Joelle Schad of the Dominican Republic 6-3, 6-3. 
</P>
<P>
	Cecil Mamiitt beat Simon Ebelyn of Trinidad &AMP; Tobago 6-3, 6-4;  
Bob Bryan was a 6-1, 6-1 winner of Felix Insaurralde of Paraguay; 
and Paul Goldstein downed Jermaine Smith of Jamaica 7-5, 6-0 in 
men's play. 
</P>
<P>
	The women's world champions in softball got their third straight  
shutout as they beat the Netherlands Antilles 7-0 behind the 
three-hit pitching of Lori Harrigan. In the three games, the 
Americans have outscored their opponents 21-0, allowing only four 
hits. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrigan, a left-hander, walked only one and struck out nine.  
</P>
<P>
	``Anytime your pitchers go out and don't allow any runs, you  
have to be happy with their performance,'' coach Ralph Raymond 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheila Douty led an 11-hit U.S. attack with two hits and two  
RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. men were just as strong, winning over the Dominican  
Republic 12-0 in six innings. Doug Middleton struck out 16 of 18 
batters and allowed only one hit. 
</P>
<P>
	A 3-0 victory over Canada gave the U.S. women's soccer squad an  
18-1 scoring edge in the preliminary round and first place in its 
group. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our team totally stepped up,'' Marcia Wallis said.  
</P>
<P>
	Despite a 0-0 tie with weak Uruguay, the American men's soccer  
team also advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	In the middle of those strong victories came a poor performance  
from the women's basketball squad, which sustained its worst Pan 
Ams loss ever, 95-64. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cuban women overwhelmed the United States with quickness,  
slashing drives to the basket and a trapping zone defense. They 
jumped to a 14-3 lead in the first five minutes and the Americans 
never recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were good, but we know we're a lot better defensive team  
than that,'' forward Lynn Pride said. ``We had a lot of breakdowns. 
We usually rely on our help, but it wasn't there tonight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No such problems for the U.S. men's squad of CBA all-stars.  
Sparked by the shot-swatting defense of 7-foot Mikki Moore, they 
rolled past Cuba 89-48 
</P>
<P>
	Carl Thomas led the Americans with 17 points. Moore contributed  
seven points, five rebounds and three blocks and generally 
intimidated any Cuban who thought of shooting near the basket. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the first half, I had some jitters early,'' Moore said. ``I  
got a few blocks and that got my blood flowing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Americans won three out of five boxing matches.  
</P>
<P>
	Bantamweight Gerald Tucker, light heavyweight Joe Pastorello and  
light welterweight Corey Bernard easily moved into the second round 
with lopsided victories. 
</P>
<P>
	Tucker, of Cincinnati, romped to a 24-4 win over Cesar Morales  
of Mexico. Pastorello of Colorado Springs, Colo., was an 11-2 
winner against Francisco Garcia of the Dominican. The referee 
stopped Bernard's bout against round Elkena Saunders of the Bahamas 
in the fourth round. 
</P>
<P>
	Tucker forced a standing-8 count in the first round and then  
eased to the victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had so many butterflies before this bout, and then to top  
things off I was the first bout,'' he said. ``I just felt I had to 
continue what was started.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans also won their first two bouts on Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	The losing U.S. fighters were Ron Siler of Cincinnati, beaten by  
Cuba's Maikros Romero in light flyweight, and lightweight Jason 
Ingwaldson of Henderson, Nev.,who was stopped in the second round 
by Fabricio Nieva of Argentina. 
</P>
<P>
	John Patterson pitched 5 2-3 hitless innings Saturday night and  
allowed two hits in eight innings. The 6-foot-5 Patterson, a 
Double-A pitcher in the Arizona Diamondbacks' organization, had not 
given up a hit when he fumbled Earl Agnoly's bunt to mound for an 
error with two outs in the sixth. Audes De Leon followed with a 
two-run homer to right for Panama's first hit. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuba, which lost its final two baseball games in pool play amid  
rumors of impending defections, beat the Dominican Republic 3-1 as 
Gabriel Pierre Lazo and Luis Ulacia homered. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very happy and now I have the possibility of playing for  
the gold medal,'' Ulacia said. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada got homers from Jeremy Ware, Ryan Radmanovich, Troy  
Fortin and Andy Stewart to beat Guatemala 12-2 in a game stopped by 
the 10-run mercy rule in the bottom of the seventh when the 
Canadians scored four runs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990731.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 17:30:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rash of Slayings Stun Atlanta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Two decades after the first bodies were found in  
what became known as the Atlanta child murders, violence has once 
again thrust this city into the national eye. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, during a month of bloodshed, few parts of Atlanta  
have been spared: Shootings have struck in the suburbs, the 
inner-city and even in the wealthy Buckhead district. 
</P>
<P>
	The victims have been white, black, Asian, Christian, Jewish,  
Muslim, middle-class, rich, poor, young, old; they have ranged from 
helpless children to SWAT team officers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just mind-boggling,'' said Georgia Hall, who lives across  
the street from the house where a July 12 murder-suicide left seven 
dead. ``It's almost unbelievable that these tragedies are just 
happening all together. You get to the point where you wonder 
what's next?'' 
</P>
<P>
	That slaying was the worst Atlanta mass killing of the century.  
It held the mark for just 17 days, when it was surpassed by Mark O. 
Barton's shooting spree Thursday in the city's Buckhead commercial 
district. 
</P>
<P>
	In July alone, 23 people -- including three gunmen -- have died in  
mass killings in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	The toll is apparent on Mayor Bill Campbell, who appeared solemn  
as he recounted the most recent tragedy to reporters and asked the 
nation to pray for his city. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are unspeakable tragedies. From Colorado to Atlanta,  
these things occur. We don't know why,'' Campbell said. ``In the 
span of 10 days, two deranged individuals have killed 17, perhaps 
more. I don't know if there's any explanation for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell has been one of the most vocal proponents of gun  
control, filing one of the first lawsuits by cities against the gun 
industry. But much of the state is pro-gun rights and the Georgia 
Legislature passed a law blocking cities from filing such suits. 
Campbell has said he will challenge the state law in court. 
</P>
<P>
	Some think he may have more support because of the recent rash  
of shootings. Among the crimes he can point to: 
</P>
<P>
	-- On May 20, 15-year-old T.J. Solomon opened fire on classmates,  
injuring six at Heritage High School in Conyers, just east of 
Atlanta. None of the injuries were fatal. Solomon faces a hearing 
this month to determine if he will be tried as an adult. 
</P>
<P>
	-- On July 12 in southwest Atlanta, Cyrano Marks fatally shot his  
live-in girlfriend, her sister and four children -- aged 9 to 16 -- 
before killing himself. Family members said Marks was upset over 
his girlfriend's intent to break up with him. 
</P>
<P>
	The only survivor in the house was an 11-year-old Santonio  
Lucas, who hid in a closet for eight hours after being shot in the 
elbow. 
</P>
<P>
	-- On July 23, a police sniper shot and killed gunman Greg Smith  
while he was trying to escape from police by climbing out a 
bathroom window in an Austell home. Officers said they feared 
Smith, who had wounded one officer and killed two, was a threat to 
them and his elderly mother -- still in the house. 
</P>
<P>
	The worst was yet to come.  
</P>
<P>
	Six days later, the same day one of the officers was buried,  
gunfire transformed the tinted office buildings and neatly 
manicured lawns of Buckhead into a field of chaos and violence. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the nine dead in two day-trading offices, 13 were  
injured before Barton, a chemist turned stock trader, fled to an 
Atlanta suburb and shot himself five hours later as police closed 
in. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a tragic year for the metro Atlanta area,'' said Tim  
Brazie, 27, a paramedic who responded to the Buckhead killings and 
the Cobb County police shootings. ``I've never experienced a year 
like this before, not this many tragedies in this short amount of 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The spate of killings comes exactly two decades after a string  
of violence that began in 1979 and left 29 young blacks dead. The 
killings ended in 1981. Wayne B. Williams was convicted in two of 
the deaths, and police blamed him for 22 others. 
</P>
<P>
	City officials are quick to point out that in the current crime  
spree, none of the shootings were connected, and note declining 
crime statistics. Preliminary FBI data showed Atlanta recorded a 
1.6 percent decline in violent crimes from 1997 to 1998. Murders 
dropped by one to 149 last year. 
</P>
<P>
	As of July 29, the city has recorded 91 murders compared to 83  
during the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``These kinds of things, unfortunate as they are, can happen  
anywhere,'' Police Chief Beverly Harvard said. ``It doesn't matter 
where you live, it doesn't really matter where you work. This kind 
of tragedy can happen.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
